{"type":"tool_execution_end","toolCallId":"ytnPFq86t","toolName":"mcp","result":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex09-20260630071703\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 885915\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex09-20260630071703\",\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"case\":{\"evidence_standard\":\"Preponderance of the evidence.\",\"member\":{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"model\":\"openrouter://mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5\",\"persona_filename\":\"personas/generic.md\"},\"opportunity\":{\"allowed_tools\":[\"submit_council_vote\"],\"id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"may_pass\":false,\"objective\":\"council vote by C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"role\":\"council\"},\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"proposition\":\"Between market creation on April 20, 2026, and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\",\"record\":{\"arguments\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff's case is strongest where it stays tied to the rule and the source chain. The proposition is not whether a child was born, and not whether every viral repost was accurate. It is whether Clavicular made a credible announcement, within the market window, that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\\n\\nThe official market evidence establishes the governing frame. The packet market page and the newly submitted official Polymarket/Gamma capture show the same rule: Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy; only credible announcements count; jokes do not; statements from Clavicular or representatives are the resolution source, with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting also permitted. The official source also shows the market was proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes again, disputed again, and finally resolved Yes. The Gamma extract fixes the market ID, condition ID, outcomes [Yes, No], outcomePrices [1,0], and resolver/closed-time fields. That is not mere trader gossip. It is the official resolution mechanism applying the very rule before this council.\\n\\nThe best explanation for that official Yes result appears in the case packet's secondary-reporting file. Forbes identified the dispute as being over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That description matters because it directly tracks the rule's central question: a statement by the covered person about having gotten a partner pregnant. Forbes also reported that the disagreement was binary: the market description and platform clarification were said to point No while the price pointed Yes, and the oracle had not closed the gap after two dispute rounds. The subsequent official record now shows the gap closed at Yes.\\n\\nThat sequence is plaintiff's preponderance case. The council can reasonably infer that the UMA/Polymarket final Yes did not arise from a vacuum. It followed a disputed process on a high-volume market whose rule allowed either the speaker's statements or a definitive credible-media consensus. The admitted record contains a credible financial-news account saying the dispute centered on a reported statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, and an official source showing the final resolver accepted Yes. On preponderance, those combined facts make a qualifying announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe defense is right that this proof has a missing primary artifact. The original livestream/VOD/transcript is not in the record. Nor is the full Polymarket clarification or transaction-level UMA voter record. The plaintiff does not ask the council to pretend otherwise. Those gaps reduce weight and make this a circumstantial/source-chain case, not a clean direct-video case.\\n\\nBut the gaps do not erase the official resolution and corroborating media account. The rule itself permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a preserved VOD is not automatically fatal. What matters is whether the admitted record, as a whole, makes the qualifying announcement more probable than the competing account that all of this was only a joke, contest, or rumor. The Forbes packet capture is the clearest pro-Yes secondary source; the official Polymarket/Gamma capture is the clearest official outcome source.\\n\\nThe plaintiff also submitted the Times of India fact-check because the council should see the strongest adverse source. It says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular, and it treats the viral claim as likely false or out of context. The live Polymarket context also cuts both ways: it describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama stunt, while acknowledging debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend pregnancy. That evidence undercuts any claim that every viral pregnancy story was credible.\\n\\nStill, TOI is not a primary record either. It is a fact-check of the rumor cycle, not the market-resolution record. It does not disprove that Clavicular made a qualifying announcement later accepted by the resolver or reflected in Forbes's account. It shows why the council should discount unsupported reposts and distinguish future-oriented fatherhood talk from an announcement of an existing pregnancy. Plaintiff's position survives that distinction because the favorable Forbes account is about a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, while the official resolver ultimately paid Yes under the same credibility standard.\\n\\nSo the plaintiff asks the council to give controlling weight to the official rule-and-resolution evidence, substantial corroborating weight to the Forbes secondary-reporting capture, and appropriate but not dispositive weight to the adverse TOI fact-check. The record is imperfect, but preponderance does not require certainty or medical confirmation. It requires the better answer. Here, the better answer is that the market's final Yes reflected a credible announcement or qualifying credible-media consensus that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy within the covered window.\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s case depends on converting a market result into proof of the underlying fact. The record does not support that conversion.\\n\\nThe rule requires a credible announcement that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. The official market evidence proves the wording, timing, dispute sequence, and final Yes outcome. It does not prove what Clavicular actually said. The packet’s official-source and primary-evidence files say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved and that the fact question remains dependent on locating the underlying stream, clip, transcript, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s new Polymarket/Gamma capture adds official details, but the added context cuts against plaintiff’s theory. It describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, a fertility-stack reveal, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama proposal involving 500 contestants. It separately describes “debunked rumors” of a girlfriend’s pregnancy after ten days. Those are not admissions that he and a partner were already expecting a baby. They are future intent, stunt framing, and rumor framing.\\n\\nThe strongest pro-Yes item is the Forbes excerpt in the secondary-reporting packet saying the dispute concerned a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But in this record Forbes is a summarized secondary account in an article about an oracle dispute, not the underlying video, transcript, source post, or representative statement. The same Forbes excerpt also reported that the market description and platform clarification said No while price said Yes, and that traders alleged the oracle had become a disinformation engine. That is not a clean source chain; it is a warning that market mechanics and trader incentives may have overtaken source proof.\\n\\nThe adverse evidence is more specific about the missing link. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, the actual preserved quote was future-oriented pregnancy-contest language, and the viral claim was false and likely came from jokes, out-of-context clips, and his content style. The secondary-reporting packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries match that: “I must have children,” “I must get children today,” and “I will be a dad in the next few months” were treated as a controversial proposal or stunt, not confirmation of an existing partner pregnancy.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a VOD is not automatically fatal. True, but the record does not show a definitive consensus. It shows conflict: Forbes characterizes the dispute one way; Times of India expressly debunks the girlfriend-pregnancy claim; Hindustan Times and Express Tribune frame the remarks as a contest/stunt; the packet says no primary source or Domahhhh thread text was located. A single favorable secondary characterization plus a final market resolution is not a definitive media consensus, especially where admitted adverse reporting directly denies confirmation.\\n\\nNor should the council give controlling weight to the final Yes state. The official resolver result proves that the market was resolved Yes. It does not reveal the evidence considered, the voters’ rationale, the proposer/disputer record, or whether the resolution rested on the same viral rumor now debunked in the record. The unresolved-gaps file expressly notes the missing UMA records and the missing Polymarket clarification Forbes said pointed No.\\n\\nOn preponderance, the better-supported finding is not that a qualifying announcement happened. It is that there was a viral controversy after market creation, built from future fatherhood talk, a pregnancy-contest stunt, social-media rumors, and a disputed market process that ultimately resolved Yes without preserving the basis. The proposition asks for a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy. The current record proves the controversy and the market result, but it does not prove that announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe defense therefore asks the council to find the proposition not proven on this record.\"}],\"closings\":[{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff does not ask you to decide that every viral post was true, or that the record proves the private medical fact of pregnancy. The proposition is narrower: whether Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the covered window.\\n\\nThe record proves the rule, the timing, and the official resolution. The market text required a credible announcement, excluded jokes, and allowed not only statements from Clavicular or representatives but also a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. The official Polymarket/Gamma evidence then shows proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes, disputed again, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0]. That is not a mere price chart. It is the official resolution process applying the same rule now before this council.\\n\\nThe record also contains the affirmative source-chain link. The secondary-reporting packet preserves Forbes's characterization that the dispute was over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is the key phrase in this case. It is not simply a desire to have children someday. It is a reported statement about having gotten a girl pregnant, which maps directly to the rule's pregnancy-announcement requirement. The final Yes resolution then confirms that the official process ultimately credited the Yes side despite disputes.\\n\\nThe defense's best point is real: the original VOD, transcript, Polymarket clarification, and UMA voter rationale are not in the record. That means the plaintiff's case is not direct-video proof. But preponderance does not demand perfect custody or certainty. It asks which inference is better supported by the admitted record.\\n\\nThe adverse record does not carry the defense over that line. The Times of India capture and the live Polymarket context warn against unsupported girlfriend-rumor reposts, out-of-context clips, future fatherhood talk, and stunt framing. Plaintiff accepts that warning. Those materials show why jokes and rumors should be discounted. They do not establish that the official resolver accepted a joke, and they do not erase Forbes's account of a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. They are secondary reports too; they are not the missing primary video.\\n\\nThe defense's theory requires a larger inference than plaintiff's. It asks you to conclude that, after two disputes, the official final Yes likely rested on nothing more than a noncredible rumor or stunt, even though the rule expressly excluded such material and even though Forbes described the dispute in terms of a pregnancy statement. That is possible, but on this record it is not the more probable account.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's account fits all of the admitted pieces: the rule allowed a credible announcement or credible-media consensus; Forbes reported the relevant announcement framing; the market underwent contested resolution; and the final official state paid Yes. The conflicting adverse reporting explains why the case was disputed and why the source chain is imperfect. It does not make No more likely than Yes.\\n\\nFor that reason, under the preponderance standard, the council should find that the proposition is proven.\"},{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the record leaves this case short of preponderance.\\n\\nThe plaintiff is right about one thing: the proposition is not whether a child was born or whether a pregnancy was medically true. The question is whether Clavicular made a credible qualifying announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. But the record still has to prove that announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe official market evidence proves the rule, the dates, the dispute sequence, and the final Yes state. It does not prove the underlying source. The case-packet official-source and primary-evidence files expressly say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved. The unresolved-gaps file identifies the same missing pieces: original livestream clip, VOD, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, and UMA proposer/disputer/voter records.\\n\\nThat matters because plaintiff’s case turns on a bridge it never fully builds. The bridge is one Forbes characterization that the dispute involved a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, plus the final Yes resolution. But the record does not preserve Forbes’s underlying source chain. And the same secondary-reporting packet records that Forbes described the market description and platform clarification as saying No, while price said Yes, and linked criticism of the oracle process. That is not a clean, independent confirmation of a qualifying announcement.\\n\\nThe contrary evidence is not just noise. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, and it identifies the actual preserved quote as future-oriented pregnancy-contest language. The packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries likewise frame the remarks as a contest or stunt: wanting children, needing children today, and being a dad in the next few months. Plaintiff’s own Polymarket/Gamma capture describes trader consensus as driven by public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, a dating-show/baby-mama stunt, and debunked girlfriend-pregnancy rumors. Those facts fit a rumor and stunt cycle at least as well as they fit a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. It does. But this record is not a consensus. It is a conflict: one favorable Forbes phrasing, adverse fact-checking, multiple contest/stunt accounts, and admitted missing source-chain material. A definitive consensus cannot be inferred from divided secondary reporting.\\n\\nPlaintiff also says the official Yes after disputes is unusually probative. It has some weight, but it cannot carry the burden by itself. The record does not show what the resolver considered or why it resolved Yes. Without the UMA rationale, source material, or platform clarification, final Yes is at risk of circular reasoning: using the market’s outcome to prove the fact that the market outcome was supposed to decide.\\n\\nThe defense is not asking the council to find that no rumor existed, or that no one ever thought Clavicular might make such an announcement. The defense is asking the council to apply the actual proposition and the preponderance standard. On this record, a qualifying credible announcement is not more likely than a nonqualifying mix of future fatherhood talk, a provocative contest proposal, out-of-context clips, and debunked viral claims.\\n\\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition not proven.\"}],\"evidence\":[{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407\",\"size_bytes\":1254,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"04/045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:34Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"size_bytes\":2189,\"source_description\":\"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.\",\"source_url\":\"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\",\"storage_name\":\"55/5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068\",\"size_bytes\":4343,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"79/795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"official-source-record.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0\",\"size_bytes\":1851,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"a7/a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"official-source-record.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"market-page.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5\",\"size_bytes\":2778,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"d1/d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"market-page.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:11Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"size_bytes\":3638,\"source_description\":\"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.\",\"source_url\":\"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\",\"storage_name\":\"f0/f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"primary-evidence.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94\",\"size_bytes\":1589,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"f8/f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"primary-evidence.txt\"}],\"exhibits\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"label\":\"PX-1 Market page packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\\n\\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRule text:\\n\\n\\u003e This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\\n\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\\n\\nEvent:\\n\\n- event id: 400878\\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: true\\n- event closed: true\\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\\n\\nMarket:\\n\\n- market id: 2037907\\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\\n- market closed: true\\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"PX-2 Official source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\n## Polymarket source\\n\\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\n\\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\\n\\n## Clavicular or representative statements\\n\\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\\n\\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\\n\\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\\n\\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\\n\\n## UMA / oracle source\\n\\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"PX-3 Secondary reporting packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"PX-4 Official Polymarket/Gamma merits capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"PX-5 Times of India adverse fact-check capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"PX-6 Record gaps packet file\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"label\":\"DX-1 Market rule and initial final-outcome packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\\n\\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRule text:\\n\\n\\u003e This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\\n\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\\n\\nEvent:\\n\\n- event id: 400878\\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: true\\n- event closed: true\\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\\n\\nMarket:\\n\\n- market id: 2037907\\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\\n- market closed: true\\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"DX-2 Official-source packet record showing missing primary statement and UMA detail\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\n## Polymarket source\\n\\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\n\\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\\n\\n## Clavicular or representative statements\\n\\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\\n\\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\\n\\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\\n\\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\\n\\n## UMA / oracle source\\n\\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence\",\"label\":\"DX-3 Primary-evidence packet assessment of missing underlying proof\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Primary evidence\\n\\n## Preserved primary/platform evidence\\n\\n- Polymarket market page: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Polymarket Gamma API event record: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Captured files: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt; source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json; source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\nThe official market rule requires a credible announcement by Clavicular that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy during the specified window.\\n\\n## Potential primary-source leads not locally preserved\\n\\n- Clavicular's Kick page or VODs: https://kick.com/clavicular/videos, referenced by Hindustan Times.\\n- Domahhhh's April 30 X thread about the oracle dispute: https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218, referenced by Forbes.\\n- JexTrade's April 29 X post about a large No buy, referenced by Forbes.\\n- @holy_moses7 posts claiming the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” referenced by Forbes.\\n- The viral Kick Champ post that Times of India says claimed Clavicular was “expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days ago.” The exact source URL was not captured.\\n\\n## Preliminary source assessment\\n\\nThe preserved primary evidence proves the contract wording and the platform's final Yes state. It does not itself prove that a qualifying credible announcement occurred. The fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"DX-4 Secondary-reporting conflict and adverse context\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"DX-5 Unresolved record gaps\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"DX-6 Plaintiff Polymarket/Gamma capture, including context about vows, stunt, and debunked rumors\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"DX-7 Plaintiff-submitted Times of India adverse fact-check\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"DX-S1 TOI fact-check on no confirming video or Clavicular statement\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"DX-S2 Conflicting secondary reporting and contest/stunt framing\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"DX-S3 Missing original statement, platform clarification, and UMA records\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"DX-S4 Official Polymarket/Gamma capture with market context\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"}],\"openings\":[{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, this case is about a narrow event definition, not about proving the private fact of a pregnancy to medical certainty. The proposition asks whether, after the April 20, 2026 market creation and before the stated deadline, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. Under the preponderance standard, the question is whether the better-supported reading of the available source chain is that a qualifying announcement occurred.\\n\\nThe present case packet already fixes the governing rule and the official market posture. The Polymarket page record states that the market resolves Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy, that only credible announcements qualify, that jokes do not suffice, and that statements from Clavicular or his representatives are the primary resolution source while a definitive consensus of credible media may also be considered. The same official-source packet records the platform/API state: the market went through proposed/disputed sequences and ultimately shows a final Yes outcome.\\n\\nThat matters, but it is not the whole case. A final Yes state is strong circumstantial and procedural evidence that the market's resolver accepted the event as satisfied, but by itself it does not show the exact words, tone, context, or credibility of the underlying announcement. The plaintiff's burden is therefore to connect that official Yes state to the source material that caused it.\\n\\nThe packet points to that connection. Forbes reported the dispute as turning on what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. Other reports described livestream remarks about wanting children or becoming a dad soon, and several sources frame the incident as a viral controversy. Those reports explain why the market moved and why the oracle dispute arose. They support the plaintiff's theory that there was, at minimum, a public announcement or reported announcement that the market treated as sufficient.\\n\\nThe defense will stress the same record's weaknesses. The packet does not yet preserve the original livestream clip, VOD, full transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification mentioned by Forbes, or UMA transaction-level record. The Times of India fact-check says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular; other reporting characterizes the comments as a contest, stunt, joke, or out-of-context viral content. Those are real weight issues because the rule expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes.\\n\\nSo the decisive factual questions are these: first, what exactly did Clavicular say, and was it about an existing partner pregnancy rather than a future desire, stunt, or contest? Second, did the statement occur after market creation? Third, did Clavicular or a representative make it, or did credible media reach the definitive consensus allowed by the rules? Fourth, does the Polymarket/UMA Yes resolution rest on that source chain or on speculation and trader pressure?\\n\\nThe plaintiff expects the later evidentiary phase to focus on the primary artifacts the packet identifies: the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, the Polymarket clarification, the Forbes source capture, the Domahhhh thread, any Kick Champ source, and UMA oracle records. If those materials show that Clavicular publicly stated that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the final Yes outcome and corroborating credible reporting should satisfy preponderance. If the best source instead shows only jokes, wishful remarks, a contest proposal, or unsupported reposts, the plaintiff's case would be materially weaker.\\n\\nFor opening purposes, the plaintiff's theory is disciplined: the official market record and secondary reporting make Yes the more plausible starting point, but the case should be decided by the preserved source chain, not by market price alone.\"},{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense position starts with the market rule itself. This case is not resolved by asking whether a rumor circulated, whether Polymarket ultimately showed a Yes outcome, or whether traders believed a provocative streamer had created controversy. The proposition requires proof, by a preponderance, that Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the relevant window.\\n\\nThe admitted packet proves some important background. The market page record fixes the contract language: only credible announcements qualify; jokes do not; the ordinary resolution source is statements from Clavicular or his representatives, with a definitive consensus of credible media as a possible secondary source. The same packet also shows the market was created on April 20, 2026 and later displayed a final Yes state after proposed and disputed resolution sequences. The defense does not need to pretend those facts are irrelevant. They explain why this dispute exists.\\n\\nBut they do not prove the proposition. The preserved primary/platform evidence is the Polymarket page and Gamma/API status material. It proves the rule and the platform result; it does not preserve the original livestream, VOD, clip, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, or UMA voter/proposer record that would show why the market ended Yes. The packet's own primary-evidence assessment says the fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\\nThat missing link matters because the secondary record is internally conflicted on the very element the plaintiff must prove. Forbes is favorable to plaintiff insofar as it describes a dispute over a streamer who allegedly told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But the Times of India fact-check, also in the packet, says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular. Other packet excerpts describe remarks about wanting children, being a dad in the next few months, or a proposed pregnancy contest. Those are not the same thing as announcing that he and a partner are already expecting a baby through pregnancy.\\n\\nThe defense theory is therefore straightforward: final Yes resolution is circumstantial evidence of market administration, not a substitute for the qualifying announcement required by the rule. A viral claim repeated through social media, a contest proposal, a future-oriented wish to have children, shock-content banter, or an out-of-context clip does not satisfy a rule that expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes. If plaintiff can later preserve the original source and it shows an unambiguous, credible statement by Clavicular or his representative that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the defense will have to confront it. On the current record, that source is absent.\\n\\nThe decisive evidence in later phases should be narrow: the full original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript; any statement from Clavicular, a representative, or a publicist; the Polymarket clarification referenced in reporting; UMA transaction-level records showing the basis for the final outcome; and the source chain behind the Forbes characterization and the Domahhhh/Kick Champ leads. Those materials would let the council distinguish a real qualifying announcement from a rumor cycle.\\n\\nUntil that bridge is built, the plaintiff's strongest proof is that the market resolved Yes and some reporters described the controversy. The defense will show that the rule asks for more: a credible announcement, from the right source or a definitive credible-media consensus, about an existing partner pregnancy. The present packet identifies exactly why that has not yet been proven.\"}],\"prior_council_votes\":[{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The record contains conflicting secondary reports and lacks any primary statement or definitive media consensus confirming a credible announcement; thus the proposition is not more likely than not proven.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record contains conflicting secondary reports and no preserved primary statement from Clavicular announcing an existing partner pregnancy. The preserved quotes describe future-oriented contest/stunt language, and Times of India explicitly states no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy. The final Yes resolution does not establish what evidence the resolver relied upon, and there is no definitive consensus of credible media as the rule requires.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record contains no primary statement confirming a pregnancy announcement and presents conflicting secondary reports, so the proposition is not proven by preponderance.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"}],\"rebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense correctly identifies the record's weakest point: no original VOD, clip, or transcript is preserved. But the defense then treats that gap as dispositive. The market rule does not. It allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, and it also allows a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. That structure matters: the drafters anticipated that the council or resolver might have to decide from credible reporting, not only from a raw stream file.\\n\\nThe defense also understates the official final Yes. Plaintiff is not asking the council to treat market price as fact. PX-4 and the packet market record show more than price: a proposed Yes, dispute, proposed Yes, dispute, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0] and a resolved official state. That is the platform's resolution mechanism applying the same credibility rule after adversarial challenge. It is circumstantial, but it is unusually probative circumstantial evidence.\\n\\nThe defense says the Polymarket context describes future vows, a fertility-stack reveal, a dating-show/baby-mama proposal, and debunked girlfriend rumors. Yes, and plaintiff admitted that because unsupported viral reposts should be discounted. But that context does not erase the separate Forbes packet account: Forbes described the dispute as involving a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is not merely \\\"I want children someday\\\" language. It is the record's strongest description of an announcement that maps onto the rule.\\n\\nThe Times of India capture is adverse, but its force is narrower than the defense claims. It debunks the specific viral claim that Clavicular was expecting a first child with a girlfriend he met ten days earlier, and it discusses an out-of-context clip and a pregnancy-contest quote. It does not establish what the UMA resolver considered. It does not preserve the Polymarket clarification. It does not refute Forbes's specific characterization that the dispute concerned a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. And, like Forbes, it is secondary reporting rather than primary video.\\n\\nSo the evidentiary choice is not \\\"primary video versus nothing.\\\" It is whether the official final Yes, reached after two disputes under a rule that permits credible-media consensus, plus Forbes's affirmative characterization, outweighs adverse secondary reporting about a narrower viral rumor and the acknowledged absence of the raw source. On preponderance, plaintiff submits that it does.\\n\\nThe defense asks the council to infer that the official resolver accepted only a joke, stunt, or debunked rumor. That is possible, but it is not the better-supported inference on this record. The better-supported inference is that the official process credited a qualifying announcement or media-consensus path, even though the underlying primary artifact was not preserved in this packet. The gaps should reduce certainty; they should not convert a final official Yes and a favorable credible-media account into a No finding.\"}],\"submitted_evidence\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"size_bytes\":3638,\"source_description\":\"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.\",\"source_url\":\"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\",\"title\":\"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"size_bytes\":2189,\"source_description\":\"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.\",\"source_url\":\"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\",\"title\":\"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\"}],\"surrebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. The defense is not arguing that a raw VOD is the only legally possible proof. The rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. But that is the point: the record does not contain such a consensus.\\n\\nWhat the record contains is one favorable Forbes characterization, adverse Times of India reporting that no video or Clavicular statement confirmed pregnancy, Hindustan Times and Express Tribune descriptions of a pregnancy-contest stunt, and an admitted gaps file saying the original stream, transcript, platform clarification, and UMA records are missing. That is not a definitive media consensus. It is a conflicted source chain.\\n\\nPlaintiff says TOI only debunks the narrower ten-day girlfriend rumor. But the proposition is itself about a partner pregnancy, and TOI’s captured text goes beyond narrow timing: no video confirms a pregnancy; no statement from Clavicular confirms it; the shared clip was out of context; the preserved quote was about wanting children and a pregnancy contest; the viral claim likely came from jokes and out-of-context clips. Those points directly undercut credibility and qualification under a rule that excludes jokes and noncredible announcements.\\n\\nPlaintiff also asks the council to treat final Yes after disputes as unusually probative. It is probative that the market resolved Yes. It is not probative enough to fill the missing basis for that resolution. The record does not show what the resolver considered, whether it relied on Forbes, the viral Kick Champ rumor, trader pressure, or something else, and it lacks the platform clarification Forbes reportedly said pointed No. Without the source chain, final Yes risks becoming circular proof: the announcement happened because the market resolved Yes, and the market resolved Yes because the announcement happened.\\n\\nThe preponderance question is not whether plaintiff’s theory is possible. It is whether the qualifying announcement is more likely than not on the admitted record. Given the conflicting media accounts, the absence of the underlying statement, and the admitted context of future vows, stunt framing, and debunked rumors, plaintiff has not crossed that line.\"}],\"technical_reports\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Before filing, plaintiff rescanned the record and evidence list. Target sources were official Polymarket/Gamma records, Forbes reporting, Times of India adverse reporting, the original Kick/VOD or clip, the Polymarket clarification, Domahhhh X thread, Kick Champ source, and UMA records. The Polymarket page was opened and the Gamma API was fetched with python3 urllib; the official rule, final Yes sequence, IDs, outcome prices, and context were preserved as PX-4. The Times of India article was opened and adverse fact-check text was preserved as PX-5. Forbes direct page capture was attempted by web open/search, but no stronger article text than the existing packet capture was obtained in time, so plaintiff relied on PX-3 rather than submitting a search snippet. No original VOD/transcript or full UMA voter record was captured this phase; those remain material gaps affecting weight.\",\"title\":\"Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"Defense rescanned the current record and evidence list, then read the two new plaintiff submissions in full. Source targets considered were the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, Clavicular/representative statements, the Polymarket clarification referenced by Forbes, UMA proposer/disputer/voter records, Forbes source chain, Domahhhh X thread, and Kick Champ source. Opening-phase searches found Forbes, Polymarket, Times of India, Hindustan Times, X Domahhhh, Inkl, Poprant/Indiatimes, Binance, and Lines leads; X thread opening produced no readable text, and no original video/transcript or representative statement was captured. No new defense evidence was submitted because the material defense sources are already admitted through the packet and plaintiff's TOI capture, while uncaptured leads remain unverified. Unresolved gaps remain the original statement, full context, platform clarification, and UMA rationale.\",\"title\":\"Defense Source-Chain And Gap Ledger\"}]}}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T07:50:07.017222578Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":885915,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex09-20260630071703\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 885915\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex09-20260630071703\",\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"case\":{\"evidence_standard\":\"Preponderance of the evidence.\",\"member\":{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"model\":\"openrouter://mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5\",\"persona_filename\":\"personas/generic.md\"},\"opportunity\":{\"allowed_tools\":[\"submit_council_vote\"],\"id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"may_pass\":false,\"objective\":\"council vote by C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"role\":\"council\"},\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"proposition\":\"Between market creation on April 20, 2026, and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\",\"record\":{\"arguments\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff's case is strongest where it stays tied to the rule and the source chain. The proposition is not whether a child was born, and not whether every viral repost was accurate. It is whether Clavicular made a credible announcement, within the market window, that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\\n\\nThe official market evidence establishes the governing frame. The packet market page and the newly submitted official Polymarket/Gamma capture show the same rule: Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy; only credible announcements count; jokes do not; statements from Clavicular or representatives are the resolution source, with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting also permitted. The official source also shows the market was proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes again, disputed again, and finally resolved Yes. The Gamma extract fixes the market ID, condition ID, outcomes [Yes, No], outcomePrices [1,0], and resolver/closed-time fields. That is not mere trader gossip. It is the official resolution mechanism applying the very rule before this council.\\n\\nThe best explanation for that official Yes result appears in the case packet's secondary-reporting file. Forbes identified the dispute as being over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That description matters because it directly tracks the rule's central question: a statement by the covered person about having gotten a partner pregnant. Forbes also reported that the disagreement was binary: the market description and platform clarification were said to point No while the price pointed Yes, and the oracle had not closed the gap after two dispute rounds. The subsequent official record now shows the gap closed at Yes.\\n\\nThat sequence is plaintiff's preponderance case. The council can reasonably infer that the UMA/Polymarket final Yes did not arise from a vacuum. It followed a disputed process on a high-volume market whose rule allowed either the speaker's statements or a definitive credible-media consensus. The admitted record contains a credible financial-news account saying the dispute centered on a reported statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, and an official source showing the final resolver accepted Yes. On preponderance, those combined facts make a qualifying announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe defense is right that this proof has a missing primary artifact. The original livestream/VOD/transcript is not in the record. Nor is the full Polymarket clarification or transaction-level UMA voter record. The plaintiff does not ask the council to pretend otherwise. Those gaps reduce weight and make this a circumstantial/source-chain case, not a clean direct-video case.\\n\\nBut the gaps do not erase the official resolution and corroborating media account. The rule itself permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a preserved VOD is not automatically fatal. What matters is whether the admitted record, as a whole, makes the qualifying announcement more probable than the competing account that all of this was only a joke, contest, or rumor. The Forbes packet capture is the clearest pro-Yes secondary source; the official Polymarket/Gamma capture is the clearest official outcome source.\\n\\nThe plaintiff also submitted the Times of India fact-check because the council should see the strongest adverse source. It says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular, and it treats the viral claim as likely false or out of context. The live Polymarket context also cuts both ways: it describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama stunt, while acknowledging debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend pregnancy. That evidence undercuts any claim that every viral pregnancy story was credible.\\n\\nStill, TOI is not a primary record either. It is a fact-check of the rumor cycle, not the market-resolution record. It does not disprove that Clavicular made a qualifying announcement later accepted by the resolver or reflected in Forbes's account. It shows why the council should discount unsupported reposts and distinguish future-oriented fatherhood talk from an announcement of an existing pregnancy. Plaintiff's position survives that distinction because the favorable Forbes account is about a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, while the official resolver ultimately paid Yes under the same credibility standard.\\n\\nSo the plaintiff asks the council to give controlling weight to the official rule-and-resolution evidence, substantial corroborating weight to the Forbes secondary-reporting capture, and appropriate but not dispositive weight to the adverse TOI fact-check. The record is imperfect, but preponderance does not require certainty or medical confirmation. It requires the better answer. Here, the better answer is that the market's final Yes reflected a credible announcement or qualifying credible-media consensus that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy within the covered window.\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s case depends on converting a market result into proof of the underlying fact. The record does not support that conversion.\\n\\nThe rule requires a credible announcement that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. The official market evidence proves the wording, timing, dispute sequence, and final Yes outcome. It does not prove what Clavicular actually said. The packet’s official-source and primary-evidence files say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved and that the fact question remains dependent on locating the underlying stream, clip, transcript, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s new Polymarket/Gamma capture adds official details, but the added context cuts against plaintiff’s theory. It describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, a fertility-stack reveal, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama proposal involving 500 contestants. It separately describes “debunked rumors” of a girlfriend’s pregnancy after ten days. Those are not admissions that he and a partner were already expecting a baby. They are future intent, stunt framing, and rumor framing.\\n\\nThe strongest pro-Yes item is the Forbes excerpt in the secondary-reporting packet saying the dispute concerned a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But in this record Forbes is a summarized secondary account in an article about an oracle dispute, not the underlying video, transcript, source post, or representative statement. The same Forbes excerpt also reported that the market description and platform clarification said No while price said Yes, and that traders alleged the oracle had become a disinformation engine. That is not a clean source chain; it is a warning that market mechanics and trader incentives may have overtaken source proof.\\n\\nThe adverse evidence is more specific about the missing link. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, the actual preserved quote was future-oriented pregnancy-contest language, and the viral claim was false and likely came from jokes, out-of-context clips, and his content style. The secondary-reporting packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries match that: “I must have children,” “I must get children today,” and “I will be a dad in the next few months” were treated as a controversial proposal or stunt, not confirmation of an existing partner pregnancy.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a VOD is not automatically fatal. True, but the record does not show a definitive consensus. It shows conflict: Forbes characterizes the dispute one way; Times of India expressly debunks the girlfriend-pregnancy claim; Hindustan Times and Express Tribune frame the remarks as a contest/stunt; the packet says no primary source or Domahhhh thread text was located. A single favorable secondary characterization plus a final market resolution is not a definitive media consensus, especially where admitted adverse reporting directly denies confirmation.\\n\\nNor should the council give controlling weight to the final Yes state. The official resolver result proves that the market was resolved Yes. It does not reveal the evidence considered, the voters’ rationale, the proposer/disputer record, or whether the resolution rested on the same viral rumor now debunked in the record. The unresolved-gaps file expressly notes the missing UMA records and the missing Polymarket clarification Forbes said pointed No.\\n\\nOn preponderance, the better-supported finding is not that a qualifying announcement happened. It is that there was a viral controversy after market creation, built from future fatherhood talk, a pregnancy-contest stunt, social-media rumors, and a disputed market process that ultimately resolved Yes without preserving the basis. The proposition asks for a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy. The current record proves the controversy and the market result, but it does not prove that announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe defense therefore asks the council to find the proposition not proven on this record.\"}],\"closings\":[{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff does not ask you to decide that every viral post was true, or that the record proves the private medical fact of pregnancy. The proposition is narrower: whether Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the covered window.\\n\\nThe record proves the rule, the timing, and the official resolution. The market text required a credible announcement, excluded jokes, and allowed not only statements from Clavicular or representatives but also a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. The official Polymarket/Gamma evidence then shows proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes, disputed again, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0]. That is not a mere price chart. It is the official resolution process applying the same rule now before this council.\\n\\nThe record also contains the affirmative source-chain link. The secondary-reporting packet preserves Forbes's characterization that the dispute was over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is the key phrase in this case. It is not simply a desire to have children someday. It is a reported statement about having gotten a girl pregnant, which maps directly to the rule's pregnancy-announcement requirement. The final Yes resolution then confirms that the official process ultimately credited the Yes side despite disputes.\\n\\nThe defense's best point is real: the original VOD, transcript, Polymarket clarification, and UMA voter rationale are not in the record. That means the plaintiff's case is not direct-video proof. But preponderance does not demand perfect custody or certainty. It asks which inference is better supported by the admitted record.\\n\\nThe adverse record does not carry the defense over that line. The Times of India capture and the live Polymarket context warn against unsupported girlfriend-rumor reposts, out-of-context clips, future fatherhood talk, and stunt framing. Plaintiff accepts that warning. Those materials show why jokes and rumors should be discounted. They do not establish that the official resolver accepted a joke, and they do not erase Forbes's account of a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. They are secondary reports too; they are not the missing primary video.\\n\\nThe defense's theory requires a larger inference than plaintiff's. It asks you to conclude that, after two disputes, the official final Yes likely rested on nothing more than a noncredible rumor or stunt, even though the rule expressly excluded such material and even though Forbes described the dispute in terms of a pregnancy statement. That is possible, but on this record it is not the more probable account.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's account fits all of the admitted pieces: the rule allowed a credible announcement or credible-media consensus; Forbes reported the relevant announcement framing; the market underwent contested resolution; and the final official state paid Yes. The conflicting adverse reporting explains why the case was disputed and why the source chain is imperfect. It does not make No more likely than Yes.\\n\\nFor that reason, under the preponderance standard, the council should find that the proposition is proven.\"},{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the record leaves this case short of preponderance.\\n\\nThe plaintiff is right about one thing: the proposition is not whether a child was born or whether a pregnancy was medically true. The question is whether Clavicular made a credible qualifying announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. But the record still has to prove that announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe official market evidence proves the rule, the dates, the dispute sequence, and the final Yes state. It does not prove the underlying source. The case-packet official-source and primary-evidence files expressly say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved. The unresolved-gaps file identifies the same missing pieces: original livestream clip, VOD, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, and UMA proposer/disputer/voter records.\\n\\nThat matters because plaintiff’s case turns on a bridge it never fully builds. The bridge is one Forbes characterization that the dispute involved a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, plus the final Yes resolution. But the record does not preserve Forbes’s underlying source chain. And the same secondary-reporting packet records that Forbes described the market description and platform clarification as saying No, while price said Yes, and linked criticism of the oracle process. That is not a clean, independent confirmation of a qualifying announcement.\\n\\nThe contrary evidence is not just noise. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, and it identifies the actual preserved quote as future-oriented pregnancy-contest language. The packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries likewise frame the remarks as a contest or stunt: wanting children, needing children today, and being a dad in the next few months. Plaintiff’s own Polymarket/Gamma capture describes trader consensus as driven by public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, a dating-show/baby-mama stunt, and debunked girlfriend-pregnancy rumors. Those facts fit a rumor and stunt cycle at least as well as they fit a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. It does. But this record is not a consensus. It is a conflict: one favorable Forbes phrasing, adverse fact-checking, multiple contest/stunt accounts, and admitted missing source-chain material. A definitive consensus cannot be inferred from divided secondary reporting.\\n\\nPlaintiff also says the official Yes after disputes is unusually probative. It has some weight, but it cannot carry the burden by itself. The record does not show what the resolver considered or why it resolved Yes. Without the UMA rationale, source material, or platform clarification, final Yes is at risk of circular reasoning: using the market’s outcome to prove the fact that the market outcome was supposed to decide.\\n\\nThe defense is not asking the council to find that no rumor existed, or that no one ever thought Clavicular might make such an announcement. The defense is asking the council to apply the actual proposition and the preponderance standard. On this record, a qualifying credible announcement is not more likely than a nonqualifying mix of future fatherhood talk, a provocative contest proposal, out-of-context clips, and debunked viral claims.\\n\\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition not proven.\"}],\"evidence\":[{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407\",\"size_bytes\":1254,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"04/045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:34Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"size_bytes\":2189,\"source_description\":\"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.\",\"source_url\":\"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\",\"storage_name\":\"55/5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068\",\"size_bytes\":4343,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"79/795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"official-source-record.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0\",\"size_bytes\":1851,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"a7/a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"official-source-record.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"market-page.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5\",\"size_bytes\":2778,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"d1/d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"market-page.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:11Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"size_bytes\":3638,\"source_description\":\"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.\",\"source_url\":\"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\",\"storage_name\":\"f0/f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"primary-evidence.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94\",\"size_bytes\":1589,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"f8/f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"primary-evidence.txt\"}],\"exhibits\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"label\":\"PX-1 Market page packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\\n\\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRule text:\\n\\n\\u003e This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\\n\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\\n\\nEvent:\\n\\n- event id: 400878\\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: true\\n- event closed: true\\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\\n\\nMarket:\\n\\n- market id: 2037907\\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\\n- market closed: true\\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"PX-2 Official source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\n## Polymarket source\\n\\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\n\\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\\n\\n## Clavicular or representative statements\\n\\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\\n\\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\\n\\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\\n\\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\\n\\n## UMA / oracle source\\n\\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"PX-3 Secondary reporting packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"PX-4 Official Polymarket/Gamma merits capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"PX-5 Times of India adverse fact-check capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"PX-6 Record gaps packet file\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"label\":\"DX-1 Market rule and initial final-outcome packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\\n\\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRule text:\\n\\n\\u003e This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\\n\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\\n\\nEvent:\\n\\n- event id: 400878\\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: true\\n- event closed: true\\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\\n\\nMarket:\\n\\n- market id: 2037907\\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\\n- market closed: true\\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"DX-2 Official-source packet record showing missing primary statement and UMA detail\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\n## Polymarket source\\n\\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\n\\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\\n\\n## Clavicular or representative statements\\n\\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\\n\\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\\n\\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\\n\\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\\n\\n## UMA / oracle source\\n\\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence\",\"label\":\"DX-3 Primary-evidence packet assessment of missing underlying proof\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Primary evidence\\n\\n## Preserved primary/platform evidence\\n\\n- Polymarket market page: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Polymarket Gamma API event record: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Captured files: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt; source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json; source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\nThe official market rule requires a credible announcement by Clavicular that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy during the specified window.\\n\\n## Potential primary-source leads not locally preserved\\n\\n- Clavicular's Kick page or VODs: https://kick.com/clavicular/videos, referenced by Hindustan Times.\\n- Domahhhh's April 30 X thread about the oracle dispute: https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218, referenced by Forbes.\\n- JexTrade's April 29 X post about a large No buy, referenced by Forbes.\\n- @holy_moses7 posts claiming the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” referenced by Forbes.\\n- The viral Kick Champ post that Times of India says claimed Clavicular was “expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days ago.” The exact source URL was not captured.\\n\\n## Preliminary source assessment\\n\\nThe preserved primary evidence proves the contract wording and the platform's final Yes state. It does not itself prove that a qualifying credible announcement occurred. The fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"DX-4 Secondary-reporting conflict and adverse context\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"DX-5 Unresolved record gaps\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"DX-6 Plaintiff Polymarket/Gamma capture, including context about vows, stunt, and debunked rumors\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"DX-7 Plaintiff-submitted Times of India adverse fact-check\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"DX-S1 TOI fact-check on no confirming video or Clavicular statement\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"DX-S2 Conflicting secondary reporting and contest/stunt framing\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"DX-S3 Missing original statement, platform clarification, and UMA records\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"DX-S4 Official Polymarket/Gamma capture with market context\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"}],\"openings\":[{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, this case is about a narrow event definition, not about proving the private fact of a pregnancy to medical certainty. The proposition asks whether, after the April 20, 2026 market creation and before the stated deadline, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. Under the preponderance standard, the question is whether the better-supported reading of the available source chain is that a qualifying announcement occurred.\\n\\nThe present case packet already fixes the governing rule and the official market posture. The Polymarket page record states that the market resolves Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy, that only credible announcements qualify, that jokes do not suffice, and that statements from Clavicular or his representatives are the primary resolution source while a definitive consensus of credible media may also be considered. The same official-source packet records the platform/API state: the market went through proposed/disputed sequences and ultimately shows a final Yes outcome.\\n\\nThat matters, but it is not the whole case. A final Yes state is strong circumstantial and procedural evidence that the market's resolver accepted the event as satisfied, but by itself it does not show the exact words, tone, context, or credibility of the underlying announcement. The plaintiff's burden is therefore to connect that official Yes state to the source material that caused it.\\n\\nThe packet points to that connection. Forbes reported the dispute as turning on what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. Other reports described livestream remarks about wanting children or becoming a dad soon, and several sources frame the incident as a viral controversy. Those reports explain why the market moved and why the oracle dispute arose. They support the plaintiff's theory that there was, at minimum, a public announcement or reported announcement that the market treated as sufficient.\\n\\nThe defense will stress the same record's weaknesses. The packet does not yet preserve the original livestream clip, VOD, full transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification mentioned by Forbes, or UMA transaction-level record. The Times of India fact-check says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular; other reporting characterizes the comments as a contest, stunt, joke, or out-of-context viral content. Those are real weight issues because the rule expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes.\\n\\nSo the decisive factual questions are these: first, what exactly did Clavicular say, and was it about an existing partner pregnancy rather than a future desire, stunt, or contest? Second, did the statement occur after market creation? Third, did Clavicular or a representative make it, or did credible media reach the definitive consensus allowed by the rules? Fourth, does the Polymarket/UMA Yes resolution rest on that source chain or on speculation and trader pressure?\\n\\nThe plaintiff expects the later evidentiary phase to focus on the primary artifacts the packet identifies: the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, the Polymarket clarification, the Forbes source capture, the Domahhhh thread, any Kick Champ source, and UMA oracle records. If those materials show that Clavicular publicly stated that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the final Yes outcome and corroborating credible reporting should satisfy preponderance. If the best source instead shows only jokes, wishful remarks, a contest proposal, or unsupported reposts, the plaintiff's case would be materially weaker.\\n\\nFor opening purposes, the plaintiff's theory is disciplined: the official market record and secondary reporting make Yes the more plausible starting point, but the case should be decided by the preserved source chain, not by market price alone.\"},{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense position starts with the market rule itself. This case is not resolved by asking whether a rumor circulated, whether Polymarket ultimately showed a Yes outcome, or whether traders believed a provocative streamer had created controversy. The proposition requires proof, by a preponderance, that Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the relevant window.\\n\\nThe admitted packet proves some important background. The market page record fixes the contract language: only credible announcements qualify; jokes do not; the ordinary resolution source is statements from Clavicular or his representatives, with a definitive consensus of credible media as a possible secondary source. The same packet also shows the market was created on April 20, 2026 and later displayed a final Yes state after proposed and disputed resolution sequences. The defense does not need to pretend those facts are irrelevant. They explain why this dispute exists.\\n\\nBut they do not prove the proposition. The preserved primary/platform evidence is the Polymarket page and Gamma/API status material. It proves the rule and the platform result; it does not preserve the original livestream, VOD, clip, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, or UMA voter/proposer record that would show why the market ended Yes. The packet's own primary-evidence assessment says the fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\\nThat missing link matters because the secondary record is internally conflicted on the very element the plaintiff must prove. Forbes is favorable to plaintiff insofar as it describes a dispute over a streamer who allegedly told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But the Times of India fact-check, also in the packet, says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular. Other packet excerpts describe remarks about wanting children, being a dad in the next few months, or a proposed pregnancy contest. Those are not the same thing as announcing that he and a partner are already expecting a baby through pregnancy.\\n\\nThe defense theory is therefore straightforward: final Yes resolution is circumstantial evidence of market administration, not a substitute for the qualifying announcement required by the rule. A viral claim repeated through social media, a contest proposal, a future-oriented wish to have children, shock-content banter, or an out-of-context clip does not satisfy a rule that expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes. If plaintiff can later preserve the original source and it shows an unambiguous, credible statement by Clavicular or his representative that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the defense will have to confront it. On the current record, that source is absent.\\n\\nThe decisive evidence in later phases should be narrow: the full original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript; any statement from Clavicular, a representative, or a publicist; the Polymarket clarification referenced in reporting; UMA transaction-level records showing the basis for the final outcome; and the source chain behind the Forbes characterization and the Domahhhh/Kick Champ leads. Those materials would let the council distinguish a real qualifying announcement from a rumor cycle.\\n\\nUntil that bridge is built, the plaintiff's strongest proof is that the market resolved Yes and some reporters described the controversy. The defense will show that the rule asks for more: a credible announcement, from the right source or a definitive credible-media consensus, about an existing partner pregnancy. The present packet identifies exactly why that has not yet been proven.\"}],\"prior_council_votes\":[{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The record contains conflicting secondary reports and lacks any primary statement or definitive media consensus confirming a credible announcement; thus the proposition is not more likely than not proven.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record contains conflicting secondary reports and no preserved primary statement from Clavicular announcing an existing partner pregnancy. The preserved quotes describe future-oriented contest/stunt language, and Times of India explicitly states no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy. The final Yes resolution does not establish what evidence the resolver relied upon, and there is no definitive consensus of credible media as the rule requires.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record contains no primary statement confirming a pregnancy announcement and presents conflicting secondary reports, so the proposition is not proven by preponderance.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"}],\"rebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense correctly identifies the record's weakest point: no original VOD, clip, or transcript is preserved. But the defense then treats that gap as dispositive. The market rule does not. It allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, and it also allows a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. That structure matters: the drafters anticipated that the council or resolver might have to decide from credible reporting, not only from a raw stream file.\\n\\nThe defense also understates the official final Yes. Plaintiff is not asking the council to treat market price as fact. PX-4 and the packet market record show more than price: a proposed Yes, dispute, proposed Yes, dispute, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0] and a resolved official state. That is the platform's resolution mechanism applying the same credibility rule after adversarial challenge. It is circumstantial, but it is unusually probative circumstantial evidence.\\n\\nThe defense says the Polymarket context describes future vows, a fertility-stack reveal, a dating-show/baby-mama proposal, and debunked girlfriend rumors. Yes, and plaintiff admitted that because unsupported viral reposts should be discounted. But that context does not erase the separate Forbes packet account: Forbes described the dispute as involving a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is not merely \\\"I want children someday\\\" language. It is the record's strongest description of an announcement that maps onto the rule.\\n\\nThe Times of India capture is adverse, but its force is narrower than the defense claims. It debunks the specific viral claim that Clavicular was expecting a first child with a girlfriend he met ten days earlier, and it discusses an out-of-context clip and a pregnancy-contest quote. It does not establish what the UMA resolver considered. It does not preserve the Polymarket clarification. It does not refute Forbes's specific characterization that the dispute concerned a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. And, like Forbes, it is secondary reporting rather than primary video.\\n\\nSo the evidentiary choice is not \\\"primary video versus nothing.\\\" It is whether the official final Yes, reached after two disputes under a rule that permits credible-media consensus, plus Forbes's affirmative characterization, outweighs adverse secondary reporting about a narrower viral rumor and the acknowledged absence of the raw source. On preponderance, plaintiff submits that it does.\\n\\nThe defense asks the council to infer that the official resolver accepted only a joke, stunt, or debunked rumor. That is possible, but it is not the better-supported inference on this record. The better-supported inference is that the official process credited a qualifying announcement or media-consensus path, even though the underlying primary artifact was not preserved in this packet. The gaps should reduce certainty; they should not convert a final official Yes and a favorable credible-media account into a No finding.\"}],\"submitted_evidence\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"size_bytes\":3638,\"source_description\":\"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.\",\"source_url\":\"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\",\"title\":\"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"size_bytes\":2189,\"source_description\":\"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.\",\"source_url\":\"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\",\"title\":\"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\"}],\"surrebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. The defense is not arguing that a raw VOD is the only legally possible proof. The rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. But that is the point: the record does not contain such a consensus.\\n\\nWhat the record contains is one favorable Forbes characterization, adverse Times of India reporting that no video or Clavicular statement confirmed pregnancy, Hindustan Times and Express Tribune descriptions of a pregnancy-contest stunt, and an admitted gaps file saying the original stream, transcript, platform clarification, and UMA records are missing. That is not a definitive media consensus. It is a conflicted source chain.\\n\\nPlaintiff says TOI only debunks the narrower ten-day girlfriend rumor. But the proposition is itself about a partner pregnancy, and TOI’s captured text goes beyond narrow timing: no video confirms a pregnancy; no statement from Clavicular confirms it; the shared clip was out of context; the preserved quote was about wanting children and a pregnancy contest; the viral claim likely came from jokes and out-of-context clips. Those points directly undercut credibility and qualification under a rule that excludes jokes and noncredible announcements.\\n\\nPlaintiff also asks the council to treat final Yes after disputes as unusually probative. It is probative that the market resolved Yes. It is not probative enough to fill the missing basis for that resolution. The record does not show what the resolver considered, whether it relied on Forbes, the viral Kick Champ rumor, trader pressure, or something else, and it lacks the platform clarification Forbes reportedly said pointed No. Without the source chain, final Yes risks becoming circular proof: the announcement happened because the market resolved Yes, and the market resolved Yes because the announcement happened.\\n\\nThe preponderance question is not whether plaintiff’s theory is possible. It is whether the qualifying announcement is more likely than not on the admitted record. Given the conflicting media accounts, the absence of the underlying statement, and the admitted context of future vows, stunt framing, and debunked rumors, plaintiff has not crossed that line.\"}],\"technical_reports\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Before filing, plaintiff rescanned the record and evidence list. Target sources were official Polymarket/Gamma records, Forbes reporting, Times of India adverse reporting, the original Kick/VOD or clip, the Polymarket clarification, Domahhhh X thread, Kick Champ source, and UMA records. The Polymarket page was opened and the Gamma API was fetched with python3 urllib; the official rule, final Yes sequence, IDs, outcome prices, and context were preserved as PX-4. The Times of India article was opened and adverse fact-check text was preserved as PX-5. Forbes direct page capture was attempted by web open/search, but no stronger article text than the existing packet capture was obtained in time, so plaintiff relied on PX-3 rather than submitting a search snippet. No original VOD/transcript or full UMA voter record was captured this phase; those remain material gaps affecting weight.\",\"title\":\"Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"Defense rescanned the current record and evidence list, then read the two new plaintiff submissions in full. Source targets considered were the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, Clavicular/representative statements, the Polymarket clarification referenced by Forbes, UMA proposer/disputer/voter records, Forbes source chain, Domahhhh X thread, and Kick Champ source. Opening-phase searches found Forbes, Polymarket, Times of India, Hindustan Times, X Domahhhh, Inkl, Poprant/Indiatimes, Binance, and Lines leads; X thread opening produced no readable text, and no original video/transcript or representative statement was captured. No new defense evidence was submitted because the material defense sources are already admitted through the packet and plaintiff's TOI capture, while uncaptured leads remain unverified. Unresolved gaps remain the original statement, full context, platform clarification, and UMA rationale.\",\"title\":\"Defense Source-Chain And Gap Ledger\"}]}}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T07:50:07.017222578Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":885915,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12}}"}],"structuredContent":{"case_id":"arb-ex09-20260630071703","member_id":"C4","ok":true,"result":{"case":{"evidence_standard":"Preponderance of the evidence.","member":{"member_id":"C4","model":"openrouter://mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5","persona_filename":"personas/generic.md"},"opportunity":{"allowed_tools":["submit_council_vote"],"id":"deliberation:1:C4","may_pass":false,"objective":"council vote by C4","phase":"deliberation","role":"council"},"phase":"deliberation","proposition":"Between market creation on April 20, 2026, and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.","record":{"arguments":[{"phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the plaintiff's case is strongest where it stays tied to the rule and the source chain. The proposition is not whether a child was born, and not whether every viral repost was accurate. It is whether Clavicular made a credible announcement, within the market window, that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\n\nThe official market evidence establishes the governing frame. The packet market page and the newly submitted official Polymarket/Gamma capture show the same rule: Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy; only credible announcements count; jokes do not; statements from Clavicular or representatives are the resolution source, with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting also permitted. The official source also shows the market was proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes again, disputed again, and finally resolved Yes. The Gamma extract fixes the market ID, condition ID, outcomes [Yes, No], outcomePrices [1,0], and resolver/closed-time fields. That is not mere trader gossip. It is the official resolution mechanism applying the very rule before this council.\n\nThe best explanation for that official Yes result appears in the case packet's secondary-reporting file. Forbes identified the dispute as being over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That description matters because it directly tracks the rule's central question: a statement by the covered person about having gotten a partner pregnant. Forbes also reported that the disagreement was binary: the market description and platform clarification were said to point No while the price pointed Yes, and the oracle had not closed the gap after two dispute rounds. The subsequent official record now shows the gap closed at Yes.\n\nThat sequence is plaintiff's preponderance case. The council can reasonably infer that the UMA/Polymarket final Yes did not arise from a vacuum. It followed a disputed process on a high-volume market whose rule allowed either the speaker's statements or a definitive credible-media consensus. The admitted record contains a credible financial-news account saying the dispute centered on a reported statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, and an official source showing the final resolver accepted Yes. On preponderance, those combined facts make a qualifying announcement more likely than not.\n\nThe defense is right that this proof has a missing primary artifact. The original livestream/VOD/transcript is not in the record. Nor is the full Polymarket clarification or transaction-level UMA voter record. The plaintiff does not ask the council to pretend otherwise. Those gaps reduce weight and make this a circumstantial/source-chain case, not a clean direct-video case.\n\nBut the gaps do not erase the official resolution and corroborating media account. The rule itself permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a preserved VOD is not automatically fatal. What matters is whether the admitted record, as a whole, makes the qualifying announcement more probable than the competing account that all of this was only a joke, contest, or rumor. The Forbes packet capture is the clearest pro-Yes secondary source; the official Polymarket/Gamma capture is the clearest official outcome source.\n\nThe plaintiff also submitted the Times of India fact-check because the council should see the strongest adverse source. It says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular, and it treats the viral claim as likely false or out of context. The live Polymarket context also cuts both ways: it describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama stunt, while acknowledging debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend pregnancy. That evidence undercuts any claim that every viral pregnancy story was credible.\n\nStill, TOI is not a primary record either. It is a fact-check of the rumor cycle, not the market-resolution record. It does not disprove that Clavicular made a qualifying announcement later accepted by the resolver or reflected in Forbes's account. It shows why the council should discount unsupported reposts and distinguish future-oriented fatherhood talk from an announcement of an existing pregnancy. Plaintiff's position survives that distinction because the favorable Forbes account is about a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, while the official resolver ultimately paid Yes under the same credibility standard.\n\nSo the plaintiff asks the council to give controlling weight to the official rule-and-resolution evidence, substantial corroborating weight to the Forbes secondary-reporting capture, and appropriate but not dispositive weight to the adverse TOI fact-check. The record is imperfect, but preponderance does not require certainty or medical confirmation. It requires the better answer. Here, the better answer is that the market's final Yes reflected a credible announcement or qualifying credible-media consensus that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy within the covered window."},{"phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, plaintiff’s case depends on converting a market result into proof of the underlying fact. The record does not support that conversion.\n\nThe rule requires a credible announcement that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. The official market evidence proves the wording, timing, dispute sequence, and final Yes outcome. It does not prove what Clavicular actually said. The packet’s official-source and primary-evidence files say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved and that the fact question remains dependent on locating the underlying stream, clip, transcript, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\n\nPlaintiff’s new Polymarket/Gamma capture adds official details, but the added context cuts against plaintiff’s theory. It describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, a fertility-stack reveal, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama proposal involving 500 contestants. It separately describes “debunked rumors” of a girlfriend’s pregnancy after ten days. Those are not admissions that he and a partner were already expecting a baby. They are future intent, stunt framing, and rumor framing.\n\nThe strongest pro-Yes item is the Forbes excerpt in the secondary-reporting packet saying the dispute concerned a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But in this record Forbes is a summarized secondary account in an article about an oracle dispute, not the underlying video, transcript, source post, or representative statement. The same Forbes excerpt also reported that the market description and platform clarification said No while price said Yes, and that traders alleged the oracle had become a disinformation engine. That is not a clean source chain; it is a warning that market mechanics and trader incentives may have overtaken source proof.\n\nThe adverse evidence is more specific about the missing link. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, the actual preserved quote was future-oriented pregnancy-contest language, and the viral claim was false and likely came from jokes, out-of-context clips, and his content style. The secondary-reporting packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries match that: “I must have children,” “I must get children today,” and “I will be a dad in the next few months” were treated as a controversial proposal or stunt, not confirmation of an existing partner pregnancy.\n\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a VOD is not automatically fatal. True, but the record does not show a definitive consensus. It shows conflict: Forbes characterizes the dispute one way; Times of India expressly debunks the girlfriend-pregnancy claim; Hindustan Times and Express Tribune frame the remarks as a contest/stunt; the packet says no primary source or Domahhhh thread text was located. A single favorable secondary characterization plus a final market resolution is not a definitive media consensus, especially where admitted adverse reporting directly denies confirmation.\n\nNor should the council give controlling weight to the final Yes state. The official resolver result proves that the market was resolved Yes. It does not reveal the evidence considered, the voters’ rationale, the proposer/disputer record, or whether the resolution rested on the same viral rumor now debunked in the record. The unresolved-gaps file expressly notes the missing UMA records and the missing Polymarket clarification Forbes said pointed No.\n\nOn preponderance, the better-supported finding is not that a qualifying announcement happened. It is that there was a viral controversy after market creation, built from future fatherhood talk, a pregnancy-contest stunt, social-media rumors, and a disputed market process that ultimately resolved Yes without preserving the basis. The proposition asks for a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy. The current record proves the controversy and the market result, but it does not prove that announcement more likely than not.\n\nThe defense therefore asks the council to find the proposition not proven on this record."}],"closings":[{"phase":"closings","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the plaintiff does not ask you to decide that every viral post was true, or that the record proves the private medical fact of pregnancy. The proposition is narrower: whether Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the covered window.\n\nThe record proves the rule, the timing, and the official resolution. The market text required a credible announcement, excluded jokes, and allowed not only statements from Clavicular or representatives but also a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. The official Polymarket/Gamma evidence then shows proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes, disputed again, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0]. That is not a mere price chart. It is the official resolution process applying the same rule now before this council.\n\nThe record also contains the affirmative source-chain link. The secondary-reporting packet preserves Forbes's characterization that the dispute was over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is the key phrase in this case. It is not simply a desire to have children someday. It is a reported statement about having gotten a girl pregnant, which maps directly to the rule's pregnancy-announcement requirement. The final Yes resolution then confirms that the official process ultimately credited the Yes side despite disputes.\n\nThe defense's best point is real: the original VOD, transcript, Polymarket clarification, and UMA voter rationale are not in the record. That means the plaintiff's case is not direct-video proof. But preponderance does not demand perfect custody or certainty. It asks which inference is better supported by the admitted record.\n\nThe adverse record does not carry the defense over that line. The Times of India capture and the live Polymarket context warn against unsupported girlfriend-rumor reposts, out-of-context clips, future fatherhood talk, and stunt framing. Plaintiff accepts that warning. Those materials show why jokes and rumors should be discounted. They do not establish that the official resolver accepted a joke, and they do not erase Forbes's account of a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. They are secondary reports too; they are not the missing primary video.\n\nThe defense's theory requires a larger inference than plaintiff's. It asks you to conclude that, after two disputes, the official final Yes likely rested on nothing more than a noncredible rumor or stunt, even though the rule expressly excluded such material and even though Forbes described the dispute in terms of a pregnancy statement. That is possible, but on this record it is not the more probable account.\n\nThe plaintiff's account fits all of the admitted pieces: the rule allowed a credible announcement or credible-media consensus; Forbes reported the relevant announcement framing; the market underwent contested resolution; and the final official state paid Yes. The conflicting adverse reporting explains why the case was disputed and why the source chain is imperfect. It does not make No more likely than Yes.\n\nFor that reason, under the preponderance standard, the council should find that the proposition is proven."},{"phase":"closings","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the record leaves this case short of preponderance.\n\nThe plaintiff is right about one thing: the proposition is not whether a child was born or whether a pregnancy was medically true. The question is whether Clavicular made a credible qualifying announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. But the record still has to prove that announcement more likely than not.\n\nThe official market evidence proves the rule, the dates, the dispute sequence, and the final Yes state. It does not prove the underlying source. The case-packet official-source and primary-evidence files expressly say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved. The unresolved-gaps file identifies the same missing pieces: original livestream clip, VOD, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, and UMA proposer/disputer/voter records.\n\nThat matters because plaintiff’s case turns on a bridge it never fully builds. The bridge is one Forbes characterization that the dispute involved a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, plus the final Yes resolution. But the record does not preserve Forbes’s underlying source chain. And the same secondary-reporting packet records that Forbes described the market description and platform clarification as saying No, while price said Yes, and linked criticism of the oracle process. That is not a clean, independent confirmation of a qualifying announcement.\n\nThe contrary evidence is not just noise. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, and it identifies the actual preserved quote as future-oriented pregnancy-contest language. The packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries likewise frame the remarks as a contest or stunt: wanting children, needing children today, and being a dad in the next few months. Plaintiff’s own Polymarket/Gamma capture describes trader consensus as driven by public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, a dating-show/baby-mama stunt, and debunked girlfriend-pregnancy rumors. Those facts fit a rumor and stunt cycle at least as well as they fit a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy.\n\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. It does. But this record is not a consensus. It is a conflict: one favorable Forbes phrasing, adverse fact-checking, multiple contest/stunt accounts, and admitted missing source-chain material. A definitive consensus cannot be inferred from divided secondary reporting.\n\nPlaintiff also says the official Yes after disputes is unusually probative. It has some weight, but it cannot carry the burden by itself. The record does not show what the resolver considered or why it resolved Yes. Without the UMA rationale, source material, or platform clarification, final Yes is at risk of circular reasoning: using the market’s outcome to prove the fact that the market outcome was supposed to decide.\n\nThe defense is not asking the council to find that no rumor existed, or that no one ever thought Clavicular might make such an announcement. The defense is asking the council to apply the actual proposition and the preponderance standard. On this record, a qualifying credible announcement is not more likely than a nonqualifying mix of future fatherhood talk, a provocative contest proposal, out-of-context clips, and debunked viral claims.\n\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition not proven."}],"evidence":[{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z","evidence_id":"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"unresolved-record-gaps.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407","size_bytes":1254,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"04/045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"unresolved-record-gaps.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:25:34Z","evidence_id":"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z","sha256":"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5","size_bytes":2189,"source_description":"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.","source_url":"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms","storage_name":"55/5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z","evidence_id":"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"secondary-reporting.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068","size_bytes":4343,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"79/795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"secondary-reporting.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z","evidence_id":"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"official-source-record.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0","size_bytes":1851,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"a7/a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"official-source-record.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z","evidence_id":"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"market-page.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5","size_bytes":2778,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"d1/d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"market-page.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:25:11Z","evidence_id":"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z","sha256":"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab","size_bytes":3638,"source_description":"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.","source_url":"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026","storage_name":"f0/f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z","evidence_id":"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"primary-evidence.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94","size_bytes":1589,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"f8/f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"primary-evidence.txt"}],"exhibits":[{"evidence_id":"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page","label":"PX-1 Market page packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Market page record\n\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\n\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\n\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRule text:\n\n> This market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n>\n> Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n>\n> The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\n\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\n\nEvent:\n\n- event id: 400878\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: true\n- event closed: true\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\n\nMarket:\n\n- market id: 2037907\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\n- market closed: true\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"1\", \"0\"]\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record","label":"PX-2 Official source packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Official source record\n\n## Polymarket source\n\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\n\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\n\n## Clavicular or representative statements\n\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\n\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\n\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\n\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\n\n## UMA / oracle source\n\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting","label":"PX-3 Secondary reporting packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Secondary reporting\n\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\n\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\n\n## Times of India fact check\n\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\n\n## Hindustan Times\n\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\n\n## The Express Tribune\n\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\n\n## Search notes\n\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad","label":"PX-4 Official Polymarket/Gamma merits capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nSources:\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\n\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDisplayed probability: >99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\n\nRules text shown on page:\nThis market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\nMarket context text shown on page:\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \"dating show\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\n\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\n\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\n\n## Gamma API fields observed\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\nEvent id: 400878.\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDescription: same rules text as above.\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\nEvent active: true.\nEvent closed: true.\nEvent archived: false.\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\nMarket id: 2037907.\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nOutcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"].\nOutcome prices: [\"1\", \"0\"].\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase."},{"evidence_id":"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e","label":"PX-5 Times of India adverse fact-check capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\n\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\n\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\"\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says: \"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\"\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \"pregnancy contest\" and quotes: \"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\"\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition."},{"evidence_id":"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps","label":"PX-6 Record gaps packet file","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Unresolved record gaps\n\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page","label":"DX-1 Market rule and initial final-outcome packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Market page record\n\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\n\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\n\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRule text:\n\n> This market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n>\n> Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n>\n> The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\n\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\n\nEvent:\n\n- event id: 400878\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: true\n- event closed: true\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\n\nMarket:\n\n- market id: 2037907\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\n- market closed: true\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"1\", \"0\"]\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record","label":"DX-2 Official-source packet record showing missing primary statement and UMA detail","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Official source record\n\n## Polymarket source\n\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\n\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\n\n## Clavicular or representative statements\n\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\n\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\n\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\n\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\n\n## UMA / oracle source\n\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence","label":"DX-3 Primary-evidence packet assessment of missing underlying proof","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Primary evidence\n\n## Preserved primary/platform evidence\n\n- Polymarket market page: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Polymarket Gamma API event record: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Captured files: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt; source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json; source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\n\nThe official market rule requires a credible announcement by Clavicular that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy during the specified window.\n\n## Potential primary-source leads not locally preserved\n\n- Clavicular's Kick page or VODs: https://kick.com/clavicular/videos, referenced by Hindustan Times.\n- Domahhhh's April 30 X thread about the oracle dispute: https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218, referenced by Forbes.\n- JexTrade's April 29 X post about a large No buy, referenced by Forbes.\n- @holy_moses7 posts claiming the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” referenced by Forbes.\n- The viral Kick Champ post that Times of India says claimed Clavicular was “expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days ago.” The exact source URL was not captured.\n\n## Preliminary source assessment\n\nThe preserved primary evidence proves the contract wording and the platform's final Yes state. It does not itself prove that a qualifying credible announcement occurred. The fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting","label":"DX-4 Secondary-reporting conflict and adverse context","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Secondary reporting\n\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\n\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\n\n## Times of India fact check\n\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\n\n## Hindustan Times\n\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\n\n## The Express Tribune\n\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\n\n## Search notes\n\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps","label":"DX-5 Unresolved record gaps","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Unresolved record gaps\n\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad","label":"DX-6 Plaintiff Polymarket/Gamma capture, including context about vows, stunt, and debunked rumors","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nSources:\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\n\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDisplayed probability: >99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\n\nRules text shown on page:\nThis market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\nMarket context text shown on page:\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \"dating show\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\n\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\n\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\n\n## Gamma API fields observed\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\nEvent id: 400878.\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDescription: same rules text as above.\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\nEvent active: true.\nEvent closed: true.\nEvent archived: false.\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\nMarket id: 2037907.\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nOutcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"].\nOutcome prices: [\"1\", \"0\"].\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase."},{"evidence_id":"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e","label":"DX-7 Plaintiff-submitted Times of India adverse fact-check","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\n\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\n\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\"\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says: \"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\"\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \"pregnancy contest\" and quotes: \"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\"\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition."},{"evidence_id":"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e","label":"DX-S1 TOI fact-check on no confirming video or Clavicular statement","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\n\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\n\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\"\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says: \"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\"\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \"pregnancy contest\" and quotes: \"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\"\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition."},{"evidence_id":"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting","label":"DX-S2 Conflicting secondary reporting and contest/stunt framing","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"# Secondary reporting\n\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\n\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\n\n## Times of India fact check\n\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\n\n## Hindustan Times\n\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\n\n## The Express Tribune\n\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\n\n## Search notes\n\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps","label":"DX-S3 Missing original statement, platform clarification, and UMA records","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"# Unresolved record gaps\n\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad","label":"DX-S4 Official Polymarket/Gamma capture with market context","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nSources:\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\n\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDisplayed probability: >99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\n\nRules text shown on page:\nThis market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\nMarket context text shown on page:\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \"dating show\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\n\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\n\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\n\n## Gamma API fields observed\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\nEvent id: 400878.\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDescription: same rules text as above.\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\nEvent active: true.\nEvent closed: true.\nEvent archived: false.\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\nMarket id: 2037907.\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nOutcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"].\nOutcome prices: [\"1\", \"0\"].\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase."}],"openings":[{"phase":"openings","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, this case is about a narrow event definition, not about proving the private fact of a pregnancy to medical certainty. The proposition asks whether, after the April 20, 2026 market creation and before the stated deadline, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. Under the preponderance standard, the question is whether the better-supported reading of the available source chain is that a qualifying announcement occurred.\n\nThe present case packet already fixes the governing rule and the official market posture. The Polymarket page record states that the market resolves Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy, that only credible announcements qualify, that jokes do not suffice, and that statements from Clavicular or his representatives are the primary resolution source while a definitive consensus of credible media may also be considered. The same official-source packet records the platform/API state: the market went through proposed/disputed sequences and ultimately shows a final Yes outcome.\n\nThat matters, but it is not the whole case. A final Yes state is strong circumstantial and procedural evidence that the market's resolver accepted the event as satisfied, but by itself it does not show the exact words, tone, context, or credibility of the underlying announcement. The plaintiff's burden is therefore to connect that official Yes state to the source material that caused it.\n\nThe packet points to that connection. Forbes reported the dispute as turning on what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. Other reports described livestream remarks about wanting children or becoming a dad soon, and several sources frame the incident as a viral controversy. Those reports explain why the market moved and why the oracle dispute arose. They support the plaintiff's theory that there was, at minimum, a public announcement or reported announcement that the market treated as sufficient.\n\nThe defense will stress the same record's weaknesses. The packet does not yet preserve the original livestream clip, VOD, full transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification mentioned by Forbes, or UMA transaction-level record. The Times of India fact-check says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular; other reporting characterizes the comments as a contest, stunt, joke, or out-of-context viral content. Those are real weight issues because the rule expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes.\n\nSo the decisive factual questions are these: first, what exactly did Clavicular say, and was it about an existing partner pregnancy rather than a future desire, stunt, or contest? Second, did the statement occur after market creation? Third, did Clavicular or a representative make it, or did credible media reach the definitive consensus allowed by the rules? Fourth, does the Polymarket/UMA Yes resolution rest on that source chain or on speculation and trader pressure?\n\nThe plaintiff expects the later evidentiary phase to focus on the primary artifacts the packet identifies: the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, the Polymarket clarification, the Forbes source capture, the Domahhhh thread, any Kick Champ source, and UMA oracle records. If those materials show that Clavicular publicly stated that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the final Yes outcome and corroborating credible reporting should satisfy preponderance. If the best source instead shows only jokes, wishful remarks, a contest proposal, or unsupported reposts, the plaintiff's case would be materially weaker.\n\nFor opening purposes, the plaintiff's theory is disciplined: the official market record and secondary reporting make Yes the more plausible starting point, but the case should be decided by the preserved source chain, not by market price alone."},{"phase":"openings","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the defense position starts with the market rule itself. This case is not resolved by asking whether a rumor circulated, whether Polymarket ultimately showed a Yes outcome, or whether traders believed a provocative streamer had created controversy. The proposition requires proof, by a preponderance, that Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the relevant window.\n\nThe admitted packet proves some important background. The market page record fixes the contract language: only credible announcements qualify; jokes do not; the ordinary resolution source is statements from Clavicular or his representatives, with a definitive consensus of credible media as a possible secondary source. The same packet also shows the market was created on April 20, 2026 and later displayed a final Yes state after proposed and disputed resolution sequences. The defense does not need to pretend those facts are irrelevant. They explain why this dispute exists.\n\nBut they do not prove the proposition. The preserved primary/platform evidence is the Polymarket page and Gamma/API status material. It proves the rule and the platform result; it does not preserve the original livestream, VOD, clip, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, or UMA voter/proposer record that would show why the market ended Yes. The packet's own primary-evidence assessment says the fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\n\nThat missing link matters because the secondary record is internally conflicted on the very element the plaintiff must prove. Forbes is favorable to plaintiff insofar as it describes a dispute over a streamer who allegedly told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But the Times of India fact-check, also in the packet, says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular. Other packet excerpts describe remarks about wanting children, being a dad in the next few months, or a proposed pregnancy contest. Those are not the same thing as announcing that he and a partner are already expecting a baby through pregnancy.\n\nThe defense theory is therefore straightforward: final Yes resolution is circumstantial evidence of market administration, not a substitute for the qualifying announcement required by the rule. A viral claim repeated through social media, a contest proposal, a future-oriented wish to have children, shock-content banter, or an out-of-context clip does not satisfy a rule that expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes. If plaintiff can later preserve the original source and it shows an unambiguous, credible statement by Clavicular or his representative that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the defense will have to confront it. On the current record, that source is absent.\n\nThe decisive evidence in later phases should be narrow: the full original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript; any statement from Clavicular, a representative, or a publicist; the Polymarket clarification referenced in reporting; UMA transaction-level records showing the basis for the final outcome; and the source chain behind the Forbes characterization and the Domahhhh/Kick Champ leads. Those materials would let the council distinguish a real qualifying announcement from a rumor cycle.\n\nUntil that bridge is built, the plaintiff's strongest proof is that the market resolved Yes and some reporters described the controversy. The defense will show that the rule asks for more: a credible announcement, from the right source or a definitive credible-media consensus, about an existing partner pregnancy. The present packet identifies exactly why that has not yet been proven."}],"prior_council_votes":[{"member_id":"C1","rationale":"The record contains conflicting secondary reports and lacks any primary statement or definitive media consensus confirming a credible announcement; thus the proposition is not more likely than not proven.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C2","rationale":"The admitted record contains conflicting secondary reports and no preserved primary statement from Clavicular announcing an existing partner pregnancy. The preserved quotes describe future-oriented contest/stunt language, and Times of India explicitly states no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy. The final Yes resolution does not establish what evidence the resolver relied upon, and there is no definitive consensus of credible media as the rule requires.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C3","rationale":"The admitted record contains no primary statement confirming a pregnancy announcement and presents conflicting secondary reports, so the proposition is not proven by preponderance.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"}],"rebuttals":[{"phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the defense correctly identifies the record's weakest point: no original VOD, clip, or transcript is preserved. But the defense then treats that gap as dispositive. The market rule does not. It allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, and it also allows a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. That structure matters: the drafters anticipated that the council or resolver might have to decide from credible reporting, not only from a raw stream file.\n\nThe defense also understates the official final Yes. Plaintiff is not asking the council to treat market price as fact. PX-4 and the packet market record show more than price: a proposed Yes, dispute, proposed Yes, dispute, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0] and a resolved official state. That is the platform's resolution mechanism applying the same credibility rule after adversarial challenge. It is circumstantial, but it is unusually probative circumstantial evidence.\n\nThe defense says the Polymarket context describes future vows, a fertility-stack reveal, a dating-show/baby-mama proposal, and debunked girlfriend rumors. Yes, and plaintiff admitted that because unsupported viral reposts should be discounted. But that context does not erase the separate Forbes packet account: Forbes described the dispute as involving a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is not merely \"I want children someday\" language. It is the record's strongest description of an announcement that maps onto the rule.\n\nThe Times of India capture is adverse, but its force is narrower than the defense claims. It debunks the specific viral claim that Clavicular was expecting a first child with a girlfriend he met ten days earlier, and it discusses an out-of-context clip and a pregnancy-contest quote. It does not establish what the UMA resolver considered. It does not preserve the Polymarket clarification. It does not refute Forbes's specific characterization that the dispute concerned a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. And, like Forbes, it is secondary reporting rather than primary video.\n\nSo the evidentiary choice is not \"primary video versus nothing.\" It is whether the official final Yes, reached after two disputes under a rule that permits credible-media consensus, plus Forbes's affirmative characterization, outweighs adverse secondary reporting about a narrower viral rumor and the acknowledged absence of the raw source. On preponderance, plaintiff submits that it does.\n\nThe defense asks the council to infer that the official resolver accepted only a joke, stunt, or debunked rumor. That is possible, but it is not the better-supported inference on this record. The better-supported inference is that the official process credited a qualifying announcement or media-consensus path, even though the underlying primary artifact was not preserved in this packet. The gaps should reduce certainty; they should not convert a final official Yes and a favorable credible-media account into a No finding."}],"submitted_evidence":[{"evidence_id":"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab","size_bytes":3638,"source_description":"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.","source_url":"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026","title":"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market"},{"evidence_id":"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5","size_bytes":2189,"source_description":"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.","source_url":"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms","title":"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor"}],"surrebuttals":[{"phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. The defense is not arguing that a raw VOD is the only legally possible proof. The rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. But that is the point: the record does not contain such a consensus.\n\nWhat the record contains is one favorable Forbes characterization, adverse Times of India reporting that no video or Clavicular statement confirmed pregnancy, Hindustan Times and Express Tribune descriptions of a pregnancy-contest stunt, and an admitted gaps file saying the original stream, transcript, platform clarification, and UMA records are missing. That is not a definitive media consensus. It is a conflicted source chain.\n\nPlaintiff says TOI only debunks the narrower ten-day girlfriend rumor. But the proposition is itself about a partner pregnancy, and TOI’s captured text goes beyond narrow timing: no video confirms a pregnancy; no statement from Clavicular confirms it; the shared clip was out of context; the preserved quote was about wanting children and a pregnancy contest; the viral claim likely came from jokes and out-of-context clips. Those points directly undercut credibility and qualification under a rule that excludes jokes and noncredible announcements.\n\nPlaintiff also asks the council to treat final Yes after disputes as unusually probative. It is probative that the market resolved Yes. It is not probative enough to fill the missing basis for that resolution. The record does not show what the resolver considered, whether it relied on Forbes, the viral Kick Champ rumor, trader pressure, or something else, and it lacks the platform clarification Forbes reportedly said pointed No. Without the source chain, final Yes risks becoming circular proof: the announcement happened because the market resolved Yes, and the market resolved Yes because the announcement happened.\n\nThe preponderance question is not whether plaintiff’s theory is possible. It is whether the qualifying announcement is more likely than not on the admitted record. Given the conflicting media accounts, the absence of the underlying statement, and the admitted context of future vows, stunt framing, and debunked rumors, plaintiff has not crossed that line."}],"technical_reports":[{"phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","summary":"Before filing, plaintiff rescanned the record and evidence list. Target sources were official Polymarket/Gamma records, Forbes reporting, Times of India adverse reporting, the original Kick/VOD or clip, the Polymarket clarification, Domahhhh X thread, Kick Champ source, and UMA records. The Polymarket page was opened and the Gamma API was fetched with python3 urllib; the official rule, final Yes sequence, IDs, outcome prices, and context were preserved as PX-4. The Times of India article was opened and adverse fact-check text was preserved as PX-5. Forbes direct page capture was attempted by web open/search, but no stronger article text than the existing packet capture was obtained in time, so plaintiff relied on PX-3 rather than submitting a search snippet. No original VOD/transcript or full UMA voter record was captured this phase; those remain material gaps affecting weight.","title":"Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger"},{"phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","summary":"Defense rescanned the current record and evidence list, then read the two new plaintiff submissions in full. Source targets considered were the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, Clavicular/representative statements, the Polymarket clarification referenced by Forbes, UMA proposer/disputer/voter records, Forbes source chain, Domahhhh X thread, and Kick Champ source. Opening-phase searches found Forbes, Polymarket, Times of India, Hindustan Times, X Domahhhh, Inkl, Poprant/Indiatimes, Binance, and Lines leads; X thread opening produced no readable text, and no original video/transcript or representative statement was captured. No new defense evidence was submitted because the material defense sources are already admitted through the packet and plaintiff's TOI capture, while uncaptured leads remain unverified. Unresolved gaps remain the original statement, full context, platform clarification, and UMA rationale.","title":"Defense Source-Chain And Gap Ledger"}]}}},"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T07:50:07.017222578Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C4","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":885915,"role_id":"council","turn_number":12}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"get_case"}},"isError":false}
{"type":"message_start","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ytnPFq86t","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex09-20260630071703\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 885915\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex09-20260630071703\",\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"case\":{\"evidence_standard\":\"Preponderance of the evidence.\",\"member\":{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"model\":\"openrouter://mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5\",\"persona_filename\":\"personas/generic.md\"},\"opportunity\":{\"allowed_tools\":[\"submit_council_vote\"],\"id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"may_pass\":false,\"objective\":\"council vote by C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"role\":\"council\"},\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"proposition\":\"Between market creation on April 20, 2026, and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\",\"record\":{\"arguments\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff's case is strongest where it stays tied to the rule and the source chain. The proposition is not whether a child was born, and not whether every viral repost was accurate. It is whether Clavicular made a credible announcement, within the market window, that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\\n\\nThe official market evidence establishes the governing frame. The packet market page and the newly submitted official Polymarket/Gamma capture show the same rule: Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy; only credible announcements count; jokes do not; statements from Clavicular or representatives are the resolution source, with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting also permitted. The official source also shows the market was proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes again, disputed again, and finally resolved Yes. The Gamma extract fixes the market ID, condition ID, outcomes [Yes, No], outcomePrices [1,0], and resolver/closed-time fields. That is not mere trader gossip. It is the official resolution mechanism applying the very rule before this council.\\n\\nThe best explanation for that official Yes result appears in the case packet's secondary-reporting file. Forbes identified the dispute as being over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That description matters because it directly tracks the rule's central question: a statement by the covered person about having gotten a partner pregnant. Forbes also reported that the disagreement was binary: the market description and platform clarification were said to point No while the price pointed Yes, and the oracle had not closed the gap after two dispute rounds. The subsequent official record now shows the gap closed at Yes.\\n\\nThat sequence is plaintiff's preponderance case. The council can reasonably infer that the UMA/Polymarket final Yes did not arise from a vacuum. It followed a disputed process on a high-volume market whose rule allowed either the speaker's statements or a definitive credible-media consensus. The admitted record contains a credible financial-news account saying the dispute centered on a reported statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, and an official source showing the final resolver accepted Yes. On preponderance, those combined facts make a qualifying announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe defense is right that this proof has a missing primary artifact. The original livestream/VOD/transcript is not in the record. Nor is the full Polymarket clarification or transaction-level UMA voter record. The plaintiff does not ask the council to pretend otherwise. Those gaps reduce weight and make this a circumstantial/source-chain case, not a clean direct-video case.\\n\\nBut the gaps do not erase the official resolution and corroborating media account. The rule itself permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a preserved VOD is not automatically fatal. What matters is whether the admitted record, as a whole, makes the qualifying announcement more probable than the competing account that all of this was only a joke, contest, or rumor. The Forbes packet capture is the clearest pro-Yes secondary source; the official Polymarket/Gamma capture is the clearest official outcome source.\\n\\nThe plaintiff also submitted the Times of India fact-check because the council should see the strongest adverse source. It says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular, and it treats the viral claim as likely false or out of context. The live Polymarket context also cuts both ways: it describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama stunt, while acknowledging debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend pregnancy. That evidence undercuts any claim that every viral pregnancy story was credible.\\n\\nStill, TOI is not a primary record either. It is a fact-check of the rumor cycle, not the market-resolution record. It does not disprove that Clavicular made a qualifying announcement later accepted by the resolver or reflected in Forbes's account. It shows why the council should discount unsupported reposts and distinguish future-oriented fatherhood talk from an announcement of an existing pregnancy. Plaintiff's position survives that distinction because the favorable Forbes account is about a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, while the official resolver ultimately paid Yes under the same credibility standard.\\n\\nSo the plaintiff asks the council to give controlling weight to the official rule-and-resolution evidence, substantial corroborating weight to the Forbes secondary-reporting capture, and appropriate but not dispositive weight to the adverse TOI fact-check. The record is imperfect, but preponderance does not require certainty or medical confirmation. It requires the better answer. Here, the better answer is that the market's final Yes reflected a credible announcement or qualifying credible-media consensus that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy within the covered window.\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s case depends on converting a market result into proof of the underlying fact. The record does not support that conversion.\\n\\nThe rule requires a credible announcement that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. The official market evidence proves the wording, timing, dispute sequence, and final Yes outcome. It does not prove what Clavicular actually said. The packet’s official-source and primary-evidence files say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved and that the fact question remains dependent on locating the underlying stream, clip, transcript, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s new Polymarket/Gamma capture adds official details, but the added context cuts against plaintiff’s theory. It describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, a fertility-stack reveal, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama proposal involving 500 contestants. It separately describes “debunked rumors” of a girlfriend’s pregnancy after ten days. Those are not admissions that he and a partner were already expecting a baby. They are future intent, stunt framing, and rumor framing.\\n\\nThe strongest pro-Yes item is the Forbes excerpt in the secondary-reporting packet saying the dispute concerned a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But in this record Forbes is a summarized secondary account in an article about an oracle dispute, not the underlying video, transcript, source post, or representative statement. The same Forbes excerpt also reported that the market description and platform clarification said No while price said Yes, and that traders alleged the oracle had become a disinformation engine. That is not a clean source chain; it is a warning that market mechanics and trader incentives may have overtaken source proof.\\n\\nThe adverse evidence is more specific about the missing link. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, the actual preserved quote was future-oriented pregnancy-contest language, and the viral claim was false and likely came from jokes, out-of-context clips, and his content style. The secondary-reporting packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries match that: “I must have children,” “I must get children today,” and “I will be a dad in the next few months” were treated as a controversial proposal or stunt, not confirmation of an existing partner pregnancy.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a VOD is not automatically fatal. True, but the record does not show a definitive consensus. It shows conflict: Forbes characterizes the dispute one way; Times of India expressly debunks the girlfriend-pregnancy claim; Hindustan Times and Express Tribune frame the remarks as a contest/stunt; the packet says no primary source or Domahhhh thread text was located. A single favorable secondary characterization plus a final market resolution is not a definitive media consensus, especially where admitted adverse reporting directly denies confirmation.\\n\\nNor should the council give controlling weight to the final Yes state. The official resolver result proves that the market was resolved Yes. It does not reveal the evidence considered, the voters’ rationale, the proposer/disputer record, or whether the resolution rested on the same viral rumor now debunked in the record. The unresolved-gaps file expressly notes the missing UMA records and the missing Polymarket clarification Forbes said pointed No.\\n\\nOn preponderance, the better-supported finding is not that a qualifying announcement happened. It is that there was a viral controversy after market creation, built from future fatherhood talk, a pregnancy-contest stunt, social-media rumors, and a disputed market process that ultimately resolved Yes without preserving the basis. The proposition asks for a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy. The current record proves the controversy and the market result, but it does not prove that announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe defense therefore asks the council to find the proposition not proven on this record.\"}],\"closings\":[{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff does not ask you to decide that every viral post was true, or that the record proves the private medical fact of pregnancy. The proposition is narrower: whether Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the covered window.\\n\\nThe record proves the rule, the timing, and the official resolution. The market text required a credible announcement, excluded jokes, and allowed not only statements from Clavicular or representatives but also a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. The official Polymarket/Gamma evidence then shows proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes, disputed again, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0]. That is not a mere price chart. It is the official resolution process applying the same rule now before this council.\\n\\nThe record also contains the affirmative source-chain link. The secondary-reporting packet preserves Forbes's characterization that the dispute was over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is the key phrase in this case. It is not simply a desire to have children someday. It is a reported statement about having gotten a girl pregnant, which maps directly to the rule's pregnancy-announcement requirement. The final Yes resolution then confirms that the official process ultimately credited the Yes side despite disputes.\\n\\nThe defense's best point is real: the original VOD, transcript, Polymarket clarification, and UMA voter rationale are not in the record. That means the plaintiff's case is not direct-video proof. But preponderance does not demand perfect custody or certainty. It asks which inference is better supported by the admitted record.\\n\\nThe adverse record does not carry the defense over that line. The Times of India capture and the live Polymarket context warn against unsupported girlfriend-rumor reposts, out-of-context clips, future fatherhood talk, and stunt framing. Plaintiff accepts that warning. Those materials show why jokes and rumors should be discounted. They do not establish that the official resolver accepted a joke, and they do not erase Forbes's account of a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. They are secondary reports too; they are not the missing primary video.\\n\\nThe defense's theory requires a larger inference than plaintiff's. It asks you to conclude that, after two disputes, the official final Yes likely rested on nothing more than a noncredible rumor or stunt, even though the rule expressly excluded such material and even though Forbes described the dispute in terms of a pregnancy statement. That is possible, but on this record it is not the more probable account.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's account fits all of the admitted pieces: the rule allowed a credible announcement or credible-media consensus; Forbes reported the relevant announcement framing; the market underwent contested resolution; and the final official state paid Yes. The conflicting adverse reporting explains why the case was disputed and why the source chain is imperfect. It does not make No more likely than Yes.\\n\\nFor that reason, under the preponderance standard, the council should find that the proposition is proven.\"},{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the record leaves this case short of preponderance.\\n\\nThe plaintiff is right about one thing: the proposition is not whether a child was born or whether a pregnancy was medically true. The question is whether Clavicular made a credible qualifying announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. But the record still has to prove that announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe official market evidence proves the rule, the dates, the dispute sequence, and the final Yes state. It does not prove the underlying source. The case-packet official-source and primary-evidence files expressly say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved. The unresolved-gaps file identifies the same missing pieces: original livestream clip, VOD, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, and UMA proposer/disputer/voter records.\\n\\nThat matters because plaintiff’s case turns on a bridge it never fully builds. The bridge is one Forbes characterization that the dispute involved a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, plus the final Yes resolution. But the record does not preserve Forbes’s underlying source chain. And the same secondary-reporting packet records that Forbes described the market description and platform clarification as saying No, while price said Yes, and linked criticism of the oracle process. That is not a clean, independent confirmation of a qualifying announcement.\\n\\nThe contrary evidence is not just noise. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, and it identifies the actual preserved quote as future-oriented pregnancy-contest language. The packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries likewise frame the remarks as a contest or stunt: wanting children, needing children today, and being a dad in the next few months. Plaintiff’s own Polymarket/Gamma capture describes trader consensus as driven by public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, a dating-show/baby-mama stunt, and debunked girlfriend-pregnancy rumors. Those facts fit a rumor and stunt cycle at least as well as they fit a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. It does. But this record is not a consensus. It is a conflict: one favorable Forbes phrasing, adverse fact-checking, multiple contest/stunt accounts, and admitted missing source-chain material. A definitive consensus cannot be inferred from divided secondary reporting.\\n\\nPlaintiff also says the official Yes after disputes is unusually probative. It has some weight, but it cannot carry the burden by itself. The record does not show what the resolver considered or why it resolved Yes. Without the UMA rationale, source material, or platform clarification, final Yes is at risk of circular reasoning: using the market’s outcome to prove the fact that the market outcome was supposed to decide.\\n\\nThe defense is not asking the council to find that no rumor existed, or that no one ever thought Clavicular might make such an announcement. The defense is asking the council to apply the actual proposition and the preponderance standard. On this record, a qualifying credible announcement is not more likely than a nonqualifying mix of future fatherhood talk, a provocative contest proposal, out-of-context clips, and debunked viral claims.\\n\\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition not proven.\"}],\"evidence\":[{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407\",\"size_bytes\":1254,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"04/045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:34Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"size_bytes\":2189,\"source_description\":\"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.\",\"source_url\":\"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\",\"storage_name\":\"55/5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068\",\"size_bytes\":4343,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"79/795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"official-source-record.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0\",\"size_bytes\":1851,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"a7/a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"official-source-record.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"market-page.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5\",\"size_bytes\":2778,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"d1/d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"market-page.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:11Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"size_bytes\":3638,\"source_description\":\"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.\",\"source_url\":\"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\",\"storage_name\":\"f0/f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"primary-evidence.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94\",\"size_bytes\":1589,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"f8/f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"primary-evidence.txt\"}],\"exhibits\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"label\":\"PX-1 Market page packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\\n\\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRule text:\\n\\n\\u003e This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\\n\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\\n\\nEvent:\\n\\n- event id: 400878\\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: true\\n- event closed: true\\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\\n\\nMarket:\\n\\n- market id: 2037907\\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\\n- market closed: true\\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"PX-2 Official source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\n## Polymarket source\\n\\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\n\\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\\n\\n## Clavicular or representative statements\\n\\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\\n\\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\\n\\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\\n\\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\\n\\n## UMA / oracle source\\n\\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"PX-3 Secondary reporting packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"PX-4 Official Polymarket/Gamma merits capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"PX-5 Times of India adverse fact-check capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"PX-6 Record gaps packet file\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"label\":\"DX-1 Market rule and initial final-outcome packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\\n\\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRule text:\\n\\n\\u003e This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\\n\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\\n\\nEvent:\\n\\n- event id: 400878\\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: true\\n- event closed: true\\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\\n\\nMarket:\\n\\n- market id: 2037907\\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\\n- market closed: true\\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"DX-2 Official-source packet record showing missing primary statement and UMA detail\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\n## Polymarket source\\n\\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\n\\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\\n\\n## Clavicular or representative statements\\n\\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\\n\\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\\n\\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\\n\\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\\n\\n## UMA / oracle source\\n\\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence\",\"label\":\"DX-3 Primary-evidence packet assessment of missing underlying proof\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Primary evidence\\n\\n## Preserved primary/platform evidence\\n\\n- Polymarket market page: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Polymarket Gamma API event record: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Captured files: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt; source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json; source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\nThe official market rule requires a credible announcement by Clavicular that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy during the specified window.\\n\\n## Potential primary-source leads not locally preserved\\n\\n- Clavicular's Kick page or VODs: https://kick.com/clavicular/videos, referenced by Hindustan Times.\\n- Domahhhh's April 30 X thread about the oracle dispute: https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218, referenced by Forbes.\\n- JexTrade's April 29 X post about a large No buy, referenced by Forbes.\\n- @holy_moses7 posts claiming the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” referenced by Forbes.\\n- The viral Kick Champ post that Times of India says claimed Clavicular was “expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days ago.” The exact source URL was not captured.\\n\\n## Preliminary source assessment\\n\\nThe preserved primary evidence proves the contract wording and the platform's final Yes state. It does not itself prove that a qualifying credible announcement occurred. The fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"DX-4 Secondary-reporting conflict and adverse context\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"DX-5 Unresolved record gaps\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"DX-6 Plaintiff Polymarket/Gamma capture, including context about vows, stunt, and debunked rumors\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"DX-7 Plaintiff-submitted Times of India adverse fact-check\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"DX-S1 TOI fact-check on no confirming video or Clavicular statement\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"DX-S2 Conflicting secondary reporting and contest/stunt framing\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"DX-S3 Missing original statement, platform clarification, and UMA records\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"DX-S4 Official Polymarket/Gamma capture with market context\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"}],\"openings\":[{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, this case is about a narrow event definition, not about proving the private fact of a pregnancy to medical certainty. The proposition asks whether, after the April 20, 2026 market creation and before the stated deadline, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. Under the preponderance standard, the question is whether the better-supported reading of the available source chain is that a qualifying announcement occurred.\\n\\nThe present case packet already fixes the governing rule and the official market posture. The Polymarket page record states that the market resolves Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy, that only credible announcements qualify, that jokes do not suffice, and that statements from Clavicular or his representatives are the primary resolution source while a definitive consensus of credible media may also be considered. The same official-source packet records the platform/API state: the market went through proposed/disputed sequences and ultimately shows a final Yes outcome.\\n\\nThat matters, but it is not the whole case. A final Yes state is strong circumstantial and procedural evidence that the market's resolver accepted the event as satisfied, but by itself it does not show the exact words, tone, context, or credibility of the underlying announcement. The plaintiff's burden is therefore to connect that official Yes state to the source material that caused it.\\n\\nThe packet points to that connection. Forbes reported the dispute as turning on what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. Other reports described livestream remarks about wanting children or becoming a dad soon, and several sources frame the incident as a viral controversy. Those reports explain why the market moved and why the oracle dispute arose. They support the plaintiff's theory that there was, at minimum, a public announcement or reported announcement that the market treated as sufficient.\\n\\nThe defense will stress the same record's weaknesses. The packet does not yet preserve the original livestream clip, VOD, full transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification mentioned by Forbes, or UMA transaction-level record. The Times of India fact-check says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular; other reporting characterizes the comments as a contest, stunt, joke, or out-of-context viral content. Those are real weight issues because the rule expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes.\\n\\nSo the decisive factual questions are these: first, what exactly did Clavicular say, and was it about an existing partner pregnancy rather than a future desire, stunt, or contest? Second, did the statement occur after market creation? Third, did Clavicular or a representative make it, or did credible media reach the definitive consensus allowed by the rules? Fourth, does the Polymarket/UMA Yes resolution rest on that source chain or on speculation and trader pressure?\\n\\nThe plaintiff expects the later evidentiary phase to focus on the primary artifacts the packet identifies: the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, the Polymarket clarification, the Forbes source capture, the Domahhhh thread, any Kick Champ source, and UMA oracle records. If those materials show that Clavicular publicly stated that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the final Yes outcome and corroborating credible reporting should satisfy preponderance. If the best source instead shows only jokes, wishful remarks, a contest proposal, or unsupported reposts, the plaintiff's case would be materially weaker.\\n\\nFor opening purposes, the plaintiff's theory is disciplined: the official market record and secondary reporting make Yes the more plausible starting point, but the case should be decided by the preserved source chain, not by market price alone.\"},{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense position starts with the market rule itself. This case is not resolved by asking whether a rumor circulated, whether Polymarket ultimately showed a Yes outcome, or whether traders believed a provocative streamer had created controversy. The proposition requires proof, by a preponderance, that Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the relevant window.\\n\\nThe admitted packet proves some important background. The market page record fixes the contract language: only credible announcements qualify; jokes do not; the ordinary resolution source is statements from Clavicular or his representatives, with a definitive consensus of credible media as a possible secondary source. The same packet also shows the market was created on April 20, 2026 and later displayed a final Yes state after proposed and disputed resolution sequences. The defense does not need to pretend those facts are irrelevant. They explain why this dispute exists.\\n\\nBut they do not prove the proposition. The preserved primary/platform evidence is the Polymarket page and Gamma/API status material. It proves the rule and the platform result; it does not preserve the original livestream, VOD, clip, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, or UMA voter/proposer record that would show why the market ended Yes. The packet's own primary-evidence assessment says the fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\\nThat missing link matters because the secondary record is internally conflicted on the very element the plaintiff must prove. Forbes is favorable to plaintiff insofar as it describes a dispute over a streamer who allegedly told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But the Times of India fact-check, also in the packet, says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular. Other packet excerpts describe remarks about wanting children, being a dad in the next few months, or a proposed pregnancy contest. Those are not the same thing as announcing that he and a partner are already expecting a baby through pregnancy.\\n\\nThe defense theory is therefore straightforward: final Yes resolution is circumstantial evidence of market administration, not a substitute for the qualifying announcement required by the rule. A viral claim repeated through social media, a contest proposal, a future-oriented wish to have children, shock-content banter, or an out-of-context clip does not satisfy a rule that expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes. If plaintiff can later preserve the original source and it shows an unambiguous, credible statement by Clavicular or his representative that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the defense will have to confront it. On the current record, that source is absent.\\n\\nThe decisive evidence in later phases should be narrow: the full original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript; any statement from Clavicular, a representative, or a publicist; the Polymarket clarification referenced in reporting; UMA transaction-level records showing the basis for the final outcome; and the source chain behind the Forbes characterization and the Domahhhh/Kick Champ leads. Those materials would let the council distinguish a real qualifying announcement from a rumor cycle.\\n\\nUntil that bridge is built, the plaintiff's strongest proof is that the market resolved Yes and some reporters described the controversy. The defense will show that the rule asks for more: a credible announcement, from the right source or a definitive credible-media consensus, about an existing partner pregnancy. The present packet identifies exactly why that has not yet been proven.\"}],\"prior_council_votes\":[{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The record contains conflicting secondary reports and lacks any primary statement or definitive media consensus confirming a credible announcement; thus the proposition is not more likely than not proven.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record contains conflicting secondary reports and no preserved primary statement from Clavicular announcing an existing partner pregnancy. The preserved quotes describe future-oriented contest/stunt language, and Times of India explicitly states no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy. The final Yes resolution does not establish what evidence the resolver relied upon, and there is no definitive consensus of credible media as the rule requires.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record contains no primary statement confirming a pregnancy announcement and presents conflicting secondary reports, so the proposition is not proven by preponderance.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"}],\"rebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense correctly identifies the record's weakest point: no original VOD, clip, or transcript is preserved. But the defense then treats that gap as dispositive. The market rule does not. It allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, and it also allows a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. That structure matters: the drafters anticipated that the council or resolver might have to decide from credible reporting, not only from a raw stream file.\\n\\nThe defense also understates the official final Yes. Plaintiff is not asking the council to treat market price as fact. PX-4 and the packet market record show more than price: a proposed Yes, dispute, proposed Yes, dispute, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0] and a resolved official state. That is the platform's resolution mechanism applying the same credibility rule after adversarial challenge. It is circumstantial, but it is unusually probative circumstantial evidence.\\n\\nThe defense says the Polymarket context describes future vows, a fertility-stack reveal, a dating-show/baby-mama proposal, and debunked girlfriend rumors. Yes, and plaintiff admitted that because unsupported viral reposts should be discounted. But that context does not erase the separate Forbes packet account: Forbes described the dispute as involving a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is not merely \\\"I want children someday\\\" language. It is the record's strongest description of an announcement that maps onto the rule.\\n\\nThe Times of India capture is adverse, but its force is narrower than the defense claims. It debunks the specific viral claim that Clavicular was expecting a first child with a girlfriend he met ten days earlier, and it discusses an out-of-context clip and a pregnancy-contest quote. It does not establish what the UMA resolver considered. It does not preserve the Polymarket clarification. It does not refute Forbes's specific characterization that the dispute concerned a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. And, like Forbes, it is secondary reporting rather than primary video.\\n\\nSo the evidentiary choice is not \\\"primary video versus nothing.\\\" It is whether the official final Yes, reached after two disputes under a rule that permits credible-media consensus, plus Forbes's affirmative characterization, outweighs adverse secondary reporting about a narrower viral rumor and the acknowledged absence of the raw source. On preponderance, plaintiff submits that it does.\\n\\nThe defense asks the council to infer that the official resolver accepted only a joke, stunt, or debunked rumor. That is possible, but it is not the better-supported inference on this record. The better-supported inference is that the official process credited a qualifying announcement or media-consensus path, even though the underlying primary artifact was not preserved in this packet. The gaps should reduce certainty; they should not convert a final official Yes and a favorable credible-media account into a No finding.\"}],\"submitted_evidence\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"size_bytes\":3638,\"source_description\":\"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.\",\"source_url\":\"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\",\"title\":\"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"size_bytes\":2189,\"source_description\":\"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.\",\"source_url\":\"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\",\"title\":\"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\"}],\"surrebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. The defense is not arguing that a raw VOD is the only legally possible proof. The rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. But that is the point: the record does not contain such a consensus.\\n\\nWhat the record contains is one favorable Forbes characterization, adverse Times of India reporting that no video or Clavicular statement confirmed pregnancy, Hindustan Times and Express Tribune descriptions of a pregnancy-contest stunt, and an admitted gaps file saying the original stream, transcript, platform clarification, and UMA records are missing. That is not a definitive media consensus. It is a conflicted source chain.\\n\\nPlaintiff says TOI only debunks the narrower ten-day girlfriend rumor. But the proposition is itself about a partner pregnancy, and TOI’s captured text goes beyond narrow timing: no video confirms a pregnancy; no statement from Clavicular confirms it; the shared clip was out of context; the preserved quote was about wanting children and a pregnancy contest; the viral claim likely came from jokes and out-of-context clips. Those points directly undercut credibility and qualification under a rule that excludes jokes and noncredible announcements.\\n\\nPlaintiff also asks the council to treat final Yes after disputes as unusually probative. It is probative that the market resolved Yes. It is not probative enough to fill the missing basis for that resolution. The record does not show what the resolver considered, whether it relied on Forbes, the viral Kick Champ rumor, trader pressure, or something else, and it lacks the platform clarification Forbes reportedly said pointed No. Without the source chain, final Yes risks becoming circular proof: the announcement happened because the market resolved Yes, and the market resolved Yes because the announcement happened.\\n\\nThe preponderance question is not whether plaintiff’s theory is possible. It is whether the qualifying announcement is more likely than not on the admitted record. Given the conflicting media accounts, the absence of the underlying statement, and the admitted context of future vows, stunt framing, and debunked rumors, plaintiff has not crossed that line.\"}],\"technical_reports\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Before filing, plaintiff rescanned the record and evidence list. Target sources were official Polymarket/Gamma records, Forbes reporting, Times of India adverse reporting, the original Kick/VOD or clip, the Polymarket clarification, Domahhhh X thread, Kick Champ source, and UMA records. The Polymarket page was opened and the Gamma API was fetched with python3 urllib; the official rule, final Yes sequence, IDs, outcome prices, and context were preserved as PX-4. The Times of India article was opened and adverse fact-check text was preserved as PX-5. Forbes direct page capture was attempted by web open/search, but no stronger article text than the existing packet capture was obtained in time, so plaintiff relied on PX-3 rather than submitting a search snippet. No original VOD/transcript or full UMA voter record was captured this phase; those remain material gaps affecting weight.\",\"title\":\"Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"Defense rescanned the current record and evidence list, then read the two new plaintiff submissions in full. Source targets considered were the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, Clavicular/representative statements, the Polymarket clarification referenced by Forbes, UMA proposer/disputer/voter records, Forbes source chain, Domahhhh X thread, and Kick Champ source. Opening-phase searches found Forbes, Polymarket, Times of India, Hindustan Times, X Domahhhh, Inkl, Poprant/Indiatimes, Binance, and Lines leads; X thread opening produced no readable text, and no original video/transcript or representative statement was captured. No new defense evidence was submitted because the material defense sources are already admitted through the packet and plaintiff's TOI capture, while uncaptured leads remain unverified. Unresolved gaps remain the original statement, full context, platform clarification, and UMA rationale.\",\"title\":\"Defense Source-Chain And Gap Ledger\"}]}}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T07:50:07.017222578Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":885915,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex09-20260630071703\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 885915\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex09-20260630071703\",\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"case\":{\"evidence_standard\":\"Preponderance of the evidence.\",\"member\":{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"model\":\"openrouter://mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5\",\"persona_filename\":\"personas/generic.md\"},\"opportunity\":{\"allowed_tools\":[\"submit_council_vote\"],\"id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"may_pass\":false,\"objective\":\"council vote by C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"role\":\"council\"},\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"proposition\":\"Between market creation on April 20, 2026, and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\",\"record\":{\"arguments\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff's case is strongest where it stays tied to the rule and the source chain. The proposition is not whether a child was born, and not whether every viral repost was accurate. It is whether Clavicular made a credible announcement, within the market window, that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\\n\\nThe official market evidence establishes the governing frame. The packet market page and the newly submitted official Polymarket/Gamma capture show the same rule: Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy; only credible announcements count; jokes do not; statements from Clavicular or representatives are the resolution source, with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting also permitted. The official source also shows the market was proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes again, disputed again, and finally resolved Yes. The Gamma extract fixes the market ID, condition ID, outcomes [Yes, No], outcomePrices [1,0], and resolver/closed-time fields. That is not mere trader gossip. It is the official resolution mechanism applying the very rule before this council.\\n\\nThe best explanation for that official Yes result appears in the case packet's secondary-reporting file. Forbes identified the dispute as being over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That description matters because it directly tracks the rule's central question: a statement by the covered person about having gotten a partner pregnant. Forbes also reported that the disagreement was binary: the market description and platform clarification were said to point No while the price pointed Yes, and the oracle had not closed the gap after two dispute rounds. The subsequent official record now shows the gap closed at Yes.\\n\\nThat sequence is plaintiff's preponderance case. The council can reasonably infer that the UMA/Polymarket final Yes did not arise from a vacuum. It followed a disputed process on a high-volume market whose rule allowed either the speaker's statements or a definitive credible-media consensus. The admitted record contains a credible financial-news account saying the dispute centered on a reported statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, and an official source showing the final resolver accepted Yes. On preponderance, those combined facts make a qualifying announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe defense is right that this proof has a missing primary artifact. The original livestream/VOD/transcript is not in the record. Nor is the full Polymarket clarification or transaction-level UMA voter record. The plaintiff does not ask the council to pretend otherwise. Those gaps reduce weight and make this a circumstantial/source-chain case, not a clean direct-video case.\\n\\nBut the gaps do not erase the official resolution and corroborating media account. The rule itself permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a preserved VOD is not automatically fatal. What matters is whether the admitted record, as a whole, makes the qualifying announcement more probable than the competing account that all of this was only a joke, contest, or rumor. The Forbes packet capture is the clearest pro-Yes secondary source; the official Polymarket/Gamma capture is the clearest official outcome source.\\n\\nThe plaintiff also submitted the Times of India fact-check because the council should see the strongest adverse source. It says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular, and it treats the viral claim as likely false or out of context. The live Polymarket context also cuts both ways: it describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama stunt, while acknowledging debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend pregnancy. That evidence undercuts any claim that every viral pregnancy story was credible.\\n\\nStill, TOI is not a primary record either. It is a fact-check of the rumor cycle, not the market-resolution record. It does not disprove that Clavicular made a qualifying announcement later accepted by the resolver or reflected in Forbes's account. It shows why the council should discount unsupported reposts and distinguish future-oriented fatherhood talk from an announcement of an existing pregnancy. Plaintiff's position survives that distinction because the favorable Forbes account is about a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, while the official resolver ultimately paid Yes under the same credibility standard.\\n\\nSo the plaintiff asks the council to give controlling weight to the official rule-and-resolution evidence, substantial corroborating weight to the Forbes secondary-reporting capture, and appropriate but not dispositive weight to the adverse TOI fact-check. The record is imperfect, but preponderance does not require certainty or medical confirmation. It requires the better answer. Here, the better answer is that the market's final Yes reflected a credible announcement or qualifying credible-media consensus that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy within the covered window.\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s case depends on converting a market result into proof of the underlying fact. The record does not support that conversion.\\n\\nThe rule requires a credible announcement that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. The official market evidence proves the wording, timing, dispute sequence, and final Yes outcome. It does not prove what Clavicular actually said. The packet’s official-source and primary-evidence files say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved and that the fact question remains dependent on locating the underlying stream, clip, transcript, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s new Polymarket/Gamma capture adds official details, but the added context cuts against plaintiff’s theory. It describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, a fertility-stack reveal, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama proposal involving 500 contestants. It separately describes “debunked rumors” of a girlfriend’s pregnancy after ten days. Those are not admissions that he and a partner were already expecting a baby. They are future intent, stunt framing, and rumor framing.\\n\\nThe strongest pro-Yes item is the Forbes excerpt in the secondary-reporting packet saying the dispute concerned a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But in this record Forbes is a summarized secondary account in an article about an oracle dispute, not the underlying video, transcript, source post, or representative statement. The same Forbes excerpt also reported that the market description and platform clarification said No while price said Yes, and that traders alleged the oracle had become a disinformation engine. That is not a clean source chain; it is a warning that market mechanics and trader incentives may have overtaken source proof.\\n\\nThe adverse evidence is more specific about the missing link. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, the actual preserved quote was future-oriented pregnancy-contest language, and the viral claim was false and likely came from jokes, out-of-context clips, and his content style. The secondary-reporting packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries match that: “I must have children,” “I must get children today,” and “I will be a dad in the next few months” were treated as a controversial proposal or stunt, not confirmation of an existing partner pregnancy.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a VOD is not automatically fatal. True, but the record does not show a definitive consensus. It shows conflict: Forbes characterizes the dispute one way; Times of India expressly debunks the girlfriend-pregnancy claim; Hindustan Times and Express Tribune frame the remarks as a contest/stunt; the packet says no primary source or Domahhhh thread text was located. A single favorable secondary characterization plus a final market resolution is not a definitive media consensus, especially where admitted adverse reporting directly denies confirmation.\\n\\nNor should the council give controlling weight to the final Yes state. The official resolver result proves that the market was resolved Yes. It does not reveal the evidence considered, the voters’ rationale, the proposer/disputer record, or whether the resolution rested on the same viral rumor now debunked in the record. The unresolved-gaps file expressly notes the missing UMA records and the missing Polymarket clarification Forbes said pointed No.\\n\\nOn preponderance, the better-supported finding is not that a qualifying announcement happened. It is that there was a viral controversy after market creation, built from future fatherhood talk, a pregnancy-contest stunt, social-media rumors, and a disputed market process that ultimately resolved Yes without preserving the basis. The proposition asks for a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy. The current record proves the controversy and the market result, but it does not prove that announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe defense therefore asks the council to find the proposition not proven on this record.\"}],\"closings\":[{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff does not ask you to decide that every viral post was true, or that the record proves the private medical fact of pregnancy. The proposition is narrower: whether Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the covered window.\\n\\nThe record proves the rule, the timing, and the official resolution. The market text required a credible announcement, excluded jokes, and allowed not only statements from Clavicular or representatives but also a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. The official Polymarket/Gamma evidence then shows proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes, disputed again, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0]. That is not a mere price chart. It is the official resolution process applying the same rule now before this council.\\n\\nThe record also contains the affirmative source-chain link. The secondary-reporting packet preserves Forbes's characterization that the dispute was over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is the key phrase in this case. It is not simply a desire to have children someday. It is a reported statement about having gotten a girl pregnant, which maps directly to the rule's pregnancy-announcement requirement. The final Yes resolution then confirms that the official process ultimately credited the Yes side despite disputes.\\n\\nThe defense's best point is real: the original VOD, transcript, Polymarket clarification, and UMA voter rationale are not in the record. That means the plaintiff's case is not direct-video proof. But preponderance does not demand perfect custody or certainty. It asks which inference is better supported by the admitted record.\\n\\nThe adverse record does not carry the defense over that line. The Times of India capture and the live Polymarket context warn against unsupported girlfriend-rumor reposts, out-of-context clips, future fatherhood talk, and stunt framing. Plaintiff accepts that warning. Those materials show why jokes and rumors should be discounted. They do not establish that the official resolver accepted a joke, and they do not erase Forbes's account of a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. They are secondary reports too; they are not the missing primary video.\\n\\nThe defense's theory requires a larger inference than plaintiff's. It asks you to conclude that, after two disputes, the official final Yes likely rested on nothing more than a noncredible rumor or stunt, even though the rule expressly excluded such material and even though Forbes described the dispute in terms of a pregnancy statement. That is possible, but on this record it is not the more probable account.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's account fits all of the admitted pieces: the rule allowed a credible announcement or credible-media consensus; Forbes reported the relevant announcement framing; the market underwent contested resolution; and the final official state paid Yes. The conflicting adverse reporting explains why the case was disputed and why the source chain is imperfect. It does not make No more likely than Yes.\\n\\nFor that reason, under the preponderance standard, the council should find that the proposition is proven.\"},{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the record leaves this case short of preponderance.\\n\\nThe plaintiff is right about one thing: the proposition is not whether a child was born or whether a pregnancy was medically true. The question is whether Clavicular made a credible qualifying announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. But the record still has to prove that announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe official market evidence proves the rule, the dates, the dispute sequence, and the final Yes state. It does not prove the underlying source. The case-packet official-source and primary-evidence files expressly say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved. The unresolved-gaps file identifies the same missing pieces: original livestream clip, VOD, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, and UMA proposer/disputer/voter records.\\n\\nThat matters because plaintiff’s case turns on a bridge it never fully builds. The bridge is one Forbes characterization that the dispute involved a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, plus the final Yes resolution. But the record does not preserve Forbes’s underlying source chain. And the same secondary-reporting packet records that Forbes described the market description and platform clarification as saying No, while price said Yes, and linked criticism of the oracle process. That is not a clean, independent confirmation of a qualifying announcement.\\n\\nThe contrary evidence is not just noise. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, and it identifies the actual preserved quote as future-oriented pregnancy-contest language. The packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries likewise frame the remarks as a contest or stunt: wanting children, needing children today, and being a dad in the next few months. Plaintiff’s own Polymarket/Gamma capture describes trader consensus as driven by public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, a dating-show/baby-mama stunt, and debunked girlfriend-pregnancy rumors. Those facts fit a rumor and stunt cycle at least as well as they fit a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. It does. But this record is not a consensus. It is a conflict: one favorable Forbes phrasing, adverse fact-checking, multiple contest/stunt accounts, and admitted missing source-chain material. A definitive consensus cannot be inferred from divided secondary reporting.\\n\\nPlaintiff also says the official Yes after disputes is unusually probative. It has some weight, but it cannot carry the burden by itself. The record does not show what the resolver considered or why it resolved Yes. Without the UMA rationale, source material, or platform clarification, final Yes is at risk of circular reasoning: using the market’s outcome to prove the fact that the market outcome was supposed to decide.\\n\\nThe defense is not asking the council to find that no rumor existed, or that no one ever thought Clavicular might make such an announcement. The defense is asking the council to apply the actual proposition and the preponderance standard. On this record, a qualifying credible announcement is not more likely than a nonqualifying mix of future fatherhood talk, a provocative contest proposal, out-of-context clips, and debunked viral claims.\\n\\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition not proven.\"}],\"evidence\":[{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407\",\"size_bytes\":1254,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"04/045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:34Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"size_bytes\":2189,\"source_description\":\"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.\",\"source_url\":\"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\",\"storage_name\":\"55/5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068\",\"size_bytes\":4343,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"79/795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"official-source-record.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0\",\"size_bytes\":1851,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"a7/a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"official-source-record.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"market-page.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5\",\"size_bytes\":2778,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"d1/d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"market-page.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:11Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"size_bytes\":3638,\"source_description\":\"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.\",\"source_url\":\"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\",\"storage_name\":\"f0/f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"primary-evidence.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94\",\"size_bytes\":1589,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"f8/f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"primary-evidence.txt\"}],\"exhibits\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"label\":\"PX-1 Market page packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\\n\\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRule text:\\n\\n\\u003e This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\\n\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\\n\\nEvent:\\n\\n- event id: 400878\\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: true\\n- event closed: true\\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\\n\\nMarket:\\n\\n- market id: 2037907\\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\\n- market closed: true\\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"PX-2 Official source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\n## Polymarket source\\n\\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\n\\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\\n\\n## Clavicular or representative statements\\n\\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\\n\\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\\n\\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\\n\\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\\n\\n## UMA / oracle source\\n\\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"PX-3 Secondary reporting packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"PX-4 Official Polymarket/Gamma merits capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"PX-5 Times of India adverse fact-check capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"PX-6 Record gaps packet file\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"label\":\"DX-1 Market rule and initial final-outcome packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\\n\\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRule text:\\n\\n\\u003e This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\\n\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\\n\\nEvent:\\n\\n- event id: 400878\\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: true\\n- event closed: true\\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\\n\\nMarket:\\n\\n- market id: 2037907\\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\\n- market closed: true\\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"DX-2 Official-source packet record showing missing primary statement and UMA detail\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\n## Polymarket source\\n\\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\n\\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\\n\\n## Clavicular or representative statements\\n\\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\\n\\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\\n\\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\\n\\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\\n\\n## UMA / oracle source\\n\\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence\",\"label\":\"DX-3 Primary-evidence packet assessment of missing underlying proof\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Primary evidence\\n\\n## Preserved primary/platform evidence\\n\\n- Polymarket market page: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Polymarket Gamma API event record: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Captured files: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt; source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json; source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\nThe official market rule requires a credible announcement by Clavicular that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy during the specified window.\\n\\n## Potential primary-source leads not locally preserved\\n\\n- Clavicular's Kick page or VODs: https://kick.com/clavicular/videos, referenced by Hindustan Times.\\n- Domahhhh's April 30 X thread about the oracle dispute: https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218, referenced by Forbes.\\n- JexTrade's April 29 X post about a large No buy, referenced by Forbes.\\n- @holy_moses7 posts claiming the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” referenced by Forbes.\\n- The viral Kick Champ post that Times of India says claimed Clavicular was “expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days ago.” The exact source URL was not captured.\\n\\n## Preliminary source assessment\\n\\nThe preserved primary evidence proves the contract wording and the platform's final Yes state. It does not itself prove that a qualifying credible announcement occurred. The fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"DX-4 Secondary-reporting conflict and adverse context\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"DX-5 Unresolved record gaps\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"DX-6 Plaintiff Polymarket/Gamma capture, including context about vows, stunt, and debunked rumors\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"DX-7 Plaintiff-submitted Times of India adverse fact-check\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"DX-S1 TOI fact-check on no confirming video or Clavicular statement\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"DX-S2 Conflicting secondary reporting and contest/stunt framing\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"DX-S3 Missing original statement, platform clarification, and UMA records\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"DX-S4 Official Polymarket/Gamma capture with market context\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"}],\"openings\":[{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, this case is about a narrow event definition, not about proving the private fact of a pregnancy to medical certainty. The proposition asks whether, after the April 20, 2026 market creation and before the stated deadline, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. Under the preponderance standard, the question is whether the better-supported reading of the available source chain is that a qualifying announcement occurred.\\n\\nThe present case packet already fixes the governing rule and the official market posture. The Polymarket page record states that the market resolves Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy, that only credible announcements qualify, that jokes do not suffice, and that statements from Clavicular or his representatives are the primary resolution source while a definitive consensus of credible media may also be considered. The same official-source packet records the platform/API state: the market went through proposed/disputed sequences and ultimately shows a final Yes outcome.\\n\\nThat matters, but it is not the whole case. A final Yes state is strong circumstantial and procedural evidence that the market's resolver accepted the event as satisfied, but by itself it does not show the exact words, tone, context, or credibility of the underlying announcement. The plaintiff's burden is therefore to connect that official Yes state to the source material that caused it.\\n\\nThe packet points to that connection. Forbes reported the dispute as turning on what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. Other reports described livestream remarks about wanting children or becoming a dad soon, and several sources frame the incident as a viral controversy. Those reports explain why the market moved and why the oracle dispute arose. They support the plaintiff's theory that there was, at minimum, a public announcement or reported announcement that the market treated as sufficient.\\n\\nThe defense will stress the same record's weaknesses. The packet does not yet preserve the original livestream clip, VOD, full transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification mentioned by Forbes, or UMA transaction-level record. The Times of India fact-check says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular; other reporting characterizes the comments as a contest, stunt, joke, or out-of-context viral content. Those are real weight issues because the rule expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes.\\n\\nSo the decisive factual questions are these: first, what exactly did Clavicular say, and was it about an existing partner pregnancy rather than a future desire, stunt, or contest? Second, did the statement occur after market creation? Third, did Clavicular or a representative make it, or did credible media reach the definitive consensus allowed by the rules? Fourth, does the Polymarket/UMA Yes resolution rest on that source chain or on speculation and trader pressure?\\n\\nThe plaintiff expects the later evidentiary phase to focus on the primary artifacts the packet identifies: the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, the Polymarket clarification, the Forbes source capture, the Domahhhh thread, any Kick Champ source, and UMA oracle records. If those materials show that Clavicular publicly stated that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the final Yes outcome and corroborating credible reporting should satisfy preponderance. If the best source instead shows only jokes, wishful remarks, a contest proposal, or unsupported reposts, the plaintiff's case would be materially weaker.\\n\\nFor opening purposes, the plaintiff's theory is disciplined: the official market record and secondary reporting make Yes the more plausible starting point, but the case should be decided by the preserved source chain, not by market price alone.\"},{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense position starts with the market rule itself. This case is not resolved by asking whether a rumor circulated, whether Polymarket ultimately showed a Yes outcome, or whether traders believed a provocative streamer had created controversy. The proposition requires proof, by a preponderance, that Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the relevant window.\\n\\nThe admitted packet proves some important background. The market page record fixes the contract language: only credible announcements qualify; jokes do not; the ordinary resolution source is statements from Clavicular or his representatives, with a definitive consensus of credible media as a possible secondary source. The same packet also shows the market was created on April 20, 2026 and later displayed a final Yes state after proposed and disputed resolution sequences. The defense does not need to pretend those facts are irrelevant. They explain why this dispute exists.\\n\\nBut they do not prove the proposition. The preserved primary/platform evidence is the Polymarket page and Gamma/API status material. It proves the rule and the platform result; it does not preserve the original livestream, VOD, clip, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, or UMA voter/proposer record that would show why the market ended Yes. The packet's own primary-evidence assessment says the fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\\nThat missing link matters because the secondary record is internally conflicted on the very element the plaintiff must prove. Forbes is favorable to plaintiff insofar as it describes a dispute over a streamer who allegedly told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But the Times of India fact-check, also in the packet, says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular. Other packet excerpts describe remarks about wanting children, being a dad in the next few months, or a proposed pregnancy contest. Those are not the same thing as announcing that he and a partner are already expecting a baby through pregnancy.\\n\\nThe defense theory is therefore straightforward: final Yes resolution is circumstantial evidence of market administration, not a substitute for the qualifying announcement required by the rule. A viral claim repeated through social media, a contest proposal, a future-oriented wish to have children, shock-content banter, or an out-of-context clip does not satisfy a rule that expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes. If plaintiff can later preserve the original source and it shows an unambiguous, credible statement by Clavicular or his representative that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the defense will have to confront it. On the current record, that source is absent.\\n\\nThe decisive evidence in later phases should be narrow: the full original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript; any statement from Clavicular, a representative, or a publicist; the Polymarket clarification referenced in reporting; UMA transaction-level records showing the basis for the final outcome; and the source chain behind the Forbes characterization and the Domahhhh/Kick Champ leads. Those materials would let the council distinguish a real qualifying announcement from a rumor cycle.\\n\\nUntil that bridge is built, the plaintiff's strongest proof is that the market resolved Yes and some reporters described the controversy. The defense will show that the rule asks for more: a credible announcement, from the right source or a definitive credible-media consensus, about an existing partner pregnancy. The present packet identifies exactly why that has not yet been proven.\"}],\"prior_council_votes\":[{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The record contains conflicting secondary reports and lacks any primary statement or definitive media consensus confirming a credible announcement; thus the proposition is not more likely than not proven.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record contains conflicting secondary reports and no preserved primary statement from Clavicular announcing an existing partner pregnancy. The preserved quotes describe future-oriented contest/stunt language, and Times of India explicitly states no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy. The final Yes resolution does not establish what evidence the resolver relied upon, and there is no definitive consensus of credible media as the rule requires.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record contains no primary statement confirming a pregnancy announcement and presents conflicting secondary reports, so the proposition is not proven by preponderance.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"}],\"rebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense correctly identifies the record's weakest point: no original VOD, clip, or transcript is preserved. But the defense then treats that gap as dispositive. The market rule does not. It allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, and it also allows a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. That structure matters: the drafters anticipated that the council or resolver might have to decide from credible reporting, not only from a raw stream file.\\n\\nThe defense also understates the official final Yes. Plaintiff is not asking the council to treat market price as fact. PX-4 and the packet market record show more than price: a proposed Yes, dispute, proposed Yes, dispute, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0] and a resolved official state. That is the platform's resolution mechanism applying the same credibility rule after adversarial challenge. It is circumstantial, but it is unusually probative circumstantial evidence.\\n\\nThe defense says the Polymarket context describes future vows, a fertility-stack reveal, a dating-show/baby-mama proposal, and debunked girlfriend rumors. Yes, and plaintiff admitted that because unsupported viral reposts should be discounted. But that context does not erase the separate Forbes packet account: Forbes described the dispute as involving a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is not merely \\\"I want children someday\\\" language. It is the record's strongest description of an announcement that maps onto the rule.\\n\\nThe Times of India capture is adverse, but its force is narrower than the defense claims. It debunks the specific viral claim that Clavicular was expecting a first child with a girlfriend he met ten days earlier, and it discusses an out-of-context clip and a pregnancy-contest quote. It does not establish what the UMA resolver considered. It does not preserve the Polymarket clarification. It does not refute Forbes's specific characterization that the dispute concerned a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. And, like Forbes, it is secondary reporting rather than primary video.\\n\\nSo the evidentiary choice is not \\\"primary video versus nothing.\\\" It is whether the official final Yes, reached after two disputes under a rule that permits credible-media consensus, plus Forbes's affirmative characterization, outweighs adverse secondary reporting about a narrower viral rumor and the acknowledged absence of the raw source. On preponderance, plaintiff submits that it does.\\n\\nThe defense asks the council to infer that the official resolver accepted only a joke, stunt, or debunked rumor. That is possible, but it is not the better-supported inference on this record. The better-supported inference is that the official process credited a qualifying announcement or media-consensus path, even though the underlying primary artifact was not preserved in this packet. The gaps should reduce certainty; they should not convert a final official Yes and a favorable credible-media account into a No finding.\"}],\"submitted_evidence\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"size_bytes\":3638,\"source_description\":\"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.\",\"source_url\":\"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\",\"title\":\"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"size_bytes\":2189,\"source_description\":\"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.\",\"source_url\":\"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\",\"title\":\"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\"}],\"surrebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. The defense is not arguing that a raw VOD is the only legally possible proof. The rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. But that is the point: the record does not contain such a consensus.\\n\\nWhat the record contains is one favorable Forbes characterization, adverse Times of India reporting that no video or Clavicular statement confirmed pregnancy, Hindustan Times and Express Tribune descriptions of a pregnancy-contest stunt, and an admitted gaps file saying the original stream, transcript, platform clarification, and UMA records are missing. That is not a definitive media consensus. It is a conflicted source chain.\\n\\nPlaintiff says TOI only debunks the narrower ten-day girlfriend rumor. But the proposition is itself about a partner pregnancy, and TOI’s captured text goes beyond narrow timing: no video confirms a pregnancy; no statement from Clavicular confirms it; the shared clip was out of context; the preserved quote was about wanting children and a pregnancy contest; the viral claim likely came from jokes and out-of-context clips. Those points directly undercut credibility and qualification under a rule that excludes jokes and noncredible announcements.\\n\\nPlaintiff also asks the council to treat final Yes after disputes as unusually probative. It is probative that the market resolved Yes. It is not probative enough to fill the missing basis for that resolution. The record does not show what the resolver considered, whether it relied on Forbes, the viral Kick Champ rumor, trader pressure, or something else, and it lacks the platform clarification Forbes reportedly said pointed No. Without the source chain, final Yes risks becoming circular proof: the announcement happened because the market resolved Yes, and the market resolved Yes because the announcement happened.\\n\\nThe preponderance question is not whether plaintiff’s theory is possible. It is whether the qualifying announcement is more likely than not on the admitted record. Given the conflicting media accounts, the absence of the underlying statement, and the admitted context of future vows, stunt framing, and debunked rumors, plaintiff has not crossed that line.\"}],\"technical_reports\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Before filing, plaintiff rescanned the record and evidence list. Target sources were official Polymarket/Gamma records, Forbes reporting, Times of India adverse reporting, the original Kick/VOD or clip, the Polymarket clarification, Domahhhh X thread, Kick Champ source, and UMA records. The Polymarket page was opened and the Gamma API was fetched with python3 urllib; the official rule, final Yes sequence, IDs, outcome prices, and context were preserved as PX-4. The Times of India article was opened and adverse fact-check text was preserved as PX-5. Forbes direct page capture was attempted by web open/search, but no stronger article text than the existing packet capture was obtained in time, so plaintiff relied on PX-3 rather than submitting a search snippet. No original VOD/transcript or full UMA voter record was captured this phase; those remain material gaps affecting weight.\",\"title\":\"Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"Defense rescanned the current record and evidence list, then read the two new plaintiff submissions in full. Source targets considered were the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, Clavicular/representative statements, the Polymarket clarification referenced by Forbes, UMA proposer/disputer/voter records, Forbes source chain, Domahhhh X thread, and Kick Champ source. Opening-phase searches found Forbes, Polymarket, Times of India, Hindustan Times, X Domahhhh, Inkl, Poprant/Indiatimes, Binance, and Lines leads; X thread opening produced no readable text, and no original video/transcript or representative statement was captured. No new defense evidence was submitted because the material defense sources are already admitted through the packet and plaintiff's TOI capture, while uncaptured leads remain unverified. Unresolved gaps remain the original statement, full context, platform clarification, and UMA rationale.\",\"title\":\"Defense Source-Chain And Gap Ledger\"}]}}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T07:50:07.017222578Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":885915,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12}}"}],"structuredContent":{"case_id":"arb-ex09-20260630071703","member_id":"C4","ok":true,"result":{"case":{"evidence_standard":"Preponderance of the evidence.","member":{"member_id":"C4","model":"openrouter://mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5","persona_filename":"personas/generic.md"},"opportunity":{"allowed_tools":["submit_council_vote"],"id":"deliberation:1:C4","may_pass":false,"objective":"council vote by C4","phase":"deliberation","role":"council"},"phase":"deliberation","proposition":"Between market creation on April 20, 2026, and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.","record":{"arguments":[{"phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the plaintiff's case is strongest where it stays tied to the rule and the source chain. The proposition is not whether a child was born, and not whether every viral repost was accurate. It is whether Clavicular made a credible announcement, within the market window, that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\n\nThe official market evidence establishes the governing frame. The packet market page and the newly submitted official Polymarket/Gamma capture show the same rule: Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy; only credible announcements count; jokes do not; statements from Clavicular or representatives are the resolution source, with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting also permitted. The official source also shows the market was proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes again, disputed again, and finally resolved Yes. The Gamma extract fixes the market ID, condition ID, outcomes [Yes, No], outcomePrices [1,0], and resolver/closed-time fields. That is not mere trader gossip. It is the official resolution mechanism applying the very rule before this council.\n\nThe best explanation for that official Yes result appears in the case packet's secondary-reporting file. Forbes identified the dispute as being over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That description matters because it directly tracks the rule's central question: a statement by the covered person about having gotten a partner pregnant. Forbes also reported that the disagreement was binary: the market description and platform clarification were said to point No while the price pointed Yes, and the oracle had not closed the gap after two dispute rounds. The subsequent official record now shows the gap closed at Yes.\n\nThat sequence is plaintiff's preponderance case. The council can reasonably infer that the UMA/Polymarket final Yes did not arise from a vacuum. It followed a disputed process on a high-volume market whose rule allowed either the speaker's statements or a definitive credible-media consensus. The admitted record contains a credible financial-news account saying the dispute centered on a reported statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, and an official source showing the final resolver accepted Yes. On preponderance, those combined facts make a qualifying announcement more likely than not.\n\nThe defense is right that this proof has a missing primary artifact. The original livestream/VOD/transcript is not in the record. Nor is the full Polymarket clarification or transaction-level UMA voter record. The plaintiff does not ask the council to pretend otherwise. Those gaps reduce weight and make this a circumstantial/source-chain case, not a clean direct-video case.\n\nBut the gaps do not erase the official resolution and corroborating media account. The rule itself permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a preserved VOD is not automatically fatal. What matters is whether the admitted record, as a whole, makes the qualifying announcement more probable than the competing account that all of this was only a joke, contest, or rumor. The Forbes packet capture is the clearest pro-Yes secondary source; the official Polymarket/Gamma capture is the clearest official outcome source.\n\nThe plaintiff also submitted the Times of India fact-check because the council should see the strongest adverse source. It says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular, and it treats the viral claim as likely false or out of context. The live Polymarket context also cuts both ways: it describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama stunt, while acknowledging debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend pregnancy. That evidence undercuts any claim that every viral pregnancy story was credible.\n\nStill, TOI is not a primary record either. It is a fact-check of the rumor cycle, not the market-resolution record. It does not disprove that Clavicular made a qualifying announcement later accepted by the resolver or reflected in Forbes's account. It shows why the council should discount unsupported reposts and distinguish future-oriented fatherhood talk from an announcement of an existing pregnancy. Plaintiff's position survives that distinction because the favorable Forbes account is about a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, while the official resolver ultimately paid Yes under the same credibility standard.\n\nSo the plaintiff asks the council to give controlling weight to the official rule-and-resolution evidence, substantial corroborating weight to the Forbes secondary-reporting capture, and appropriate but not dispositive weight to the adverse TOI fact-check. The record is imperfect, but preponderance does not require certainty or medical confirmation. It requires the better answer. Here, the better answer is that the market's final Yes reflected a credible announcement or qualifying credible-media consensus that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy within the covered window."},{"phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, plaintiff’s case depends on converting a market result into proof of the underlying fact. The record does not support that conversion.\n\nThe rule requires a credible announcement that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. The official market evidence proves the wording, timing, dispute sequence, and final Yes outcome. It does not prove what Clavicular actually said. The packet’s official-source and primary-evidence files say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved and that the fact question remains dependent on locating the underlying stream, clip, transcript, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\n\nPlaintiff’s new Polymarket/Gamma capture adds official details, but the added context cuts against plaintiff’s theory. It describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, a fertility-stack reveal, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama proposal involving 500 contestants. It separately describes “debunked rumors” of a girlfriend’s pregnancy after ten days. Those are not admissions that he and a partner were already expecting a baby. They are future intent, stunt framing, and rumor framing.\n\nThe strongest pro-Yes item is the Forbes excerpt in the secondary-reporting packet saying the dispute concerned a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But in this record Forbes is a summarized secondary account in an article about an oracle dispute, not the underlying video, transcript, source post, or representative statement. The same Forbes excerpt also reported that the market description and platform clarification said No while price said Yes, and that traders alleged the oracle had become a disinformation engine. That is not a clean source chain; it is a warning that market mechanics and trader incentives may have overtaken source proof.\n\nThe adverse evidence is more specific about the missing link. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, the actual preserved quote was future-oriented pregnancy-contest language, and the viral claim was false and likely came from jokes, out-of-context clips, and his content style. The secondary-reporting packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries match that: “I must have children,” “I must get children today,” and “I will be a dad in the next few months” were treated as a controversial proposal or stunt, not confirmation of an existing partner pregnancy.\n\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a VOD is not automatically fatal. True, but the record does not show a definitive consensus. It shows conflict: Forbes characterizes the dispute one way; Times of India expressly debunks the girlfriend-pregnancy claim; Hindustan Times and Express Tribune frame the remarks as a contest/stunt; the packet says no primary source or Domahhhh thread text was located. A single favorable secondary characterization plus a final market resolution is not a definitive media consensus, especially where admitted adverse reporting directly denies confirmation.\n\nNor should the council give controlling weight to the final Yes state. The official resolver result proves that the market was resolved Yes. It does not reveal the evidence considered, the voters’ rationale, the proposer/disputer record, or whether the resolution rested on the same viral rumor now debunked in the record. The unresolved-gaps file expressly notes the missing UMA records and the missing Polymarket clarification Forbes said pointed No.\n\nOn preponderance, the better-supported finding is not that a qualifying announcement happened. It is that there was a viral controversy after market creation, built from future fatherhood talk, a pregnancy-contest stunt, social-media rumors, and a disputed market process that ultimately resolved Yes without preserving the basis. The proposition asks for a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy. The current record proves the controversy and the market result, but it does not prove that announcement more likely than not.\n\nThe defense therefore asks the council to find the proposition not proven on this record."}],"closings":[{"phase":"closings","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the plaintiff does not ask you to decide that every viral post was true, or that the record proves the private medical fact of pregnancy. The proposition is narrower: whether Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the covered window.\n\nThe record proves the rule, the timing, and the official resolution. The market text required a credible announcement, excluded jokes, and allowed not only statements from Clavicular or representatives but also a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. The official Polymarket/Gamma evidence then shows proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes, disputed again, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0]. That is not a mere price chart. It is the official resolution process applying the same rule now before this council.\n\nThe record also contains the affirmative source-chain link. The secondary-reporting packet preserves Forbes's characterization that the dispute was over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is the key phrase in this case. It is not simply a desire to have children someday. It is a reported statement about having gotten a girl pregnant, which maps directly to the rule's pregnancy-announcement requirement. The final Yes resolution then confirms that the official process ultimately credited the Yes side despite disputes.\n\nThe defense's best point is real: the original VOD, transcript, Polymarket clarification, and UMA voter rationale are not in the record. That means the plaintiff's case is not direct-video proof. But preponderance does not demand perfect custody or certainty. It asks which inference is better supported by the admitted record.\n\nThe adverse record does not carry the defense over that line. The Times of India capture and the live Polymarket context warn against unsupported girlfriend-rumor reposts, out-of-context clips, future fatherhood talk, and stunt framing. Plaintiff accepts that warning. Those materials show why jokes and rumors should be discounted. They do not establish that the official resolver accepted a joke, and they do not erase Forbes's account of a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. They are secondary reports too; they are not the missing primary video.\n\nThe defense's theory requires a larger inference than plaintiff's. It asks you to conclude that, after two disputes, the official final Yes likely rested on nothing more than a noncredible rumor or stunt, even though the rule expressly excluded such material and even though Forbes described the dispute in terms of a pregnancy statement. That is possible, but on this record it is not the more probable account.\n\nThe plaintiff's account fits all of the admitted pieces: the rule allowed a credible announcement or credible-media consensus; Forbes reported the relevant announcement framing; the market underwent contested resolution; and the final official state paid Yes. The conflicting adverse reporting explains why the case was disputed and why the source chain is imperfect. It does not make No more likely than Yes.\n\nFor that reason, under the preponderance standard, the council should find that the proposition is proven."},{"phase":"closings","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the record leaves this case short of preponderance.\n\nThe plaintiff is right about one thing: the proposition is not whether a child was born or whether a pregnancy was medically true. The question is whether Clavicular made a credible qualifying announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. But the record still has to prove that announcement more likely than not.\n\nThe official market evidence proves the rule, the dates, the dispute sequence, and the final Yes state. It does not prove the underlying source. The case-packet official-source and primary-evidence files expressly say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved. The unresolved-gaps file identifies the same missing pieces: original livestream clip, VOD, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, and UMA proposer/disputer/voter records.\n\nThat matters because plaintiff’s case turns on a bridge it never fully builds. The bridge is one Forbes characterization that the dispute involved a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, plus the final Yes resolution. But the record does not preserve Forbes’s underlying source chain. And the same secondary-reporting packet records that Forbes described the market description and platform clarification as saying No, while price said Yes, and linked criticism of the oracle process. That is not a clean, independent confirmation of a qualifying announcement.\n\nThe contrary evidence is not just noise. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, and it identifies the actual preserved quote as future-oriented pregnancy-contest language. The packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries likewise frame the remarks as a contest or stunt: wanting children, needing children today, and being a dad in the next few months. Plaintiff’s own Polymarket/Gamma capture describes trader consensus as driven by public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, a dating-show/baby-mama stunt, and debunked girlfriend-pregnancy rumors. Those facts fit a rumor and stunt cycle at least as well as they fit a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy.\n\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. It does. But this record is not a consensus. It is a conflict: one favorable Forbes phrasing, adverse fact-checking, multiple contest/stunt accounts, and admitted missing source-chain material. A definitive consensus cannot be inferred from divided secondary reporting.\n\nPlaintiff also says the official Yes after disputes is unusually probative. It has some weight, but it cannot carry the burden by itself. The record does not show what the resolver considered or why it resolved Yes. Without the UMA rationale, source material, or platform clarification, final Yes is at risk of circular reasoning: using the market’s outcome to prove the fact that the market outcome was supposed to decide.\n\nThe defense is not asking the council to find that no rumor existed, or that no one ever thought Clavicular might make such an announcement. The defense is asking the council to apply the actual proposition and the preponderance standard. On this record, a qualifying credible announcement is not more likely than a nonqualifying mix of future fatherhood talk, a provocative contest proposal, out-of-context clips, and debunked viral claims.\n\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition not proven."}],"evidence":[{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z","evidence_id":"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"unresolved-record-gaps.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407","size_bytes":1254,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"04/045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"unresolved-record-gaps.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:25:34Z","evidence_id":"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z","sha256":"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5","size_bytes":2189,"source_description":"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.","source_url":"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms","storage_name":"55/5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z","evidence_id":"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"secondary-reporting.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068","size_bytes":4343,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"79/795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"secondary-reporting.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z","evidence_id":"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"official-source-record.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0","size_bytes":1851,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"a7/a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"official-source-record.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z","evidence_id":"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"market-page.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5","size_bytes":2778,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"d1/d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"market-page.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:25:11Z","evidence_id":"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z","sha256":"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab","size_bytes":3638,"source_description":"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.","source_url":"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026","storage_name":"f0/f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z","evidence_id":"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"primary-evidence.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94","size_bytes":1589,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"f8/f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"primary-evidence.txt"}],"exhibits":[{"evidence_id":"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page","label":"PX-1 Market page packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Market page record\n\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\n\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\n\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRule text:\n\n> This market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n>\n> Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n>\n> The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\n\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\n\nEvent:\n\n- event id: 400878\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: true\n- event closed: true\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\n\nMarket:\n\n- market id: 2037907\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\n- market closed: true\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"1\", \"0\"]\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record","label":"PX-2 Official source packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Official source record\n\n## Polymarket source\n\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\n\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\n\n## Clavicular or representative statements\n\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\n\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\n\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\n\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\n\n## UMA / oracle source\n\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting","label":"PX-3 Secondary reporting packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Secondary reporting\n\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\n\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\n\n## Times of India fact check\n\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\n\n## Hindustan Times\n\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\n\n## The Express Tribune\n\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\n\n## Search notes\n\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad","label":"PX-4 Official Polymarket/Gamma merits capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nSources:\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\n\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDisplayed probability: >99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\n\nRules text shown on page:\nThis market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\nMarket context text shown on page:\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \"dating show\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\n\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\n\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\n\n## Gamma API fields observed\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\nEvent id: 400878.\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDescription: same rules text as above.\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\nEvent active: true.\nEvent closed: true.\nEvent archived: false.\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\nMarket id: 2037907.\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nOutcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"].\nOutcome prices: [\"1\", \"0\"].\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase."},{"evidence_id":"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e","label":"PX-5 Times of India adverse fact-check capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\n\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\n\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\"\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says: \"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\"\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \"pregnancy contest\" and quotes: \"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\"\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition."},{"evidence_id":"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps","label":"PX-6 Record gaps packet file","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Unresolved record gaps\n\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page","label":"DX-1 Market rule and initial final-outcome packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Market page record\n\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\n\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\n\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRule text:\n\n> This market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n>\n> Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n>\n> The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\n\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\n\nEvent:\n\n- event id: 400878\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: true\n- event closed: true\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\n\nMarket:\n\n- market id: 2037907\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\n- market closed: true\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"1\", \"0\"]\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record","label":"DX-2 Official-source packet record showing missing primary statement and UMA detail","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Official source record\n\n## Polymarket source\n\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\n\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\n\n## Clavicular or representative statements\n\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\n\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\n\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\n\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\n\n## UMA / oracle source\n\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence","label":"DX-3 Primary-evidence packet assessment of missing underlying proof","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Primary evidence\n\n## Preserved primary/platform evidence\n\n- Polymarket market page: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Polymarket Gamma API event record: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Captured files: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt; source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json; source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\n\nThe official market rule requires a credible announcement by Clavicular that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy during the specified window.\n\n## Potential primary-source leads not locally preserved\n\n- Clavicular's Kick page or VODs: https://kick.com/clavicular/videos, referenced by Hindustan Times.\n- Domahhhh's April 30 X thread about the oracle dispute: https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218, referenced by Forbes.\n- JexTrade's April 29 X post about a large No buy, referenced by Forbes.\n- @holy_moses7 posts claiming the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” referenced by Forbes.\n- The viral Kick Champ post that Times of India says claimed Clavicular was “expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days ago.” The exact source URL was not captured.\n\n## Preliminary source assessment\n\nThe preserved primary evidence proves the contract wording and the platform's final Yes state. It does not itself prove that a qualifying credible announcement occurred. The fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting","label":"DX-4 Secondary-reporting conflict and adverse context","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Secondary reporting\n\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\n\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\n\n## Times of India fact check\n\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\n\n## Hindustan Times\n\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\n\n## The Express Tribune\n\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\n\n## Search notes\n\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps","label":"DX-5 Unresolved record gaps","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Unresolved record gaps\n\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad","label":"DX-6 Plaintiff Polymarket/Gamma capture, including context about vows, stunt, and debunked rumors","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nSources:\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\n\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDisplayed probability: >99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\n\nRules text shown on page:\nThis market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\nMarket context text shown on page:\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \"dating show\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\n\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\n\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\n\n## Gamma API fields observed\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\nEvent id: 400878.\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDescription: same rules text as above.\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\nEvent active: true.\nEvent closed: true.\nEvent archived: false.\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\nMarket id: 2037907.\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nOutcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"].\nOutcome prices: [\"1\", \"0\"].\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase."},{"evidence_id":"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e","label":"DX-7 Plaintiff-submitted Times of India adverse fact-check","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\n\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\n\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\"\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says: \"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\"\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \"pregnancy contest\" and quotes: \"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\"\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition."},{"evidence_id":"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e","label":"DX-S1 TOI fact-check on no confirming video or Clavicular statement","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\n\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\n\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\"\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says: \"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\"\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \"pregnancy contest\" and quotes: \"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\"\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition."},{"evidence_id":"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting","label":"DX-S2 Conflicting secondary reporting and contest/stunt framing","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"# Secondary reporting\n\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\n\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\n\n## Times of India fact check\n\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\n\n## Hindustan Times\n\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\n\n## The Express Tribune\n\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\n\n## Search notes\n\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps","label":"DX-S3 Missing original statement, platform clarification, and UMA records","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"# Unresolved record gaps\n\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad","label":"DX-S4 Official Polymarket/Gamma capture with market context","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nSources:\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\n\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDisplayed probability: >99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\n\nRules text shown on page:\nThis market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\nMarket context text shown on page:\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \"dating show\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\n\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\n\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\n\n## Gamma API fields observed\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\nEvent id: 400878.\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDescription: same rules text as above.\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\nEvent active: true.\nEvent closed: true.\nEvent archived: false.\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\nMarket id: 2037907.\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nOutcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"].\nOutcome prices: [\"1\", \"0\"].\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase."}],"openings":[{"phase":"openings","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, this case is about a narrow event definition, not about proving the private fact of a pregnancy to medical certainty. The proposition asks whether, after the April 20, 2026 market creation and before the stated deadline, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. Under the preponderance standard, the question is whether the better-supported reading of the available source chain is that a qualifying announcement occurred.\n\nThe present case packet already fixes the governing rule and the official market posture. The Polymarket page record states that the market resolves Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy, that only credible announcements qualify, that jokes do not suffice, and that statements from Clavicular or his representatives are the primary resolution source while a definitive consensus of credible media may also be considered. The same official-source packet records the platform/API state: the market went through proposed/disputed sequences and ultimately shows a final Yes outcome.\n\nThat matters, but it is not the whole case. A final Yes state is strong circumstantial and procedural evidence that the market's resolver accepted the event as satisfied, but by itself it does not show the exact words, tone, context, or credibility of the underlying announcement. The plaintiff's burden is therefore to connect that official Yes state to the source material that caused it.\n\nThe packet points to that connection. Forbes reported the dispute as turning on what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. Other reports described livestream remarks about wanting children or becoming a dad soon, and several sources frame the incident as a viral controversy. Those reports explain why the market moved and why the oracle dispute arose. They support the plaintiff's theory that there was, at minimum, a public announcement or reported announcement that the market treated as sufficient.\n\nThe defense will stress the same record's weaknesses. The packet does not yet preserve the original livestream clip, VOD, full transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification mentioned by Forbes, or UMA transaction-level record. The Times of India fact-check says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular; other reporting characterizes the comments as a contest, stunt, joke, or out-of-context viral content. Those are real weight issues because the rule expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes.\n\nSo the decisive factual questions are these: first, what exactly did Clavicular say, and was it about an existing partner pregnancy rather than a future desire, stunt, or contest? Second, did the statement occur after market creation? Third, did Clavicular or a representative make it, or did credible media reach the definitive consensus allowed by the rules? Fourth, does the Polymarket/UMA Yes resolution rest on that source chain or on speculation and trader pressure?\n\nThe plaintiff expects the later evidentiary phase to focus on the primary artifacts the packet identifies: the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, the Polymarket clarification, the Forbes source capture, the Domahhhh thread, any Kick Champ source, and UMA oracle records. If those materials show that Clavicular publicly stated that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the final Yes outcome and corroborating credible reporting should satisfy preponderance. If the best source instead shows only jokes, wishful remarks, a contest proposal, or unsupported reposts, the plaintiff's case would be materially weaker.\n\nFor opening purposes, the plaintiff's theory is disciplined: the official market record and secondary reporting make Yes the more plausible starting point, but the case should be decided by the preserved source chain, not by market price alone."},{"phase":"openings","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the defense position starts with the market rule itself. This case is not resolved by asking whether a rumor circulated, whether Polymarket ultimately showed a Yes outcome, or whether traders believed a provocative streamer had created controversy. The proposition requires proof, by a preponderance, that Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the relevant window.\n\nThe admitted packet proves some important background. The market page record fixes the contract language: only credible announcements qualify; jokes do not; the ordinary resolution source is statements from Clavicular or his representatives, with a definitive consensus of credible media as a possible secondary source. The same packet also shows the market was created on April 20, 2026 and later displayed a final Yes state after proposed and disputed resolution sequences. The defense does not need to pretend those facts are irrelevant. They explain why this dispute exists.\n\nBut they do not prove the proposition. The preserved primary/platform evidence is the Polymarket page and Gamma/API status material. It proves the rule and the platform result; it does not preserve the original livestream, VOD, clip, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, or UMA voter/proposer record that would show why the market ended Yes. The packet's own primary-evidence assessment says the fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\n\nThat missing link matters because the secondary record is internally conflicted on the very element the plaintiff must prove. Forbes is favorable to plaintiff insofar as it describes a dispute over a streamer who allegedly told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But the Times of India fact-check, also in the packet, says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular. Other packet excerpts describe remarks about wanting children, being a dad in the next few months, or a proposed pregnancy contest. Those are not the same thing as announcing that he and a partner are already expecting a baby through pregnancy.\n\nThe defense theory is therefore straightforward: final Yes resolution is circumstantial evidence of market administration, not a substitute for the qualifying announcement required by the rule. A viral claim repeated through social media, a contest proposal, a future-oriented wish to have children, shock-content banter, or an out-of-context clip does not satisfy a rule that expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes. If plaintiff can later preserve the original source and it shows an unambiguous, credible statement by Clavicular or his representative that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the defense will have to confront it. On the current record, that source is absent.\n\nThe decisive evidence in later phases should be narrow: the full original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript; any statement from Clavicular, a representative, or a publicist; the Polymarket clarification referenced in reporting; UMA transaction-level records showing the basis for the final outcome; and the source chain behind the Forbes characterization and the Domahhhh/Kick Champ leads. Those materials would let the council distinguish a real qualifying announcement from a rumor cycle.\n\nUntil that bridge is built, the plaintiff's strongest proof is that the market resolved Yes and some reporters described the controversy. The defense will show that the rule asks for more: a credible announcement, from the right source or a definitive credible-media consensus, about an existing partner pregnancy. The present packet identifies exactly why that has not yet been proven."}],"prior_council_votes":[{"member_id":"C1","rationale":"The record contains conflicting secondary reports and lacks any primary statement or definitive media consensus confirming a credible announcement; thus the proposition is not more likely than not proven.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C2","rationale":"The admitted record contains conflicting secondary reports and no preserved primary statement from Clavicular announcing an existing partner pregnancy. The preserved quotes describe future-oriented contest/stunt language, and Times of India explicitly states no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy. The final Yes resolution does not establish what evidence the resolver relied upon, and there is no definitive consensus of credible media as the rule requires.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C3","rationale":"The admitted record contains no primary statement confirming a pregnancy announcement and presents conflicting secondary reports, so the proposition is not proven by preponderance.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"}],"rebuttals":[{"phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the defense correctly identifies the record's weakest point: no original VOD, clip, or transcript is preserved. But the defense then treats that gap as dispositive. The market rule does not. It allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, and it also allows a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. That structure matters: the drafters anticipated that the council or resolver might have to decide from credible reporting, not only from a raw stream file.\n\nThe defense also understates the official final Yes. Plaintiff is not asking the council to treat market price as fact. PX-4 and the packet market record show more than price: a proposed Yes, dispute, proposed Yes, dispute, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0] and a resolved official state. That is the platform's resolution mechanism applying the same credibility rule after adversarial challenge. It is circumstantial, but it is unusually probative circumstantial evidence.\n\nThe defense says the Polymarket context describes future vows, a fertility-stack reveal, a dating-show/baby-mama proposal, and debunked girlfriend rumors. Yes, and plaintiff admitted that because unsupported viral reposts should be discounted. But that context does not erase the separate Forbes packet account: Forbes described the dispute as involving a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is not merely \"I want children someday\" language. It is the record's strongest description of an announcement that maps onto the rule.\n\nThe Times of India capture is adverse, but its force is narrower than the defense claims. It debunks the specific viral claim that Clavicular was expecting a first child with a girlfriend he met ten days earlier, and it discusses an out-of-context clip and a pregnancy-contest quote. It does not establish what the UMA resolver considered. It does not preserve the Polymarket clarification. It does not refute Forbes's specific characterization that the dispute concerned a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. And, like Forbes, it is secondary reporting rather than primary video.\n\nSo the evidentiary choice is not \"primary video versus nothing.\" It is whether the official final Yes, reached after two disputes under a rule that permits credible-media consensus, plus Forbes's affirmative characterization, outweighs adverse secondary reporting about a narrower viral rumor and the acknowledged absence of the raw source. On preponderance, plaintiff submits that it does.\n\nThe defense asks the council to infer that the official resolver accepted only a joke, stunt, or debunked rumor. That is possible, but it is not the better-supported inference on this record. The better-supported inference is that the official process credited a qualifying announcement or media-consensus path, even though the underlying primary artifact was not preserved in this packet. The gaps should reduce certainty; they should not convert a final official Yes and a favorable credible-media account into a No finding."}],"submitted_evidence":[{"evidence_id":"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab","size_bytes":3638,"source_description":"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.","source_url":"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026","title":"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market"},{"evidence_id":"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5","size_bytes":2189,"source_description":"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.","source_url":"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms","title":"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor"}],"surrebuttals":[{"phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. The defense is not arguing that a raw VOD is the only legally possible proof. The rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. But that is the point: the record does not contain such a consensus.\n\nWhat the record contains is one favorable Forbes characterization, adverse Times of India reporting that no video or Clavicular statement confirmed pregnancy, Hindustan Times and Express Tribune descriptions of a pregnancy-contest stunt, and an admitted gaps file saying the original stream, transcript, platform clarification, and UMA records are missing. That is not a definitive media consensus. It is a conflicted source chain.\n\nPlaintiff says TOI only debunks the narrower ten-day girlfriend rumor. But the proposition is itself about a partner pregnancy, and TOI’s captured text goes beyond narrow timing: no video confirms a pregnancy; no statement from Clavicular confirms it; the shared clip was out of context; the preserved quote was about wanting children and a pregnancy contest; the viral claim likely came from jokes and out-of-context clips. Those points directly undercut credibility and qualification under a rule that excludes jokes and noncredible announcements.\n\nPlaintiff also asks the council to treat final Yes after disputes as unusually probative. It is probative that the market resolved Yes. It is not probative enough to fill the missing basis for that resolution. The record does not show what the resolver considered, whether it relied on Forbes, the viral Kick Champ rumor, trader pressure, or something else, and it lacks the platform clarification Forbes reportedly said pointed No. Without the source chain, final Yes risks becoming circular proof: the announcement happened because the market resolved Yes, and the market resolved Yes because the announcement happened.\n\nThe preponderance question is not whether plaintiff’s theory is possible. It is whether the qualifying announcement is more likely than not on the admitted record. Given the conflicting media accounts, the absence of the underlying statement, and the admitted context of future vows, stunt framing, and debunked rumors, plaintiff has not crossed that line."}],"technical_reports":[{"phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","summary":"Before filing, plaintiff rescanned the record and evidence list. Target sources were official Polymarket/Gamma records, Forbes reporting, Times of India adverse reporting, the original Kick/VOD or clip, the Polymarket clarification, Domahhhh X thread, Kick Champ source, and UMA records. The Polymarket page was opened and the Gamma API was fetched with python3 urllib; the official rule, final Yes sequence, IDs, outcome prices, and context were preserved as PX-4. The Times of India article was opened and adverse fact-check text was preserved as PX-5. Forbes direct page capture was attempted by web open/search, but no stronger article text than the existing packet capture was obtained in time, so plaintiff relied on PX-3 rather than submitting a search snippet. No original VOD/transcript or full UMA voter record was captured this phase; those remain material gaps affecting weight.","title":"Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger"},{"phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","summary":"Defense rescanned the current record and evidence list, then read the two new plaintiff submissions in full. Source targets considered were the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, Clavicular/representative statements, the Polymarket clarification referenced by Forbes, UMA proposer/disputer/voter records, Forbes source chain, Domahhhh X thread, and Kick Champ source. Opening-phase searches found Forbes, Polymarket, Times of India, Hindustan Times, X Domahhhh, Inkl, Poprant/Indiatimes, Binance, and Lines leads; X thread opening produced no readable text, and no original video/transcript or representative statement was captured. No new defense evidence was submitted because the material defense sources are already admitted through the packet and plaintiff's TOI capture, while uncaptured leads remain unverified. Unresolved gaps remain the original statement, full context, platform clarification, and UMA rationale.","title":"Defense Source-Chain And Gap Ledger"}]}}},"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T07:50:07.017222578Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C4","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":885915,"role_id":"council","turn_number":12}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"get_case"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782804921105}}
{"type":"message_end","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ytnPFq86t","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex09-20260630071703\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 885915\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex09-20260630071703\",\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"case\":{\"evidence_standard\":\"Preponderance of the evidence.\",\"member\":{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"model\":\"openrouter://mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5\",\"persona_filename\":\"personas/generic.md\"},\"opportunity\":{\"allowed_tools\":[\"submit_council_vote\"],\"id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"may_pass\":false,\"objective\":\"council vote by C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"role\":\"council\"},\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"proposition\":\"Between market creation on April 20, 2026, and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\",\"record\":{\"arguments\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff's case is strongest where it stays tied to the rule and the source chain. The proposition is not whether a child was born, and not whether every viral repost was accurate. It is whether Clavicular made a credible announcement, within the market window, that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\\n\\nThe official market evidence establishes the governing frame. The packet market page and the newly submitted official Polymarket/Gamma capture show the same rule: Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy; only credible announcements count; jokes do not; statements from Clavicular or representatives are the resolution source, with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting also permitted. The official source also shows the market was proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes again, disputed again, and finally resolved Yes. The Gamma extract fixes the market ID, condition ID, outcomes [Yes, No], outcomePrices [1,0], and resolver/closed-time fields. That is not mere trader gossip. It is the official resolution mechanism applying the very rule before this council.\\n\\nThe best explanation for that official Yes result appears in the case packet's secondary-reporting file. Forbes identified the dispute as being over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That description matters because it directly tracks the rule's central question: a statement by the covered person about having gotten a partner pregnant. Forbes also reported that the disagreement was binary: the market description and platform clarification were said to point No while the price pointed Yes, and the oracle had not closed the gap after two dispute rounds. The subsequent official record now shows the gap closed at Yes.\\n\\nThat sequence is plaintiff's preponderance case. The council can reasonably infer that the UMA/Polymarket final Yes did not arise from a vacuum. It followed a disputed process on a high-volume market whose rule allowed either the speaker's statements or a definitive credible-media consensus. The admitted record contains a credible financial-news account saying the dispute centered on a reported statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, and an official source showing the final resolver accepted Yes. On preponderance, those combined facts make a qualifying announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe defense is right that this proof has a missing primary artifact. The original livestream/VOD/transcript is not in the record. Nor is the full Polymarket clarification or transaction-level UMA voter record. The plaintiff does not ask the council to pretend otherwise. Those gaps reduce weight and make this a circumstantial/source-chain case, not a clean direct-video case.\\n\\nBut the gaps do not erase the official resolution and corroborating media account. The rule itself permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a preserved VOD is not automatically fatal. What matters is whether the admitted record, as a whole, makes the qualifying announcement more probable than the competing account that all of this was only a joke, contest, or rumor. The Forbes packet capture is the clearest pro-Yes secondary source; the official Polymarket/Gamma capture is the clearest official outcome source.\\n\\nThe plaintiff also submitted the Times of India fact-check because the council should see the strongest adverse source. It says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular, and it treats the viral claim as likely false or out of context. The live Polymarket context also cuts both ways: it describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama stunt, while acknowledging debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend pregnancy. That evidence undercuts any claim that every viral pregnancy story was credible.\\n\\nStill, TOI is not a primary record either. It is a fact-check of the rumor cycle, not the market-resolution record. It does not disprove that Clavicular made a qualifying announcement later accepted by the resolver or reflected in Forbes's account. It shows why the council should discount unsupported reposts and distinguish future-oriented fatherhood talk from an announcement of an existing pregnancy. Plaintiff's position survives that distinction because the favorable Forbes account is about a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, while the official resolver ultimately paid Yes under the same credibility standard.\\n\\nSo the plaintiff asks the council to give controlling weight to the official rule-and-resolution evidence, substantial corroborating weight to the Forbes secondary-reporting capture, and appropriate but not dispositive weight to the adverse TOI fact-check. The record is imperfect, but preponderance does not require certainty or medical confirmation. It requires the better answer. Here, the better answer is that the market's final Yes reflected a credible announcement or qualifying credible-media consensus that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy within the covered window.\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s case depends on converting a market result into proof of the underlying fact. The record does not support that conversion.\\n\\nThe rule requires a credible announcement that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. The official market evidence proves the wording, timing, dispute sequence, and final Yes outcome. It does not prove what Clavicular actually said. The packet’s official-source and primary-evidence files say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved and that the fact question remains dependent on locating the underlying stream, clip, transcript, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s new Polymarket/Gamma capture adds official details, but the added context cuts against plaintiff’s theory. It describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, a fertility-stack reveal, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama proposal involving 500 contestants. It separately describes “debunked rumors” of a girlfriend’s pregnancy after ten days. Those are not admissions that he and a partner were already expecting a baby. They are future intent, stunt framing, and rumor framing.\\n\\nThe strongest pro-Yes item is the Forbes excerpt in the secondary-reporting packet saying the dispute concerned a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But in this record Forbes is a summarized secondary account in an article about an oracle dispute, not the underlying video, transcript, source post, or representative statement. The same Forbes excerpt also reported that the market description and platform clarification said No while price said Yes, and that traders alleged the oracle had become a disinformation engine. That is not a clean source chain; it is a warning that market mechanics and trader incentives may have overtaken source proof.\\n\\nThe adverse evidence is more specific about the missing link. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, the actual preserved quote was future-oriented pregnancy-contest language, and the viral claim was false and likely came from jokes, out-of-context clips, and his content style. The secondary-reporting packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries match that: “I must have children,” “I must get children today,” and “I will be a dad in the next few months” were treated as a controversial proposal or stunt, not confirmation of an existing partner pregnancy.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a VOD is not automatically fatal. True, but the record does not show a definitive consensus. It shows conflict: Forbes characterizes the dispute one way; Times of India expressly debunks the girlfriend-pregnancy claim; Hindustan Times and Express Tribune frame the remarks as a contest/stunt; the packet says no primary source or Domahhhh thread text was located. A single favorable secondary characterization plus a final market resolution is not a definitive media consensus, especially where admitted adverse reporting directly denies confirmation.\\n\\nNor should the council give controlling weight to the final Yes state. The official resolver result proves that the market was resolved Yes. It does not reveal the evidence considered, the voters’ rationale, the proposer/disputer record, or whether the resolution rested on the same viral rumor now debunked in the record. The unresolved-gaps file expressly notes the missing UMA records and the missing Polymarket clarification Forbes said pointed No.\\n\\nOn preponderance, the better-supported finding is not that a qualifying announcement happened. It is that there was a viral controversy after market creation, built from future fatherhood talk, a pregnancy-contest stunt, social-media rumors, and a disputed market process that ultimately resolved Yes without preserving the basis. The proposition asks for a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy. The current record proves the controversy and the market result, but it does not prove that announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe defense therefore asks the council to find the proposition not proven on this record.\"}],\"closings\":[{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff does not ask you to decide that every viral post was true, or that the record proves the private medical fact of pregnancy. The proposition is narrower: whether Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the covered window.\\n\\nThe record proves the rule, the timing, and the official resolution. The market text required a credible announcement, excluded jokes, and allowed not only statements from Clavicular or representatives but also a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. The official Polymarket/Gamma evidence then shows proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes, disputed again, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0]. That is not a mere price chart. It is the official resolution process applying the same rule now before this council.\\n\\nThe record also contains the affirmative source-chain link. The secondary-reporting packet preserves Forbes's characterization that the dispute was over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is the key phrase in this case. It is not simply a desire to have children someday. It is a reported statement about having gotten a girl pregnant, which maps directly to the rule's pregnancy-announcement requirement. The final Yes resolution then confirms that the official process ultimately credited the Yes side despite disputes.\\n\\nThe defense's best point is real: the original VOD, transcript, Polymarket clarification, and UMA voter rationale are not in the record. That means the plaintiff's case is not direct-video proof. But preponderance does not demand perfect custody or certainty. It asks which inference is better supported by the admitted record.\\n\\nThe adverse record does not carry the defense over that line. The Times of India capture and the live Polymarket context warn against unsupported girlfriend-rumor reposts, out-of-context clips, future fatherhood talk, and stunt framing. Plaintiff accepts that warning. Those materials show why jokes and rumors should be discounted. They do not establish that the official resolver accepted a joke, and they do not erase Forbes's account of a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. They are secondary reports too; they are not the missing primary video.\\n\\nThe defense's theory requires a larger inference than plaintiff's. It asks you to conclude that, after two disputes, the official final Yes likely rested on nothing more than a noncredible rumor or stunt, even though the rule expressly excluded such material and even though Forbes described the dispute in terms of a pregnancy statement. That is possible, but on this record it is not the more probable account.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's account fits all of the admitted pieces: the rule allowed a credible announcement or credible-media consensus; Forbes reported the relevant announcement framing; the market underwent contested resolution; and the final official state paid Yes. The conflicting adverse reporting explains why the case was disputed and why the source chain is imperfect. It does not make No more likely than Yes.\\n\\nFor that reason, under the preponderance standard, the council should find that the proposition is proven.\"},{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the record leaves this case short of preponderance.\\n\\nThe plaintiff is right about one thing: the proposition is not whether a child was born or whether a pregnancy was medically true. The question is whether Clavicular made a credible qualifying announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. But the record still has to prove that announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe official market evidence proves the rule, the dates, the dispute sequence, and the final Yes state. It does not prove the underlying source. The case-packet official-source and primary-evidence files expressly say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved. The unresolved-gaps file identifies the same missing pieces: original livestream clip, VOD, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, and UMA proposer/disputer/voter records.\\n\\nThat matters because plaintiff’s case turns on a bridge it never fully builds. The bridge is one Forbes characterization that the dispute involved a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, plus the final Yes resolution. But the record does not preserve Forbes’s underlying source chain. And the same secondary-reporting packet records that Forbes described the market description and platform clarification as saying No, while price said Yes, and linked criticism of the oracle process. That is not a clean, independent confirmation of a qualifying announcement.\\n\\nThe contrary evidence is not just noise. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, and it identifies the actual preserved quote as future-oriented pregnancy-contest language. The packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries likewise frame the remarks as a contest or stunt: wanting children, needing children today, and being a dad in the next few months. Plaintiff’s own Polymarket/Gamma capture describes trader consensus as driven by public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, a dating-show/baby-mama stunt, and debunked girlfriend-pregnancy rumors. Those facts fit a rumor and stunt cycle at least as well as they fit a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. It does. But this record is not a consensus. It is a conflict: one favorable Forbes phrasing, adverse fact-checking, multiple contest/stunt accounts, and admitted missing source-chain material. A definitive consensus cannot be inferred from divided secondary reporting.\\n\\nPlaintiff also says the official Yes after disputes is unusually probative. It has some weight, but it cannot carry the burden by itself. The record does not show what the resolver considered or why it resolved Yes. Without the UMA rationale, source material, or platform clarification, final Yes is at risk of circular reasoning: using the market’s outcome to prove the fact that the market outcome was supposed to decide.\\n\\nThe defense is not asking the council to find that no rumor existed, or that no one ever thought Clavicular might make such an announcement. The defense is asking the council to apply the actual proposition and the preponderance standard. On this record, a qualifying credible announcement is not more likely than a nonqualifying mix of future fatherhood talk, a provocative contest proposal, out-of-context clips, and debunked viral claims.\\n\\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition not proven.\"}],\"evidence\":[{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407\",\"size_bytes\":1254,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"04/045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:34Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"size_bytes\":2189,\"source_description\":\"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.\",\"source_url\":\"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\",\"storage_name\":\"55/5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068\",\"size_bytes\":4343,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"79/795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"official-source-record.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0\",\"size_bytes\":1851,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"a7/a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"official-source-record.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"market-page.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5\",\"size_bytes\":2778,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"d1/d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"market-page.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:11Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"size_bytes\":3638,\"source_description\":\"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.\",\"source_url\":\"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\",\"storage_name\":\"f0/f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"primary-evidence.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94\",\"size_bytes\":1589,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"f8/f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"primary-evidence.txt\"}],\"exhibits\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"label\":\"PX-1 Market page packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\\n\\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRule text:\\n\\n\\u003e This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\\n\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\\n\\nEvent:\\n\\n- event id: 400878\\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: true\\n- event closed: true\\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\\n\\nMarket:\\n\\n- market id: 2037907\\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\\n- market closed: true\\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"PX-2 Official source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\n## Polymarket source\\n\\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\n\\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\\n\\n## Clavicular or representative statements\\n\\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\\n\\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\\n\\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\\n\\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\\n\\n## UMA / oracle source\\n\\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"PX-3 Secondary reporting packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"PX-4 Official Polymarket/Gamma merits capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"PX-5 Times of India adverse fact-check capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"PX-6 Record gaps packet file\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"label\":\"DX-1 Market rule and initial final-outcome packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\\n\\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRule text:\\n\\n\\u003e This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\\n\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\\n\\nEvent:\\n\\n- event id: 400878\\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: true\\n- event closed: true\\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\\n\\nMarket:\\n\\n- market id: 2037907\\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\\n- market closed: true\\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"DX-2 Official-source packet record showing missing primary statement and UMA detail\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\n## Polymarket source\\n\\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\n\\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\\n\\n## Clavicular or representative statements\\n\\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\\n\\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\\n\\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\\n\\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\\n\\n## UMA / oracle source\\n\\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence\",\"label\":\"DX-3 Primary-evidence packet assessment of missing underlying proof\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Primary evidence\\n\\n## Preserved primary/platform evidence\\n\\n- Polymarket market page: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Polymarket Gamma API event record: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Captured files: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt; source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json; source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\nThe official market rule requires a credible announcement by Clavicular that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy during the specified window.\\n\\n## Potential primary-source leads not locally preserved\\n\\n- Clavicular's Kick page or VODs: https://kick.com/clavicular/videos, referenced by Hindustan Times.\\n- Domahhhh's April 30 X thread about the oracle dispute: https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218, referenced by Forbes.\\n- JexTrade's April 29 X post about a large No buy, referenced by Forbes.\\n- @holy_moses7 posts claiming the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” referenced by Forbes.\\n- The viral Kick Champ post that Times of India says claimed Clavicular was “expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days ago.” The exact source URL was not captured.\\n\\n## Preliminary source assessment\\n\\nThe preserved primary evidence proves the contract wording and the platform's final Yes state. It does not itself prove that a qualifying credible announcement occurred. The fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"DX-4 Secondary-reporting conflict and adverse context\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"DX-5 Unresolved record gaps\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"DX-6 Plaintiff Polymarket/Gamma capture, including context about vows, stunt, and debunked rumors\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"DX-7 Plaintiff-submitted Times of India adverse fact-check\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"DX-S1 TOI fact-check on no confirming video or Clavicular statement\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"DX-S2 Conflicting secondary reporting and contest/stunt framing\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"DX-S3 Missing original statement, platform clarification, and UMA records\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"DX-S4 Official Polymarket/Gamma capture with market context\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"}],\"openings\":[{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, this case is about a narrow event definition, not about proving the private fact of a pregnancy to medical certainty. The proposition asks whether, after the April 20, 2026 market creation and before the stated deadline, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. Under the preponderance standard, the question is whether the better-supported reading of the available source chain is that a qualifying announcement occurred.\\n\\nThe present case packet already fixes the governing rule and the official market posture. The Polymarket page record states that the market resolves Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy, that only credible announcements qualify, that jokes do not suffice, and that statements from Clavicular or his representatives are the primary resolution source while a definitive consensus of credible media may also be considered. The same official-source packet records the platform/API state: the market went through proposed/disputed sequences and ultimately shows a final Yes outcome.\\n\\nThat matters, but it is not the whole case. A final Yes state is strong circumstantial and procedural evidence that the market's resolver accepted the event as satisfied, but by itself it does not show the exact words, tone, context, or credibility of the underlying announcement. The plaintiff's burden is therefore to connect that official Yes state to the source material that caused it.\\n\\nThe packet points to that connection. Forbes reported the dispute as turning on what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. Other reports described livestream remarks about wanting children or becoming a dad soon, and several sources frame the incident as a viral controversy. Those reports explain why the market moved and why the oracle dispute arose. They support the plaintiff's theory that there was, at minimum, a public announcement or reported announcement that the market treated as sufficient.\\n\\nThe defense will stress the same record's weaknesses. The packet does not yet preserve the original livestream clip, VOD, full transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification mentioned by Forbes, or UMA transaction-level record. The Times of India fact-check says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular; other reporting characterizes the comments as a contest, stunt, joke, or out-of-context viral content. Those are real weight issues because the rule expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes.\\n\\nSo the decisive factual questions are these: first, what exactly did Clavicular say, and was it about an existing partner pregnancy rather than a future desire, stunt, or contest? Second, did the statement occur after market creation? Third, did Clavicular or a representative make it, or did credible media reach the definitive consensus allowed by the rules? Fourth, does the Polymarket/UMA Yes resolution rest on that source chain or on speculation and trader pressure?\\n\\nThe plaintiff expects the later evidentiary phase to focus on the primary artifacts the packet identifies: the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, the Polymarket clarification, the Forbes source capture, the Domahhhh thread, any Kick Champ source, and UMA oracle records. If those materials show that Clavicular publicly stated that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the final Yes outcome and corroborating credible reporting should satisfy preponderance. If the best source instead shows only jokes, wishful remarks, a contest proposal, or unsupported reposts, the plaintiff's case would be materially weaker.\\n\\nFor opening purposes, the plaintiff's theory is disciplined: the official market record and secondary reporting make Yes the more plausible starting point, but the case should be decided by the preserved source chain, not by market price alone.\"},{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense position starts with the market rule itself. This case is not resolved by asking whether a rumor circulated, whether Polymarket ultimately showed a Yes outcome, or whether traders believed a provocative streamer had created controversy. The proposition requires proof, by a preponderance, that Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the relevant window.\\n\\nThe admitted packet proves some important background. The market page record fixes the contract language: only credible announcements qualify; jokes do not; the ordinary resolution source is statements from Clavicular or his representatives, with a definitive consensus of credible media as a possible secondary source. The same packet also shows the market was created on April 20, 2026 and later displayed a final Yes state after proposed and disputed resolution sequences. The defense does not need to pretend those facts are irrelevant. They explain why this dispute exists.\\n\\nBut they do not prove the proposition. The preserved primary/platform evidence is the Polymarket page and Gamma/API status material. It proves the rule and the platform result; it does not preserve the original livestream, VOD, clip, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, or UMA voter/proposer record that would show why the market ended Yes. The packet's own primary-evidence assessment says the fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\\nThat missing link matters because the secondary record is internally conflicted on the very element the plaintiff must prove. Forbes is favorable to plaintiff insofar as it describes a dispute over a streamer who allegedly told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But the Times of India fact-check, also in the packet, says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular. Other packet excerpts describe remarks about wanting children, being a dad in the next few months, or a proposed pregnancy contest. Those are not the same thing as announcing that he and a partner are already expecting a baby through pregnancy.\\n\\nThe defense theory is therefore straightforward: final Yes resolution is circumstantial evidence of market administration, not a substitute for the qualifying announcement required by the rule. A viral claim repeated through social media, a contest proposal, a future-oriented wish to have children, shock-content banter, or an out-of-context clip does not satisfy a rule that expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes. If plaintiff can later preserve the original source and it shows an unambiguous, credible statement by Clavicular or his representative that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the defense will have to confront it. On the current record, that source is absent.\\n\\nThe decisive evidence in later phases should be narrow: the full original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript; any statement from Clavicular, a representative, or a publicist; the Polymarket clarification referenced in reporting; UMA transaction-level records showing the basis for the final outcome; and the source chain behind the Forbes characterization and the Domahhhh/Kick Champ leads. Those materials would let the council distinguish a real qualifying announcement from a rumor cycle.\\n\\nUntil that bridge is built, the plaintiff's strongest proof is that the market resolved Yes and some reporters described the controversy. The defense will show that the rule asks for more: a credible announcement, from the right source or a definitive credible-media consensus, about an existing partner pregnancy. The present packet identifies exactly why that has not yet been proven.\"}],\"prior_council_votes\":[{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The record contains conflicting secondary reports and lacks any primary statement or definitive media consensus confirming a credible announcement; thus the proposition is not more likely than not proven.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record contains conflicting secondary reports and no preserved primary statement from Clavicular announcing an existing partner pregnancy. The preserved quotes describe future-oriented contest/stunt language, and Times of India explicitly states no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy. The final Yes resolution does not establish what evidence the resolver relied upon, and there is no definitive consensus of credible media as the rule requires.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record contains no primary statement confirming a pregnancy announcement and presents conflicting secondary reports, so the proposition is not proven by preponderance.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"}],\"rebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense correctly identifies the record's weakest point: no original VOD, clip, or transcript is preserved. But the defense then treats that gap as dispositive. The market rule does not. It allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, and it also allows a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. That structure matters: the drafters anticipated that the council or resolver might have to decide from credible reporting, not only from a raw stream file.\\n\\nThe defense also understates the official final Yes. Plaintiff is not asking the council to treat market price as fact. PX-4 and the packet market record show more than price: a proposed Yes, dispute, proposed Yes, dispute, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0] and a resolved official state. That is the platform's resolution mechanism applying the same credibility rule after adversarial challenge. It is circumstantial, but it is unusually probative circumstantial evidence.\\n\\nThe defense says the Polymarket context describes future vows, a fertility-stack reveal, a dating-show/baby-mama proposal, and debunked girlfriend rumors. Yes, and plaintiff admitted that because unsupported viral reposts should be discounted. But that context does not erase the separate Forbes packet account: Forbes described the dispute as involving a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is not merely \\\"I want children someday\\\" language. It is the record's strongest description of an announcement that maps onto the rule.\\n\\nThe Times of India capture is adverse, but its force is narrower than the defense claims. It debunks the specific viral claim that Clavicular was expecting a first child with a girlfriend he met ten days earlier, and it discusses an out-of-context clip and a pregnancy-contest quote. It does not establish what the UMA resolver considered. It does not preserve the Polymarket clarification. It does not refute Forbes's specific characterization that the dispute concerned a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. And, like Forbes, it is secondary reporting rather than primary video.\\n\\nSo the evidentiary choice is not \\\"primary video versus nothing.\\\" It is whether the official final Yes, reached after two disputes under a rule that permits credible-media consensus, plus Forbes's affirmative characterization, outweighs adverse secondary reporting about a narrower viral rumor and the acknowledged absence of the raw source. On preponderance, plaintiff submits that it does.\\n\\nThe defense asks the council to infer that the official resolver accepted only a joke, stunt, or debunked rumor. That is possible, but it is not the better-supported inference on this record. The better-supported inference is that the official process credited a qualifying announcement or media-consensus path, even though the underlying primary artifact was not preserved in this packet. The gaps should reduce certainty; they should not convert a final official Yes and a favorable credible-media account into a No finding.\"}],\"submitted_evidence\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"size_bytes\":3638,\"source_description\":\"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.\",\"source_url\":\"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\",\"title\":\"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"size_bytes\":2189,\"source_description\":\"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.\",\"source_url\":\"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\",\"title\":\"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\"}],\"surrebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. The defense is not arguing that a raw VOD is the only legally possible proof. The rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. But that is the point: the record does not contain such a consensus.\\n\\nWhat the record contains is one favorable Forbes characterization, adverse Times of India reporting that no video or Clavicular statement confirmed pregnancy, Hindustan Times and Express Tribune descriptions of a pregnancy-contest stunt, and an admitted gaps file saying the original stream, transcript, platform clarification, and UMA records are missing. That is not a definitive media consensus. It is a conflicted source chain.\\n\\nPlaintiff says TOI only debunks the narrower ten-day girlfriend rumor. But the proposition is itself about a partner pregnancy, and TOI’s captured text goes beyond narrow timing: no video confirms a pregnancy; no statement from Clavicular confirms it; the shared clip was out of context; the preserved quote was about wanting children and a pregnancy contest; the viral claim likely came from jokes and out-of-context clips. Those points directly undercut credibility and qualification under a rule that excludes jokes and noncredible announcements.\\n\\nPlaintiff also asks the council to treat final Yes after disputes as unusually probative. It is probative that the market resolved Yes. It is not probative enough to fill the missing basis for that resolution. The record does not show what the resolver considered, whether it relied on Forbes, the viral Kick Champ rumor, trader pressure, or something else, and it lacks the platform clarification Forbes reportedly said pointed No. Without the source chain, final Yes risks becoming circular proof: the announcement happened because the market resolved Yes, and the market resolved Yes because the announcement happened.\\n\\nThe preponderance question is not whether plaintiff’s theory is possible. It is whether the qualifying announcement is more likely than not on the admitted record. Given the conflicting media accounts, the absence of the underlying statement, and the admitted context of future vows, stunt framing, and debunked rumors, plaintiff has not crossed that line.\"}],\"technical_reports\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Before filing, plaintiff rescanned the record and evidence list. Target sources were official Polymarket/Gamma records, Forbes reporting, Times of India adverse reporting, the original Kick/VOD or clip, the Polymarket clarification, Domahhhh X thread, Kick Champ source, and UMA records. The Polymarket page was opened and the Gamma API was fetched with python3 urllib; the official rule, final Yes sequence, IDs, outcome prices, and context were preserved as PX-4. The Times of India article was opened and adverse fact-check text was preserved as PX-5. Forbes direct page capture was attempted by web open/search, but no stronger article text than the existing packet capture was obtained in time, so plaintiff relied on PX-3 rather than submitting a search snippet. No original VOD/transcript or full UMA voter record was captured this phase; those remain material gaps affecting weight.\",\"title\":\"Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"Defense rescanned the current record and evidence list, then read the two new plaintiff submissions in full. Source targets considered were the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, Clavicular/representative statements, the Polymarket clarification referenced by Forbes, UMA proposer/disputer/voter records, Forbes source chain, Domahhhh X thread, and Kick Champ source. Opening-phase searches found Forbes, Polymarket, Times of India, Hindustan Times, X Domahhhh, Inkl, Poprant/Indiatimes, Binance, and Lines leads; X thread opening produced no readable text, and no original video/transcript or representative statement was captured. No new defense evidence was submitted because the material defense sources are already admitted through the packet and plaintiff's TOI capture, while uncaptured leads remain unverified. Unresolved gaps remain the original statement, full context, platform clarification, and UMA rationale.\",\"title\":\"Defense Source-Chain And Gap Ledger\"}]}}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T07:50:07.017222578Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":885915,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex09-20260630071703\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 885915\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex09-20260630071703\",\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"case\":{\"evidence_standard\":\"Preponderance of the evidence.\",\"member\":{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"model\":\"openrouter://mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5\",\"persona_filename\":\"personas/generic.md\"},\"opportunity\":{\"allowed_tools\":[\"submit_council_vote\"],\"id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"may_pass\":false,\"objective\":\"council vote by C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"role\":\"council\"},\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"proposition\":\"Between market creation on April 20, 2026, and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\",\"record\":{\"arguments\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff's case is strongest where it stays tied to the rule and the source chain. The proposition is not whether a child was born, and not whether every viral repost was accurate. It is whether Clavicular made a credible announcement, within the market window, that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\\n\\nThe official market evidence establishes the governing frame. The packet market page and the newly submitted official Polymarket/Gamma capture show the same rule: Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy; only credible announcements count; jokes do not; statements from Clavicular or representatives are the resolution source, with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting also permitted. The official source also shows the market was proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes again, disputed again, and finally resolved Yes. The Gamma extract fixes the market ID, condition ID, outcomes [Yes, No], outcomePrices [1,0], and resolver/closed-time fields. That is not mere trader gossip. It is the official resolution mechanism applying the very rule before this council.\\n\\nThe best explanation for that official Yes result appears in the case packet's secondary-reporting file. Forbes identified the dispute as being over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That description matters because it directly tracks the rule's central question: a statement by the covered person about having gotten a partner pregnant. Forbes also reported that the disagreement was binary: the market description and platform clarification were said to point No while the price pointed Yes, and the oracle had not closed the gap after two dispute rounds. The subsequent official record now shows the gap closed at Yes.\\n\\nThat sequence is plaintiff's preponderance case. The council can reasonably infer that the UMA/Polymarket final Yes did not arise from a vacuum. It followed a disputed process on a high-volume market whose rule allowed either the speaker's statements or a definitive credible-media consensus. The admitted record contains a credible financial-news account saying the dispute centered on a reported statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, and an official source showing the final resolver accepted Yes. On preponderance, those combined facts make a qualifying announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe defense is right that this proof has a missing primary artifact. The original livestream/VOD/transcript is not in the record. Nor is the full Polymarket clarification or transaction-level UMA voter record. The plaintiff does not ask the council to pretend otherwise. Those gaps reduce weight and make this a circumstantial/source-chain case, not a clean direct-video case.\\n\\nBut the gaps do not erase the official resolution and corroborating media account. The rule itself permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a preserved VOD is not automatically fatal. What matters is whether the admitted record, as a whole, makes the qualifying announcement more probable than the competing account that all of this was only a joke, contest, or rumor. The Forbes packet capture is the clearest pro-Yes secondary source; the official Polymarket/Gamma capture is the clearest official outcome source.\\n\\nThe plaintiff also submitted the Times of India fact-check because the council should see the strongest adverse source. It says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular, and it treats the viral claim as likely false or out of context. The live Polymarket context also cuts both ways: it describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama stunt, while acknowledging debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend pregnancy. That evidence undercuts any claim that every viral pregnancy story was credible.\\n\\nStill, TOI is not a primary record either. It is a fact-check of the rumor cycle, not the market-resolution record. It does not disprove that Clavicular made a qualifying announcement later accepted by the resolver or reflected in Forbes's account. It shows why the council should discount unsupported reposts and distinguish future-oriented fatherhood talk from an announcement of an existing pregnancy. Plaintiff's position survives that distinction because the favorable Forbes account is about a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, while the official resolver ultimately paid Yes under the same credibility standard.\\n\\nSo the plaintiff asks the council to give controlling weight to the official rule-and-resolution evidence, substantial corroborating weight to the Forbes secondary-reporting capture, and appropriate but not dispositive weight to the adverse TOI fact-check. The record is imperfect, but preponderance does not require certainty or medical confirmation. It requires the better answer. Here, the better answer is that the market's final Yes reflected a credible announcement or qualifying credible-media consensus that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy within the covered window.\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s case depends on converting a market result into proof of the underlying fact. The record does not support that conversion.\\n\\nThe rule requires a credible announcement that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. The official market evidence proves the wording, timing, dispute sequence, and final Yes outcome. It does not prove what Clavicular actually said. The packet’s official-source and primary-evidence files say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved and that the fact question remains dependent on locating the underlying stream, clip, transcript, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s new Polymarket/Gamma capture adds official details, but the added context cuts against plaintiff’s theory. It describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, a fertility-stack reveal, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama proposal involving 500 contestants. It separately describes “debunked rumors” of a girlfriend’s pregnancy after ten days. Those are not admissions that he and a partner were already expecting a baby. They are future intent, stunt framing, and rumor framing.\\n\\nThe strongest pro-Yes item is the Forbes excerpt in the secondary-reporting packet saying the dispute concerned a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But in this record Forbes is a summarized secondary account in an article about an oracle dispute, not the underlying video, transcript, source post, or representative statement. The same Forbes excerpt also reported that the market description and platform clarification said No while price said Yes, and that traders alleged the oracle had become a disinformation engine. That is not a clean source chain; it is a warning that market mechanics and trader incentives may have overtaken source proof.\\n\\nThe adverse evidence is more specific about the missing link. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, the actual preserved quote was future-oriented pregnancy-contest language, and the viral claim was false and likely came from jokes, out-of-context clips, and his content style. The secondary-reporting packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries match that: “I must have children,” “I must get children today,” and “I will be a dad in the next few months” were treated as a controversial proposal or stunt, not confirmation of an existing partner pregnancy.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a VOD is not automatically fatal. True, but the record does not show a definitive consensus. It shows conflict: Forbes characterizes the dispute one way; Times of India expressly debunks the girlfriend-pregnancy claim; Hindustan Times and Express Tribune frame the remarks as a contest/stunt; the packet says no primary source or Domahhhh thread text was located. A single favorable secondary characterization plus a final market resolution is not a definitive media consensus, especially where admitted adverse reporting directly denies confirmation.\\n\\nNor should the council give controlling weight to the final Yes state. The official resolver result proves that the market was resolved Yes. It does not reveal the evidence considered, the voters’ rationale, the proposer/disputer record, or whether the resolution rested on the same viral rumor now debunked in the record. The unresolved-gaps file expressly notes the missing UMA records and the missing Polymarket clarification Forbes said pointed No.\\n\\nOn preponderance, the better-supported finding is not that a qualifying announcement happened. It is that there was a viral controversy after market creation, built from future fatherhood talk, a pregnancy-contest stunt, social-media rumors, and a disputed market process that ultimately resolved Yes without preserving the basis. The proposition asks for a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy. The current record proves the controversy and the market result, but it does not prove that announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe defense therefore asks the council to find the proposition not proven on this record.\"}],\"closings\":[{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff does not ask you to decide that every viral post was true, or that the record proves the private medical fact of pregnancy. The proposition is narrower: whether Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the covered window.\\n\\nThe record proves the rule, the timing, and the official resolution. The market text required a credible announcement, excluded jokes, and allowed not only statements from Clavicular or representatives but also a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. The official Polymarket/Gamma evidence then shows proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes, disputed again, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0]. That is not a mere price chart. It is the official resolution process applying the same rule now before this council.\\n\\nThe record also contains the affirmative source-chain link. The secondary-reporting packet preserves Forbes's characterization that the dispute was over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is the key phrase in this case. It is not simply a desire to have children someday. It is a reported statement about having gotten a girl pregnant, which maps directly to the rule's pregnancy-announcement requirement. The final Yes resolution then confirms that the official process ultimately credited the Yes side despite disputes.\\n\\nThe defense's best point is real: the original VOD, transcript, Polymarket clarification, and UMA voter rationale are not in the record. That means the plaintiff's case is not direct-video proof. But preponderance does not demand perfect custody or certainty. It asks which inference is better supported by the admitted record.\\n\\nThe adverse record does not carry the defense over that line. The Times of India capture and the live Polymarket context warn against unsupported girlfriend-rumor reposts, out-of-context clips, future fatherhood talk, and stunt framing. Plaintiff accepts that warning. Those materials show why jokes and rumors should be discounted. They do not establish that the official resolver accepted a joke, and they do not erase Forbes's account of a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. They are secondary reports too; they are not the missing primary video.\\n\\nThe defense's theory requires a larger inference than plaintiff's. It asks you to conclude that, after two disputes, the official final Yes likely rested on nothing more than a noncredible rumor or stunt, even though the rule expressly excluded such material and even though Forbes described the dispute in terms of a pregnancy statement. That is possible, but on this record it is not the more probable account.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's account fits all of the admitted pieces: the rule allowed a credible announcement or credible-media consensus; Forbes reported the relevant announcement framing; the market underwent contested resolution; and the final official state paid Yes. The conflicting adverse reporting explains why the case was disputed and why the source chain is imperfect. It does not make No more likely than Yes.\\n\\nFor that reason, under the preponderance standard, the council should find that the proposition is proven.\"},{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the record leaves this case short of preponderance.\\n\\nThe plaintiff is right about one thing: the proposition is not whether a child was born or whether a pregnancy was medically true. The question is whether Clavicular made a credible qualifying announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. But the record still has to prove that announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe official market evidence proves the rule, the dates, the dispute sequence, and the final Yes state. It does not prove the underlying source. The case-packet official-source and primary-evidence files expressly say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved. The unresolved-gaps file identifies the same missing pieces: original livestream clip, VOD, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, and UMA proposer/disputer/voter records.\\n\\nThat matters because plaintiff’s case turns on a bridge it never fully builds. The bridge is one Forbes characterization that the dispute involved a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, plus the final Yes resolution. But the record does not preserve Forbes’s underlying source chain. And the same secondary-reporting packet records that Forbes described the market description and platform clarification as saying No, while price said Yes, and linked criticism of the oracle process. That is not a clean, independent confirmation of a qualifying announcement.\\n\\nThe contrary evidence is not just noise. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, and it identifies the actual preserved quote as future-oriented pregnancy-contest language. The packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries likewise frame the remarks as a contest or stunt: wanting children, needing children today, and being a dad in the next few months. Plaintiff’s own Polymarket/Gamma capture describes trader consensus as driven by public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, a dating-show/baby-mama stunt, and debunked girlfriend-pregnancy rumors. Those facts fit a rumor and stunt cycle at least as well as they fit a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. It does. But this record is not a consensus. It is a conflict: one favorable Forbes phrasing, adverse fact-checking, multiple contest/stunt accounts, and admitted missing source-chain material. A definitive consensus cannot be inferred from divided secondary reporting.\\n\\nPlaintiff also says the official Yes after disputes is unusually probative. It has some weight, but it cannot carry the burden by itself. The record does not show what the resolver considered or why it resolved Yes. Without the UMA rationale, source material, or platform clarification, final Yes is at risk of circular reasoning: using the market’s outcome to prove the fact that the market outcome was supposed to decide.\\n\\nThe defense is not asking the council to find that no rumor existed, or that no one ever thought Clavicular might make such an announcement. The defense is asking the council to apply the actual proposition and the preponderance standard. On this record, a qualifying credible announcement is not more likely than a nonqualifying mix of future fatherhood talk, a provocative contest proposal, out-of-context clips, and debunked viral claims.\\n\\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition not proven.\"}],\"evidence\":[{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407\",\"size_bytes\":1254,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"04/045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:34Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"size_bytes\":2189,\"source_description\":\"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.\",\"source_url\":\"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\",\"storage_name\":\"55/5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068\",\"size_bytes\":4343,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"79/795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"official-source-record.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0\",\"size_bytes\":1851,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"a7/a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"official-source-record.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"market-page.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5\",\"size_bytes\":2778,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"d1/d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"market-page.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:11Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"size_bytes\":3638,\"source_description\":\"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.\",\"source_url\":\"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\",\"storage_name\":\"f0/f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"primary-evidence.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94\",\"size_bytes\":1589,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"f8/f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"primary-evidence.txt\"}],\"exhibits\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"label\":\"PX-1 Market page packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\\n\\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRule text:\\n\\n\\u003e This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\\n\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\\n\\nEvent:\\n\\n- event id: 400878\\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: true\\n- event closed: true\\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\\n\\nMarket:\\n\\n- market id: 2037907\\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\\n- market closed: true\\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"PX-2 Official source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\n## Polymarket source\\n\\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\n\\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\\n\\n## Clavicular or representative statements\\n\\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\\n\\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\\n\\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\\n\\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\\n\\n## UMA / oracle source\\n\\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"PX-3 Secondary reporting packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"PX-4 Official Polymarket/Gamma merits capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"PX-5 Times of India adverse fact-check capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"PX-6 Record gaps packet file\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"label\":\"DX-1 Market rule and initial final-outcome packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\\n\\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRule text:\\n\\n\\u003e This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\\n\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\\n\\nEvent:\\n\\n- event id: 400878\\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: true\\n- event closed: true\\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\\n\\nMarket:\\n\\n- market id: 2037907\\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\\n- market closed: true\\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"DX-2 Official-source packet record showing missing primary statement and UMA detail\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\n## Polymarket source\\n\\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\n\\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\\n\\n## Clavicular or representative statements\\n\\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\\n\\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\\n\\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\\n\\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\\n\\n## UMA / oracle source\\n\\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence\",\"label\":\"DX-3 Primary-evidence packet assessment of missing underlying proof\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Primary evidence\\n\\n## Preserved primary/platform evidence\\n\\n- Polymarket market page: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Polymarket Gamma API event record: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Captured files: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt; source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json; source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\nThe official market rule requires a credible announcement by Clavicular that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy during the specified window.\\n\\n## Potential primary-source leads not locally preserved\\n\\n- Clavicular's Kick page or VODs: https://kick.com/clavicular/videos, referenced by Hindustan Times.\\n- Domahhhh's April 30 X thread about the oracle dispute: https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218, referenced by Forbes.\\n- JexTrade's April 29 X post about a large No buy, referenced by Forbes.\\n- @holy_moses7 posts claiming the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” referenced by Forbes.\\n- The viral Kick Champ post that Times of India says claimed Clavicular was “expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days ago.” The exact source URL was not captured.\\n\\n## Preliminary source assessment\\n\\nThe preserved primary evidence proves the contract wording and the platform's final Yes state. It does not itself prove that a qualifying credible announcement occurred. The fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"DX-4 Secondary-reporting conflict and adverse context\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"DX-5 Unresolved record gaps\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"DX-6 Plaintiff Polymarket/Gamma capture, including context about vows, stunt, and debunked rumors\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"DX-7 Plaintiff-submitted Times of India adverse fact-check\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"DX-S1 TOI fact-check on no confirming video or Clavicular statement\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"DX-S2 Conflicting secondary reporting and contest/stunt framing\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"DX-S3 Missing original statement, platform clarification, and UMA records\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"DX-S4 Official Polymarket/Gamma capture with market context\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"}],\"openings\":[{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, this case is about a narrow event definition, not about proving the private fact of a pregnancy to medical certainty. The proposition asks whether, after the April 20, 2026 market creation and before the stated deadline, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. Under the preponderance standard, the question is whether the better-supported reading of the available source chain is that a qualifying announcement occurred.\\n\\nThe present case packet already fixes the governing rule and the official market posture. The Polymarket page record states that the market resolves Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy, that only credible announcements qualify, that jokes do not suffice, and that statements from Clavicular or his representatives are the primary resolution source while a definitive consensus of credible media may also be considered. The same official-source packet records the platform/API state: the market went through proposed/disputed sequences and ultimately shows a final Yes outcome.\\n\\nThat matters, but it is not the whole case. A final Yes state is strong circumstantial and procedural evidence that the market's resolver accepted the event as satisfied, but by itself it does not show the exact words, tone, context, or credibility of the underlying announcement. The plaintiff's burden is therefore to connect that official Yes state to the source material that caused it.\\n\\nThe packet points to that connection. Forbes reported the dispute as turning on what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. Other reports described livestream remarks about wanting children or becoming a dad soon, and several sources frame the incident as a viral controversy. Those reports explain why the market moved and why the oracle dispute arose. They support the plaintiff's theory that there was, at minimum, a public announcement or reported announcement that the market treated as sufficient.\\n\\nThe defense will stress the same record's weaknesses. The packet does not yet preserve the original livestream clip, VOD, full transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification mentioned by Forbes, or UMA transaction-level record. The Times of India fact-check says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular; other reporting characterizes the comments as a contest, stunt, joke, or out-of-context viral content. Those are real weight issues because the rule expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes.\\n\\nSo the decisive factual questions are these: first, what exactly did Clavicular say, and was it about an existing partner pregnancy rather than a future desire, stunt, or contest? Second, did the statement occur after market creation? Third, did Clavicular or a representative make it, or did credible media reach the definitive consensus allowed by the rules? Fourth, does the Polymarket/UMA Yes resolution rest on that source chain or on speculation and trader pressure?\\n\\nThe plaintiff expects the later evidentiary phase to focus on the primary artifacts the packet identifies: the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, the Polymarket clarification, the Forbes source capture, the Domahhhh thread, any Kick Champ source, and UMA oracle records. If those materials show that Clavicular publicly stated that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the final Yes outcome and corroborating credible reporting should satisfy preponderance. If the best source instead shows only jokes, wishful remarks, a contest proposal, or unsupported reposts, the plaintiff's case would be materially weaker.\\n\\nFor opening purposes, the plaintiff's theory is disciplined: the official market record and secondary reporting make Yes the more plausible starting point, but the case should be decided by the preserved source chain, not by market price alone.\"},{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense position starts with the market rule itself. This case is not resolved by asking whether a rumor circulated, whether Polymarket ultimately showed a Yes outcome, or whether traders believed a provocative streamer had created controversy. The proposition requires proof, by a preponderance, that Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the relevant window.\\n\\nThe admitted packet proves some important background. The market page record fixes the contract language: only credible announcements qualify; jokes do not; the ordinary resolution source is statements from Clavicular or his representatives, with a definitive consensus of credible media as a possible secondary source. The same packet also shows the market was created on April 20, 2026 and later displayed a final Yes state after proposed and disputed resolution sequences. The defense does not need to pretend those facts are irrelevant. They explain why this dispute exists.\\n\\nBut they do not prove the proposition. The preserved primary/platform evidence is the Polymarket page and Gamma/API status material. It proves the rule and the platform result; it does not preserve the original livestream, VOD, clip, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, or UMA voter/proposer record that would show why the market ended Yes. The packet's own primary-evidence assessment says the fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\\nThat missing link matters because the secondary record is internally conflicted on the very element the plaintiff must prove. Forbes is favorable to plaintiff insofar as it describes a dispute over a streamer who allegedly told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But the Times of India fact-check, also in the packet, says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular. Other packet excerpts describe remarks about wanting children, being a dad in the next few months, or a proposed pregnancy contest. Those are not the same thing as announcing that he and a partner are already expecting a baby through pregnancy.\\n\\nThe defense theory is therefore straightforward: final Yes resolution is circumstantial evidence of market administration, not a substitute for the qualifying announcement required by the rule. A viral claim repeated through social media, a contest proposal, a future-oriented wish to have children, shock-content banter, or an out-of-context clip does not satisfy a rule that expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes. If plaintiff can later preserve the original source and it shows an unambiguous, credible statement by Clavicular or his representative that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the defense will have to confront it. On the current record, that source is absent.\\n\\nThe decisive evidence in later phases should be narrow: the full original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript; any statement from Clavicular, a representative, or a publicist; the Polymarket clarification referenced in reporting; UMA transaction-level records showing the basis for the final outcome; and the source chain behind the Forbes characterization and the Domahhhh/Kick Champ leads. Those materials would let the council distinguish a real qualifying announcement from a rumor cycle.\\n\\nUntil that bridge is built, the plaintiff's strongest proof is that the market resolved Yes and some reporters described the controversy. The defense will show that the rule asks for more: a credible announcement, from the right source or a definitive credible-media consensus, about an existing partner pregnancy. The present packet identifies exactly why that has not yet been proven.\"}],\"prior_council_votes\":[{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The record contains conflicting secondary reports and lacks any primary statement or definitive media consensus confirming a credible announcement; thus the proposition is not more likely than not proven.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record contains conflicting secondary reports and no preserved primary statement from Clavicular announcing an existing partner pregnancy. The preserved quotes describe future-oriented contest/stunt language, and Times of India explicitly states no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy. The final Yes resolution does not establish what evidence the resolver relied upon, and there is no definitive consensus of credible media as the rule requires.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record contains no primary statement confirming a pregnancy announcement and presents conflicting secondary reports, so the proposition is not proven by preponderance.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"}],\"rebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense correctly identifies the record's weakest point: no original VOD, clip, or transcript is preserved. But the defense then treats that gap as dispositive. The market rule does not. It allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, and it also allows a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. That structure matters: the drafters anticipated that the council or resolver might have to decide from credible reporting, not only from a raw stream file.\\n\\nThe defense also understates the official final Yes. Plaintiff is not asking the council to treat market price as fact. PX-4 and the packet market record show more than price: a proposed Yes, dispute, proposed Yes, dispute, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0] and a resolved official state. That is the platform's resolution mechanism applying the same credibility rule after adversarial challenge. It is circumstantial, but it is unusually probative circumstantial evidence.\\n\\nThe defense says the Polymarket context describes future vows, a fertility-stack reveal, a dating-show/baby-mama proposal, and debunked girlfriend rumors. Yes, and plaintiff admitted that because unsupported viral reposts should be discounted. But that context does not erase the separate Forbes packet account: Forbes described the dispute as involving a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is not merely \\\"I want children someday\\\" language. It is the record's strongest description of an announcement that maps onto the rule.\\n\\nThe Times of India capture is adverse, but its force is narrower than the defense claims. It debunks the specific viral claim that Clavicular was expecting a first child with a girlfriend he met ten days earlier, and it discusses an out-of-context clip and a pregnancy-contest quote. It does not establish what the UMA resolver considered. It does not preserve the Polymarket clarification. It does not refute Forbes's specific characterization that the dispute concerned a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. And, like Forbes, it is secondary reporting rather than primary video.\\n\\nSo the evidentiary choice is not \\\"primary video versus nothing.\\\" It is whether the official final Yes, reached after two disputes under a rule that permits credible-media consensus, plus Forbes's affirmative characterization, outweighs adverse secondary reporting about a narrower viral rumor and the acknowledged absence of the raw source. On preponderance, plaintiff submits that it does.\\n\\nThe defense asks the council to infer that the official resolver accepted only a joke, stunt, or debunked rumor. That is possible, but it is not the better-supported inference on this record. The better-supported inference is that the official process credited a qualifying announcement or media-consensus path, even though the underlying primary artifact was not preserved in this packet. The gaps should reduce certainty; they should not convert a final official Yes and a favorable credible-media account into a No finding.\"}],\"submitted_evidence\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"size_bytes\":3638,\"source_description\":\"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.\",\"source_url\":\"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\",\"title\":\"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"size_bytes\":2189,\"source_description\":\"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.\",\"source_url\":\"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\",\"title\":\"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\"}],\"surrebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. The defense is not arguing that a raw VOD is the only legally possible proof. The rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. But that is the point: the record does not contain such a consensus.\\n\\nWhat the record contains is one favorable Forbes characterization, adverse Times of India reporting that no video or Clavicular statement confirmed pregnancy, Hindustan Times and Express Tribune descriptions of a pregnancy-contest stunt, and an admitted gaps file saying the original stream, transcript, platform clarification, and UMA records are missing. That is not a definitive media consensus. It is a conflicted source chain.\\n\\nPlaintiff says TOI only debunks the narrower ten-day girlfriend rumor. But the proposition is itself about a partner pregnancy, and TOI’s captured text goes beyond narrow timing: no video confirms a pregnancy; no statement from Clavicular confirms it; the shared clip was out of context; the preserved quote was about wanting children and a pregnancy contest; the viral claim likely came from jokes and out-of-context clips. Those points directly undercut credibility and qualification under a rule that excludes jokes and noncredible announcements.\\n\\nPlaintiff also asks the council to treat final Yes after disputes as unusually probative. It is probative that the market resolved Yes. It is not probative enough to fill the missing basis for that resolution. The record does not show what the resolver considered, whether it relied on Forbes, the viral Kick Champ rumor, trader pressure, or something else, and it lacks the platform clarification Forbes reportedly said pointed No. Without the source chain, final Yes risks becoming circular proof: the announcement happened because the market resolved Yes, and the market resolved Yes because the announcement happened.\\n\\nThe preponderance question is not whether plaintiff’s theory is possible. It is whether the qualifying announcement is more likely than not on the admitted record. Given the conflicting media accounts, the absence of the underlying statement, and the admitted context of future vows, stunt framing, and debunked rumors, plaintiff has not crossed that line.\"}],\"technical_reports\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Before filing, plaintiff rescanned the record and evidence list. Target sources were official Polymarket/Gamma records, Forbes reporting, Times of India adverse reporting, the original Kick/VOD or clip, the Polymarket clarification, Domahhhh X thread, Kick Champ source, and UMA records. The Polymarket page was opened and the Gamma API was fetched with python3 urllib; the official rule, final Yes sequence, IDs, outcome prices, and context were preserved as PX-4. The Times of India article was opened and adverse fact-check text was preserved as PX-5. Forbes direct page capture was attempted by web open/search, but no stronger article text than the existing packet capture was obtained in time, so plaintiff relied on PX-3 rather than submitting a search snippet. No original VOD/transcript or full UMA voter record was captured this phase; those remain material gaps affecting weight.\",\"title\":\"Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"Defense rescanned the current record and evidence list, then read the two new plaintiff submissions in full. Source targets considered were the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, Clavicular/representative statements, the Polymarket clarification referenced by Forbes, UMA proposer/disputer/voter records, Forbes source chain, Domahhhh X thread, and Kick Champ source. Opening-phase searches found Forbes, Polymarket, Times of India, Hindustan Times, X Domahhhh, Inkl, Poprant/Indiatimes, Binance, and Lines leads; X thread opening produced no readable text, and no original video/transcript or representative statement was captured. No new defense evidence was submitted because the material defense sources are already admitted through the packet and plaintiff's TOI capture, while uncaptured leads remain unverified. Unresolved gaps remain the original statement, full context, platform clarification, and UMA rationale.\",\"title\":\"Defense Source-Chain And Gap Ledger\"}]}}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T07:50:07.017222578Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":885915,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12}}"}],"structuredContent":{"case_id":"arb-ex09-20260630071703","member_id":"C4","ok":true,"result":{"case":{"evidence_standard":"Preponderance of the evidence.","member":{"member_id":"C4","model":"openrouter://mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5","persona_filename":"personas/generic.md"},"opportunity":{"allowed_tools":["submit_council_vote"],"id":"deliberation:1:C4","may_pass":false,"objective":"council vote by C4","phase":"deliberation","role":"council"},"phase":"deliberation","proposition":"Between market creation on April 20, 2026, and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.","record":{"arguments":[{"phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the plaintiff's case is strongest where it stays tied to the rule and the source chain. The proposition is not whether a child was born, and not whether every viral repost was accurate. It is whether Clavicular made a credible announcement, within the market window, that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\n\nThe official market evidence establishes the governing frame. The packet market page and the newly submitted official Polymarket/Gamma capture show the same rule: Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy; only credible announcements count; jokes do not; statements from Clavicular or representatives are the resolution source, with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting also permitted. The official source also shows the market was proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes again, disputed again, and finally resolved Yes. The Gamma extract fixes the market ID, condition ID, outcomes [Yes, No], outcomePrices [1,0], and resolver/closed-time fields. That is not mere trader gossip. It is the official resolution mechanism applying the very rule before this council.\n\nThe best explanation for that official Yes result appears in the case packet's secondary-reporting file. Forbes identified the dispute as being over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That description matters because it directly tracks the rule's central question: a statement by the covered person about having gotten a partner pregnant. Forbes also reported that the disagreement was binary: the market description and platform clarification were said to point No while the price pointed Yes, and the oracle had not closed the gap after two dispute rounds. The subsequent official record now shows the gap closed at Yes.\n\nThat sequence is plaintiff's preponderance case. The council can reasonably infer that the UMA/Polymarket final Yes did not arise from a vacuum. It followed a disputed process on a high-volume market whose rule allowed either the speaker's statements or a definitive credible-media consensus. The admitted record contains a credible financial-news account saying the dispute centered on a reported statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, and an official source showing the final resolver accepted Yes. On preponderance, those combined facts make a qualifying announcement more likely than not.\n\nThe defense is right that this proof has a missing primary artifact. The original livestream/VOD/transcript is not in the record. Nor is the full Polymarket clarification or transaction-level UMA voter record. The plaintiff does not ask the council to pretend otherwise. Those gaps reduce weight and make this a circumstantial/source-chain case, not a clean direct-video case.\n\nBut the gaps do not erase the official resolution and corroborating media account. The rule itself permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a preserved VOD is not automatically fatal. What matters is whether the admitted record, as a whole, makes the qualifying announcement more probable than the competing account that all of this was only a joke, contest, or rumor. The Forbes packet capture is the clearest pro-Yes secondary source; the official Polymarket/Gamma capture is the clearest official outcome source.\n\nThe plaintiff also submitted the Times of India fact-check because the council should see the strongest adverse source. It says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular, and it treats the viral claim as likely false or out of context. The live Polymarket context also cuts both ways: it describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama stunt, while acknowledging debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend pregnancy. That evidence undercuts any claim that every viral pregnancy story was credible.\n\nStill, TOI is not a primary record either. It is a fact-check of the rumor cycle, not the market-resolution record. It does not disprove that Clavicular made a qualifying announcement later accepted by the resolver or reflected in Forbes's account. It shows why the council should discount unsupported reposts and distinguish future-oriented fatherhood talk from an announcement of an existing pregnancy. Plaintiff's position survives that distinction because the favorable Forbes account is about a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, while the official resolver ultimately paid Yes under the same credibility standard.\n\nSo the plaintiff asks the council to give controlling weight to the official rule-and-resolution evidence, substantial corroborating weight to the Forbes secondary-reporting capture, and appropriate but not dispositive weight to the adverse TOI fact-check. The record is imperfect, but preponderance does not require certainty or medical confirmation. It requires the better answer. Here, the better answer is that the market's final Yes reflected a credible announcement or qualifying credible-media consensus that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy within the covered window."},{"phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, plaintiff’s case depends on converting a market result into proof of the underlying fact. The record does not support that conversion.\n\nThe rule requires a credible announcement that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. The official market evidence proves the wording, timing, dispute sequence, and final Yes outcome. It does not prove what Clavicular actually said. The packet’s official-source and primary-evidence files say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved and that the fact question remains dependent on locating the underlying stream, clip, transcript, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\n\nPlaintiff’s new Polymarket/Gamma capture adds official details, but the added context cuts against plaintiff’s theory. It describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, a fertility-stack reveal, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama proposal involving 500 contestants. It separately describes “debunked rumors” of a girlfriend’s pregnancy after ten days. Those are not admissions that he and a partner were already expecting a baby. They are future intent, stunt framing, and rumor framing.\n\nThe strongest pro-Yes item is the Forbes excerpt in the secondary-reporting packet saying the dispute concerned a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But in this record Forbes is a summarized secondary account in an article about an oracle dispute, not the underlying video, transcript, source post, or representative statement. The same Forbes excerpt also reported that the market description and platform clarification said No while price said Yes, and that traders alleged the oracle had become a disinformation engine. That is not a clean source chain; it is a warning that market mechanics and trader incentives may have overtaken source proof.\n\nThe adverse evidence is more specific about the missing link. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, the actual preserved quote was future-oriented pregnancy-contest language, and the viral claim was false and likely came from jokes, out-of-context clips, and his content style. The secondary-reporting packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries match that: “I must have children,” “I must get children today,” and “I will be a dad in the next few months” were treated as a controversial proposal or stunt, not confirmation of an existing partner pregnancy.\n\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a VOD is not automatically fatal. True, but the record does not show a definitive consensus. It shows conflict: Forbes characterizes the dispute one way; Times of India expressly debunks the girlfriend-pregnancy claim; Hindustan Times and Express Tribune frame the remarks as a contest/stunt; the packet says no primary source or Domahhhh thread text was located. A single favorable secondary characterization plus a final market resolution is not a definitive media consensus, especially where admitted adverse reporting directly denies confirmation.\n\nNor should the council give controlling weight to the final Yes state. The official resolver result proves that the market was resolved Yes. It does not reveal the evidence considered, the voters’ rationale, the proposer/disputer record, or whether the resolution rested on the same viral rumor now debunked in the record. The unresolved-gaps file expressly notes the missing UMA records and the missing Polymarket clarification Forbes said pointed No.\n\nOn preponderance, the better-supported finding is not that a qualifying announcement happened. It is that there was a viral controversy after market creation, built from future fatherhood talk, a pregnancy-contest stunt, social-media rumors, and a disputed market process that ultimately resolved Yes without preserving the basis. The proposition asks for a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy. The current record proves the controversy and the market result, but it does not prove that announcement more likely than not.\n\nThe defense therefore asks the council to find the proposition not proven on this record."}],"closings":[{"phase":"closings","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the plaintiff does not ask you to decide that every viral post was true, or that the record proves the private medical fact of pregnancy. The proposition is narrower: whether Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the covered window.\n\nThe record proves the rule, the timing, and the official resolution. The market text required a credible announcement, excluded jokes, and allowed not only statements from Clavicular or representatives but also a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. The official Polymarket/Gamma evidence then shows proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes, disputed again, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0]. That is not a mere price chart. It is the official resolution process applying the same rule now before this council.\n\nThe record also contains the affirmative source-chain link. The secondary-reporting packet preserves Forbes's characterization that the dispute was over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is the key phrase in this case. It is not simply a desire to have children someday. It is a reported statement about having gotten a girl pregnant, which maps directly to the rule's pregnancy-announcement requirement. The final Yes resolution then confirms that the official process ultimately credited the Yes side despite disputes.\n\nThe defense's best point is real: the original VOD, transcript, Polymarket clarification, and UMA voter rationale are not in the record. That means the plaintiff's case is not direct-video proof. But preponderance does not demand perfect custody or certainty. It asks which inference is better supported by the admitted record.\n\nThe adverse record does not carry the defense over that line. The Times of India capture and the live Polymarket context warn against unsupported girlfriend-rumor reposts, out-of-context clips, future fatherhood talk, and stunt framing. Plaintiff accepts that warning. Those materials show why jokes and rumors should be discounted. They do not establish that the official resolver accepted a joke, and they do not erase Forbes's account of a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. They are secondary reports too; they are not the missing primary video.\n\nThe defense's theory requires a larger inference than plaintiff's. It asks you to conclude that, after two disputes, the official final Yes likely rested on nothing more than a noncredible rumor or stunt, even though the rule expressly excluded such material and even though Forbes described the dispute in terms of a pregnancy statement. That is possible, but on this record it is not the more probable account.\n\nThe plaintiff's account fits all of the admitted pieces: the rule allowed a credible announcement or credible-media consensus; Forbes reported the relevant announcement framing; the market underwent contested resolution; and the final official state paid Yes. The conflicting adverse reporting explains why the case was disputed and why the source chain is imperfect. It does not make No more likely than Yes.\n\nFor that reason, under the preponderance standard, the council should find that the proposition is proven."},{"phase":"closings","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the record leaves this case short of preponderance.\n\nThe plaintiff is right about one thing: the proposition is not whether a child was born or whether a pregnancy was medically true. The question is whether Clavicular made a credible qualifying announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. But the record still has to prove that announcement more likely than not.\n\nThe official market evidence proves the rule, the dates, the dispute sequence, and the final Yes state. It does not prove the underlying source. The case-packet official-source and primary-evidence files expressly say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved. The unresolved-gaps file identifies the same missing pieces: original livestream clip, VOD, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, and UMA proposer/disputer/voter records.\n\nThat matters because plaintiff’s case turns on a bridge it never fully builds. The bridge is one Forbes characterization that the dispute involved a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, plus the final Yes resolution. But the record does not preserve Forbes’s underlying source chain. And the same secondary-reporting packet records that Forbes described the market description and platform clarification as saying No, while price said Yes, and linked criticism of the oracle process. That is not a clean, independent confirmation of a qualifying announcement.\n\nThe contrary evidence is not just noise. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, and it identifies the actual preserved quote as future-oriented pregnancy-contest language. The packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries likewise frame the remarks as a contest or stunt: wanting children, needing children today, and being a dad in the next few months. Plaintiff’s own Polymarket/Gamma capture describes trader consensus as driven by public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, a dating-show/baby-mama stunt, and debunked girlfriend-pregnancy rumors. Those facts fit a rumor and stunt cycle at least as well as they fit a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy.\n\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. It does. But this record is not a consensus. It is a conflict: one favorable Forbes phrasing, adverse fact-checking, multiple contest/stunt accounts, and admitted missing source-chain material. A definitive consensus cannot be inferred from divided secondary reporting.\n\nPlaintiff also says the official Yes after disputes is unusually probative. It has some weight, but it cannot carry the burden by itself. The record does not show what the resolver considered or why it resolved Yes. Without the UMA rationale, source material, or platform clarification, final Yes is at risk of circular reasoning: using the market’s outcome to prove the fact that the market outcome was supposed to decide.\n\nThe defense is not asking the council to find that no rumor existed, or that no one ever thought Clavicular might make such an announcement. The defense is asking the council to apply the actual proposition and the preponderance standard. On this record, a qualifying credible announcement is not more likely than a nonqualifying mix of future fatherhood talk, a provocative contest proposal, out-of-context clips, and debunked viral claims.\n\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition not proven."}],"evidence":[{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z","evidence_id":"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"unresolved-record-gaps.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407","size_bytes":1254,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"04/045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"unresolved-record-gaps.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:25:34Z","evidence_id":"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z","sha256":"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5","size_bytes":2189,"source_description":"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.","source_url":"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms","storage_name":"55/5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z","evidence_id":"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"secondary-reporting.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068","size_bytes":4343,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"79/795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"secondary-reporting.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z","evidence_id":"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"official-source-record.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0","size_bytes":1851,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"a7/a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"official-source-record.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z","evidence_id":"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"market-page.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5","size_bytes":2778,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"d1/d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"market-page.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:25:11Z","evidence_id":"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z","sha256":"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab","size_bytes":3638,"source_description":"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.","source_url":"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026","storage_name":"f0/f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z","evidence_id":"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"primary-evidence.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94","size_bytes":1589,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"f8/f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"primary-evidence.txt"}],"exhibits":[{"evidence_id":"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page","label":"PX-1 Market page packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Market page record\n\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\n\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\n\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRule text:\n\n> This market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n>\n> Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n>\n> The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\n\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\n\nEvent:\n\n- event id: 400878\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: true\n- event closed: true\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\n\nMarket:\n\n- market id: 2037907\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\n- market closed: true\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"1\", \"0\"]\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record","label":"PX-2 Official source packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Official source record\n\n## Polymarket source\n\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\n\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\n\n## Clavicular or representative statements\n\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\n\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\n\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\n\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\n\n## UMA / oracle source\n\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting","label":"PX-3 Secondary reporting packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Secondary reporting\n\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\n\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\n\n## Times of India fact check\n\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\n\n## Hindustan Times\n\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\n\n## The Express Tribune\n\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\n\n## Search notes\n\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad","label":"PX-4 Official Polymarket/Gamma merits capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nSources:\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\n\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDisplayed probability: >99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\n\nRules text shown on page:\nThis market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\nMarket context text shown on page:\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \"dating show\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\n\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\n\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\n\n## Gamma API fields observed\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\nEvent id: 400878.\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDescription: same rules text as above.\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\nEvent active: true.\nEvent closed: true.\nEvent archived: false.\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\nMarket id: 2037907.\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nOutcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"].\nOutcome prices: [\"1\", \"0\"].\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase."},{"evidence_id":"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e","label":"PX-5 Times of India adverse fact-check capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\n\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\n\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\"\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says: \"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\"\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \"pregnancy contest\" and quotes: \"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\"\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition."},{"evidence_id":"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps","label":"PX-6 Record gaps packet file","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Unresolved record gaps\n\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page","label":"DX-1 Market rule and initial final-outcome packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Market page record\n\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\n\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\n\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRule text:\n\n> This market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n>\n> Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n>\n> The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\n\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\n\nEvent:\n\n- event id: 400878\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: true\n- event closed: true\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\n\nMarket:\n\n- market id: 2037907\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\n- market closed: true\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"1\", \"0\"]\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record","label":"DX-2 Official-source packet record showing missing primary statement and UMA detail","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Official source record\n\n## Polymarket source\n\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\n\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\n\n## Clavicular or representative statements\n\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\n\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\n\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\n\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\n\n## UMA / oracle source\n\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence","label":"DX-3 Primary-evidence packet assessment of missing underlying proof","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Primary evidence\n\n## Preserved primary/platform evidence\n\n- Polymarket market page: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Polymarket Gamma API event record: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Captured files: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt; source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json; source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\n\nThe official market rule requires a credible announcement by Clavicular that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy during the specified window.\n\n## Potential primary-source leads not locally preserved\n\n- Clavicular's Kick page or VODs: https://kick.com/clavicular/videos, referenced by Hindustan Times.\n- Domahhhh's April 30 X thread about the oracle dispute: https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218, referenced by Forbes.\n- JexTrade's April 29 X post about a large No buy, referenced by Forbes.\n- @holy_moses7 posts claiming the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” referenced by Forbes.\n- The viral Kick Champ post that Times of India says claimed Clavicular was “expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days ago.” The exact source URL was not captured.\n\n## Preliminary source assessment\n\nThe preserved primary evidence proves the contract wording and the platform's final Yes state. It does not itself prove that a qualifying credible announcement occurred. The fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting","label":"DX-4 Secondary-reporting conflict and adverse context","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Secondary reporting\n\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\n\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\n\n## Times of India fact check\n\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\n\n## Hindustan Times\n\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\n\n## The Express Tribune\n\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\n\n## Search notes\n\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps","label":"DX-5 Unresolved record gaps","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Unresolved record gaps\n\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad","label":"DX-6 Plaintiff Polymarket/Gamma capture, including context about vows, stunt, and debunked rumors","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nSources:\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\n\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDisplayed probability: >99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\n\nRules text shown on page:\nThis market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\nMarket context text shown on page:\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \"dating show\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\n\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\n\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\n\n## Gamma API fields observed\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\nEvent id: 400878.\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDescription: same rules text as above.\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\nEvent active: true.\nEvent closed: true.\nEvent archived: false.\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\nMarket id: 2037907.\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nOutcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"].\nOutcome prices: [\"1\", \"0\"].\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase."},{"evidence_id":"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e","label":"DX-7 Plaintiff-submitted Times of India adverse fact-check","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\n\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\n\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\"\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says: \"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\"\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \"pregnancy contest\" and quotes: \"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\"\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition."},{"evidence_id":"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e","label":"DX-S1 TOI fact-check on no confirming video or Clavicular statement","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\n\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\n\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\"\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says: \"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\"\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \"pregnancy contest\" and quotes: \"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\"\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition."},{"evidence_id":"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting","label":"DX-S2 Conflicting secondary reporting and contest/stunt framing","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"# Secondary reporting\n\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\n\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\n\n## Times of India fact check\n\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\n\n## Hindustan Times\n\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\n\n## The Express Tribune\n\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\n\n## Search notes\n\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps","label":"DX-S3 Missing original statement, platform clarification, and UMA records","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"# Unresolved record gaps\n\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad","label":"DX-S4 Official Polymarket/Gamma capture with market context","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nSources:\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\n\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDisplayed probability: >99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\n\nRules text shown on page:\nThis market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\nMarket context text shown on page:\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \"dating show\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\n\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\n\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\n\n## Gamma API fields observed\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\nEvent id: 400878.\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDescription: same rules text as above.\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\nEvent active: true.\nEvent closed: true.\nEvent archived: false.\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\nMarket id: 2037907.\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nOutcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"].\nOutcome prices: [\"1\", \"0\"].\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase."}],"openings":[{"phase":"openings","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, this case is about a narrow event definition, not about proving the private fact of a pregnancy to medical certainty. The proposition asks whether, after the April 20, 2026 market creation and before the stated deadline, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. Under the preponderance standard, the question is whether the better-supported reading of the available source chain is that a qualifying announcement occurred.\n\nThe present case packet already fixes the governing rule and the official market posture. The Polymarket page record states that the market resolves Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy, that only credible announcements qualify, that jokes do not suffice, and that statements from Clavicular or his representatives are the primary resolution source while a definitive consensus of credible media may also be considered. The same official-source packet records the platform/API state: the market went through proposed/disputed sequences and ultimately shows a final Yes outcome.\n\nThat matters, but it is not the whole case. A final Yes state is strong circumstantial and procedural evidence that the market's resolver accepted the event as satisfied, but by itself it does not show the exact words, tone, context, or credibility of the underlying announcement. The plaintiff's burden is therefore to connect that official Yes state to the source material that caused it.\n\nThe packet points to that connection. Forbes reported the dispute as turning on what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. Other reports described livestream remarks about wanting children or becoming a dad soon, and several sources frame the incident as a viral controversy. Those reports explain why the market moved and why the oracle dispute arose. They support the plaintiff's theory that there was, at minimum, a public announcement or reported announcement that the market treated as sufficient.\n\nThe defense will stress the same record's weaknesses. The packet does not yet preserve the original livestream clip, VOD, full transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification mentioned by Forbes, or UMA transaction-level record. The Times of India fact-check says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular; other reporting characterizes the comments as a contest, stunt, joke, or out-of-context viral content. Those are real weight issues because the rule expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes.\n\nSo the decisive factual questions are these: first, what exactly did Clavicular say, and was it about an existing partner pregnancy rather than a future desire, stunt, or contest? Second, did the statement occur after market creation? Third, did Clavicular or a representative make it, or did credible media reach the definitive consensus allowed by the rules? Fourth, does the Polymarket/UMA Yes resolution rest on that source chain or on speculation and trader pressure?\n\nThe plaintiff expects the later evidentiary phase to focus on the primary artifacts the packet identifies: the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, the Polymarket clarification, the Forbes source capture, the Domahhhh thread, any Kick Champ source, and UMA oracle records. If those materials show that Clavicular publicly stated that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the final Yes outcome and corroborating credible reporting should satisfy preponderance. If the best source instead shows only jokes, wishful remarks, a contest proposal, or unsupported reposts, the plaintiff's case would be materially weaker.\n\nFor opening purposes, the plaintiff's theory is disciplined: the official market record and secondary reporting make Yes the more plausible starting point, but the case should be decided by the preserved source chain, not by market price alone."},{"phase":"openings","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the defense position starts with the market rule itself. This case is not resolved by asking whether a rumor circulated, whether Polymarket ultimately showed a Yes outcome, or whether traders believed a provocative streamer had created controversy. The proposition requires proof, by a preponderance, that Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the relevant window.\n\nThe admitted packet proves some important background. The market page record fixes the contract language: only credible announcements qualify; jokes do not; the ordinary resolution source is statements from Clavicular or his representatives, with a definitive consensus of credible media as a possible secondary source. The same packet also shows the market was created on April 20, 2026 and later displayed a final Yes state after proposed and disputed resolution sequences. The defense does not need to pretend those facts are irrelevant. They explain why this dispute exists.\n\nBut they do not prove the proposition. The preserved primary/platform evidence is the Polymarket page and Gamma/API status material. It proves the rule and the platform result; it does not preserve the original livestream, VOD, clip, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, or UMA voter/proposer record that would show why the market ended Yes. The packet's own primary-evidence assessment says the fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\n\nThat missing link matters because the secondary record is internally conflicted on the very element the plaintiff must prove. Forbes is favorable to plaintiff insofar as it describes a dispute over a streamer who allegedly told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But the Times of India fact-check, also in the packet, says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular. Other packet excerpts describe remarks about wanting children, being a dad in the next few months, or a proposed pregnancy contest. Those are not the same thing as announcing that he and a partner are already expecting a baby through pregnancy.\n\nThe defense theory is therefore straightforward: final Yes resolution is circumstantial evidence of market administration, not a substitute for the qualifying announcement required by the rule. A viral claim repeated through social media, a contest proposal, a future-oriented wish to have children, shock-content banter, or an out-of-context clip does not satisfy a rule that expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes. If plaintiff can later preserve the original source and it shows an unambiguous, credible statement by Clavicular or his representative that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the defense will have to confront it. On the current record, that source is absent.\n\nThe decisive evidence in later phases should be narrow: the full original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript; any statement from Clavicular, a representative, or a publicist; the Polymarket clarification referenced in reporting; UMA transaction-level records showing the basis for the final outcome; and the source chain behind the Forbes characterization and the Domahhhh/Kick Champ leads. Those materials would let the council distinguish a real qualifying announcement from a rumor cycle.\n\nUntil that bridge is built, the plaintiff's strongest proof is that the market resolved Yes and some reporters described the controversy. The defense will show that the rule asks for more: a credible announcement, from the right source or a definitive credible-media consensus, about an existing partner pregnancy. The present packet identifies exactly why that has not yet been proven."}],"prior_council_votes":[{"member_id":"C1","rationale":"The record contains conflicting secondary reports and lacks any primary statement or definitive media consensus confirming a credible announcement; thus the proposition is not more likely than not proven.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C2","rationale":"The admitted record contains conflicting secondary reports and no preserved primary statement from Clavicular announcing an existing partner pregnancy. The preserved quotes describe future-oriented contest/stunt language, and Times of India explicitly states no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy. The final Yes resolution does not establish what evidence the resolver relied upon, and there is no definitive consensus of credible media as the rule requires.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C3","rationale":"The admitted record contains no primary statement confirming a pregnancy announcement and presents conflicting secondary reports, so the proposition is not proven by preponderance.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"}],"rebuttals":[{"phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the defense correctly identifies the record's weakest point: no original VOD, clip, or transcript is preserved. But the defense then treats that gap as dispositive. The market rule does not. It allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, and it also allows a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. That structure matters: the drafters anticipated that the council or resolver might have to decide from credible reporting, not only from a raw stream file.\n\nThe defense also understates the official final Yes. Plaintiff is not asking the council to treat market price as fact. PX-4 and the packet market record show more than price: a proposed Yes, dispute, proposed Yes, dispute, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0] and a resolved official state. That is the platform's resolution mechanism applying the same credibility rule after adversarial challenge. It is circumstantial, but it is unusually probative circumstantial evidence.\n\nThe defense says the Polymarket context describes future vows, a fertility-stack reveal, a dating-show/baby-mama proposal, and debunked girlfriend rumors. Yes, and plaintiff admitted that because unsupported viral reposts should be discounted. But that context does not erase the separate Forbes packet account: Forbes described the dispute as involving a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is not merely \"I want children someday\" language. It is the record's strongest description of an announcement that maps onto the rule.\n\nThe Times of India capture is adverse, but its force is narrower than the defense claims. It debunks the specific viral claim that Clavicular was expecting a first child with a girlfriend he met ten days earlier, and it discusses an out-of-context clip and a pregnancy-contest quote. It does not establish what the UMA resolver considered. It does not preserve the Polymarket clarification. It does not refute Forbes's specific characterization that the dispute concerned a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. And, like Forbes, it is secondary reporting rather than primary video.\n\nSo the evidentiary choice is not \"primary video versus nothing.\" It is whether the official final Yes, reached after two disputes under a rule that permits credible-media consensus, plus Forbes's affirmative characterization, outweighs adverse secondary reporting about a narrower viral rumor and the acknowledged absence of the raw source. On preponderance, plaintiff submits that it does.\n\nThe defense asks the council to infer that the official resolver accepted only a joke, stunt, or debunked rumor. That is possible, but it is not the better-supported inference on this record. The better-supported inference is that the official process credited a qualifying announcement or media-consensus path, even though the underlying primary artifact was not preserved in this packet. The gaps should reduce certainty; they should not convert a final official Yes and a favorable credible-media account into a No finding."}],"submitted_evidence":[{"evidence_id":"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab","size_bytes":3638,"source_description":"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.","source_url":"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026","title":"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market"},{"evidence_id":"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5","size_bytes":2189,"source_description":"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.","source_url":"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms","title":"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor"}],"surrebuttals":[{"phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. The defense is not arguing that a raw VOD is the only legally possible proof. The rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. But that is the point: the record does not contain such a consensus.\n\nWhat the record contains is one favorable Forbes characterization, adverse Times of India reporting that no video or Clavicular statement confirmed pregnancy, Hindustan Times and Express Tribune descriptions of a pregnancy-contest stunt, and an admitted gaps file saying the original stream, transcript, platform clarification, and UMA records are missing. That is not a definitive media consensus. It is a conflicted source chain.\n\nPlaintiff says TOI only debunks the narrower ten-day girlfriend rumor. But the proposition is itself about a partner pregnancy, and TOI’s captured text goes beyond narrow timing: no video confirms a pregnancy; no statement from Clavicular confirms it; the shared clip was out of context; the preserved quote was about wanting children and a pregnancy contest; the viral claim likely came from jokes and out-of-context clips. Those points directly undercut credibility and qualification under a rule that excludes jokes and noncredible announcements.\n\nPlaintiff also asks the council to treat final Yes after disputes as unusually probative. It is probative that the market resolved Yes. It is not probative enough to fill the missing basis for that resolution. The record does not show what the resolver considered, whether it relied on Forbes, the viral Kick Champ rumor, trader pressure, or something else, and it lacks the platform clarification Forbes reportedly said pointed No. Without the source chain, final Yes risks becoming circular proof: the announcement happened because the market resolved Yes, and the market resolved Yes because the announcement happened.\n\nThe preponderance question is not whether plaintiff’s theory is possible. It is whether the qualifying announcement is more likely than not on the admitted record. Given the conflicting media accounts, the absence of the underlying statement, and the admitted context of future vows, stunt framing, and debunked rumors, plaintiff has not crossed that line."}],"technical_reports":[{"phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","summary":"Before filing, plaintiff rescanned the record and evidence list. Target sources were official Polymarket/Gamma records, Forbes reporting, Times of India adverse reporting, the original Kick/VOD or clip, the Polymarket clarification, Domahhhh X thread, Kick Champ source, and UMA records. The Polymarket page was opened and the Gamma API was fetched with python3 urllib; the official rule, final Yes sequence, IDs, outcome prices, and context were preserved as PX-4. The Times of India article was opened and adverse fact-check text was preserved as PX-5. Forbes direct page capture was attempted by web open/search, but no stronger article text than the existing packet capture was obtained in time, so plaintiff relied on PX-3 rather than submitting a search snippet. No original VOD/transcript or full UMA voter record was captured this phase; those remain material gaps affecting weight.","title":"Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger"},{"phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","summary":"Defense rescanned the current record and evidence list, then read the two new plaintiff submissions in full. Source targets considered were the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, Clavicular/representative statements, the Polymarket clarification referenced by Forbes, UMA proposer/disputer/voter records, Forbes source chain, Domahhhh X thread, and Kick Champ source. Opening-phase searches found Forbes, Polymarket, Times of India, Hindustan Times, X Domahhhh, Inkl, Poprant/Indiatimes, Binance, and Lines leads; X thread opening produced no readable text, and no original video/transcript or representative statement was captured. No new defense evidence was submitted because the material defense sources are already admitted through the packet and plaintiff's TOI capture, while uncaptured leads remain unverified. Unresolved gaps remain the original statement, full context, platform clarification, and UMA rationale.","title":"Defense Source-Chain And Gap Ledger"}]}}},"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T07:50:07.017222578Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C4","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":885915,"role_id":"council","turn_number":12}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"get_case"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782804921105}}
{"type":"turn_end","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I need to examine the admitted evidence to ground my vote in the record. Let me first get the case details and list the available evidence."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ytnPFq86t","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_get_case","args":"{}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5","usage":{"input":21441,"output":47,"cacheRead":2352,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":23840,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782804916051,"responseId":"gen-1782804916-M9UzNCP3ATxaNR0aoBQF","responseModel":"mistralai/mistral-medium-3.5-20260430"},"toolResults":[{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ytnPFq86t","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex09-20260630071703\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 885915\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex09-20260630071703\",\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"case\":{\"evidence_standard\":\"Preponderance of the evidence.\",\"member\":{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"model\":\"openrouter://mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5\",\"persona_filename\":\"personas/generic.md\"},\"opportunity\":{\"allowed_tools\":[\"submit_council_vote\"],\"id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"may_pass\":false,\"objective\":\"council vote by C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"role\":\"council\"},\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"proposition\":\"Between market creation on April 20, 2026, and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\",\"record\":{\"arguments\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff's case is strongest where it stays tied to the rule and the source chain. The proposition is not whether a child was born, and not whether every viral repost was accurate. It is whether Clavicular made a credible announcement, within the market window, that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\\n\\nThe official market evidence establishes the governing frame. The packet market page and the newly submitted official Polymarket/Gamma capture show the same rule: Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy; only credible announcements count; jokes do not; statements from Clavicular or representatives are the resolution source, with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting also permitted. The official source also shows the market was proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes again, disputed again, and finally resolved Yes. The Gamma extract fixes the market ID, condition ID, outcomes [Yes, No], outcomePrices [1,0], and resolver/closed-time fields. That is not mere trader gossip. It is the official resolution mechanism applying the very rule before this council.\\n\\nThe best explanation for that official Yes result appears in the case packet's secondary-reporting file. Forbes identified the dispute as being over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That description matters because it directly tracks the rule's central question: a statement by the covered person about having gotten a partner pregnant. Forbes also reported that the disagreement was binary: the market description and platform clarification were said to point No while the price pointed Yes, and the oracle had not closed the gap after two dispute rounds. The subsequent official record now shows the gap closed at Yes.\\n\\nThat sequence is plaintiff's preponderance case. The council can reasonably infer that the UMA/Polymarket final Yes did not arise from a vacuum. It followed a disputed process on a high-volume market whose rule allowed either the speaker's statements or a definitive credible-media consensus. The admitted record contains a credible financial-news account saying the dispute centered on a reported statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, and an official source showing the final resolver accepted Yes. On preponderance, those combined facts make a qualifying announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe defense is right that this proof has a missing primary artifact. The original livestream/VOD/transcript is not in the record. Nor is the full Polymarket clarification or transaction-level UMA voter record. The plaintiff does not ask the council to pretend otherwise. Those gaps reduce weight and make this a circumstantial/source-chain case, not a clean direct-video case.\\n\\nBut the gaps do not erase the official resolution and corroborating media account. The rule itself permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a preserved VOD is not automatically fatal. What matters is whether the admitted record, as a whole, makes the qualifying announcement more probable than the competing account that all of this was only a joke, contest, or rumor. The Forbes packet capture is the clearest pro-Yes secondary source; the official Polymarket/Gamma capture is the clearest official outcome source.\\n\\nThe plaintiff also submitted the Times of India fact-check because the council should see the strongest adverse source. It says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular, and it treats the viral claim as likely false or out of context. The live Polymarket context also cuts both ways: it describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama stunt, while acknowledging debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend pregnancy. That evidence undercuts any claim that every viral pregnancy story was credible.\\n\\nStill, TOI is not a primary record either. It is a fact-check of the rumor cycle, not the market-resolution record. It does not disprove that Clavicular made a qualifying announcement later accepted by the resolver or reflected in Forbes's account. It shows why the council should discount unsupported reposts and distinguish future-oriented fatherhood talk from an announcement of an existing pregnancy. Plaintiff's position survives that distinction because the favorable Forbes account is about a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, while the official resolver ultimately paid Yes under the same credibility standard.\\n\\nSo the plaintiff asks the council to give controlling weight to the official rule-and-resolution evidence, substantial corroborating weight to the Forbes secondary-reporting capture, and appropriate but not dispositive weight to the adverse TOI fact-check. The record is imperfect, but preponderance does not require certainty or medical confirmation. It requires the better answer. Here, the better answer is that the market's final Yes reflected a credible announcement or qualifying credible-media consensus that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy within the covered window.\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s case depends on converting a market result into proof of the underlying fact. The record does not support that conversion.\\n\\nThe rule requires a credible announcement that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. The official market evidence proves the wording, timing, dispute sequence, and final Yes outcome. It does not prove what Clavicular actually said. The packet’s official-source and primary-evidence files say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved and that the fact question remains dependent on locating the underlying stream, clip, transcript, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s new Polymarket/Gamma capture adds official details, but the added context cuts against plaintiff’s theory. It describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, a fertility-stack reveal, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama proposal involving 500 contestants. It separately describes “debunked rumors” of a girlfriend’s pregnancy after ten days. Those are not admissions that he and a partner were already expecting a baby. They are future intent, stunt framing, and rumor framing.\\n\\nThe strongest pro-Yes item is the Forbes excerpt in the secondary-reporting packet saying the dispute concerned a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But in this record Forbes is a summarized secondary account in an article about an oracle dispute, not the underlying video, transcript, source post, or representative statement. The same Forbes excerpt also reported that the market description and platform clarification said No while price said Yes, and that traders alleged the oracle had become a disinformation engine. That is not a clean source chain; it is a warning that market mechanics and trader incentives may have overtaken source proof.\\n\\nThe adverse evidence is more specific about the missing link. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, the actual preserved quote was future-oriented pregnancy-contest language, and the viral claim was false and likely came from jokes, out-of-context clips, and his content style. The secondary-reporting packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries match that: “I must have children,” “I must get children today,” and “I will be a dad in the next few months” were treated as a controversial proposal or stunt, not confirmation of an existing partner pregnancy.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a VOD is not automatically fatal. True, but the record does not show a definitive consensus. It shows conflict: Forbes characterizes the dispute one way; Times of India expressly debunks the girlfriend-pregnancy claim; Hindustan Times and Express Tribune frame the remarks as a contest/stunt; the packet says no primary source or Domahhhh thread text was located. A single favorable secondary characterization plus a final market resolution is not a definitive media consensus, especially where admitted adverse reporting directly denies confirmation.\\n\\nNor should the council give controlling weight to the final Yes state. The official resolver result proves that the market was resolved Yes. It does not reveal the evidence considered, the voters’ rationale, the proposer/disputer record, or whether the resolution rested on the same viral rumor now debunked in the record. The unresolved-gaps file expressly notes the missing UMA records and the missing Polymarket clarification Forbes said pointed No.\\n\\nOn preponderance, the better-supported finding is not that a qualifying announcement happened. It is that there was a viral controversy after market creation, built from future fatherhood talk, a pregnancy-contest stunt, social-media rumors, and a disputed market process that ultimately resolved Yes without preserving the basis. The proposition asks for a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy. The current record proves the controversy and the market result, but it does not prove that announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe defense therefore asks the council to find the proposition not proven on this record.\"}],\"closings\":[{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff does not ask you to decide that every viral post was true, or that the record proves the private medical fact of pregnancy. The proposition is narrower: whether Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the covered window.\\n\\nThe record proves the rule, the timing, and the official resolution. The market text required a credible announcement, excluded jokes, and allowed not only statements from Clavicular or representatives but also a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. The official Polymarket/Gamma evidence then shows proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes, disputed again, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0]. That is not a mere price chart. It is the official resolution process applying the same rule now before this council.\\n\\nThe record also contains the affirmative source-chain link. The secondary-reporting packet preserves Forbes's characterization that the dispute was over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is the key phrase in this case. It is not simply a desire to have children someday. It is a reported statement about having gotten a girl pregnant, which maps directly to the rule's pregnancy-announcement requirement. The final Yes resolution then confirms that the official process ultimately credited the Yes side despite disputes.\\n\\nThe defense's best point is real: the original VOD, transcript, Polymarket clarification, and UMA voter rationale are not in the record. That means the plaintiff's case is not direct-video proof. But preponderance does not demand perfect custody or certainty. It asks which inference is better supported by the admitted record.\\n\\nThe adverse record does not carry the defense over that line. The Times of India capture and the live Polymarket context warn against unsupported girlfriend-rumor reposts, out-of-context clips, future fatherhood talk, and stunt framing. Plaintiff accepts that warning. Those materials show why jokes and rumors should be discounted. They do not establish that the official resolver accepted a joke, and they do not erase Forbes's account of a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. They are secondary reports too; they are not the missing primary video.\\n\\nThe defense's theory requires a larger inference than plaintiff's. It asks you to conclude that, after two disputes, the official final Yes likely rested on nothing more than a noncredible rumor or stunt, even though the rule expressly excluded such material and even though Forbes described the dispute in terms of a pregnancy statement. That is possible, but on this record it is not the more probable account.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's account fits all of the admitted pieces: the rule allowed a credible announcement or credible-media consensus; Forbes reported the relevant announcement framing; the market underwent contested resolution; and the final official state paid Yes. The conflicting adverse reporting explains why the case was disputed and why the source chain is imperfect. It does not make No more likely than Yes.\\n\\nFor that reason, under the preponderance standard, the council should find that the proposition is proven.\"},{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the record leaves this case short of preponderance.\\n\\nThe plaintiff is right about one thing: the proposition is not whether a child was born or whether a pregnancy was medically true. The question is whether Clavicular made a credible qualifying announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. But the record still has to prove that announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe official market evidence proves the rule, the dates, the dispute sequence, and the final Yes state. It does not prove the underlying source. The case-packet official-source and primary-evidence files expressly say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved. The unresolved-gaps file identifies the same missing pieces: original livestream clip, VOD, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, and UMA proposer/disputer/voter records.\\n\\nThat matters because plaintiff’s case turns on a bridge it never fully builds. The bridge is one Forbes characterization that the dispute involved a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, plus the final Yes resolution. But the record does not preserve Forbes’s underlying source chain. And the same secondary-reporting packet records that Forbes described the market description and platform clarification as saying No, while price said Yes, and linked criticism of the oracle process. That is not a clean, independent confirmation of a qualifying announcement.\\n\\nThe contrary evidence is not just noise. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, and it identifies the actual preserved quote as future-oriented pregnancy-contest language. The packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries likewise frame the remarks as a contest or stunt: wanting children, needing children today, and being a dad in the next few months. Plaintiff’s own Polymarket/Gamma capture describes trader consensus as driven by public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, a dating-show/baby-mama stunt, and debunked girlfriend-pregnancy rumors. Those facts fit a rumor and stunt cycle at least as well as they fit a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. It does. But this record is not a consensus. It is a conflict: one favorable Forbes phrasing, adverse fact-checking, multiple contest/stunt accounts, and admitted missing source-chain material. A definitive consensus cannot be inferred from divided secondary reporting.\\n\\nPlaintiff also says the official Yes after disputes is unusually probative. It has some weight, but it cannot carry the burden by itself. The record does not show what the resolver considered or why it resolved Yes. Without the UMA rationale, source material, or platform clarification, final Yes is at risk of circular reasoning: using the market’s outcome to prove the fact that the market outcome was supposed to decide.\\n\\nThe defense is not asking the council to find that no rumor existed, or that no one ever thought Clavicular might make such an announcement. The defense is asking the council to apply the actual proposition and the preponderance standard. On this record, a qualifying credible announcement is not more likely than a nonqualifying mix of future fatherhood talk, a provocative contest proposal, out-of-context clips, and debunked viral claims.\\n\\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition not proven.\"}],\"evidence\":[{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407\",\"size_bytes\":1254,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"04/045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:34Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"size_bytes\":2189,\"source_description\":\"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.\",\"source_url\":\"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\",\"storage_name\":\"55/5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068\",\"size_bytes\":4343,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"79/795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"official-source-record.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0\",\"size_bytes\":1851,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"a7/a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"official-source-record.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"market-page.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5\",\"size_bytes\":2778,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"d1/d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"market-page.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:11Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"size_bytes\":3638,\"source_description\":\"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.\",\"source_url\":\"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\",\"storage_name\":\"f0/f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"primary-evidence.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94\",\"size_bytes\":1589,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"f8/f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"primary-evidence.txt\"}],\"exhibits\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"label\":\"PX-1 Market page packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\\n\\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRule text:\\n\\n\\u003e This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\\n\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\\n\\nEvent:\\n\\n- event id: 400878\\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: true\\n- event closed: true\\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\\n\\nMarket:\\n\\n- market id: 2037907\\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\\n- market closed: true\\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"PX-2 Official source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\n## Polymarket source\\n\\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\n\\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\\n\\n## Clavicular or representative statements\\n\\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\\n\\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\\n\\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\\n\\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\\n\\n## UMA / oracle source\\n\\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"PX-3 Secondary reporting packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"PX-4 Official Polymarket/Gamma merits capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"PX-5 Times of India adverse fact-check capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"PX-6 Record gaps packet file\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"label\":\"DX-1 Market rule and initial final-outcome packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\\n\\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRule text:\\n\\n\\u003e This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\\n\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\\n\\nEvent:\\n\\n- event id: 400878\\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: true\\n- event closed: true\\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\\n\\nMarket:\\n\\n- market id: 2037907\\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\\n- market closed: true\\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"DX-2 Official-source packet record showing missing primary statement and UMA detail\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\n## Polymarket source\\n\\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\n\\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\\n\\n## Clavicular or representative statements\\n\\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\\n\\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\\n\\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\\n\\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\\n\\n## UMA / oracle source\\n\\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence\",\"label\":\"DX-3 Primary-evidence packet assessment of missing underlying proof\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Primary evidence\\n\\n## Preserved primary/platform evidence\\n\\n- Polymarket market page: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Polymarket Gamma API event record: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Captured files: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt; source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json; source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\nThe official market rule requires a credible announcement by Clavicular that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy during the specified window.\\n\\n## Potential primary-source leads not locally preserved\\n\\n- Clavicular's Kick page or VODs: https://kick.com/clavicular/videos, referenced by Hindustan Times.\\n- Domahhhh's April 30 X thread about the oracle dispute: https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218, referenced by Forbes.\\n- JexTrade's April 29 X post about a large No buy, referenced by Forbes.\\n- @holy_moses7 posts claiming the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” referenced by Forbes.\\n- The viral Kick Champ post that Times of India says claimed Clavicular was “expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days ago.” The exact source URL was not captured.\\n\\n## Preliminary source assessment\\n\\nThe preserved primary evidence proves the contract wording and the platform's final Yes state. It does not itself prove that a qualifying credible announcement occurred. The fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"DX-4 Secondary-reporting conflict and adverse context\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"DX-5 Unresolved record gaps\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"DX-6 Plaintiff Polymarket/Gamma capture, including context about vows, stunt, and debunked rumors\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"DX-7 Plaintiff-submitted Times of India adverse fact-check\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"DX-S1 TOI fact-check on no confirming video or Clavicular statement\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"DX-S2 Conflicting secondary reporting and contest/stunt framing\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"DX-S3 Missing original statement, platform clarification, and UMA records\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"DX-S4 Official Polymarket/Gamma capture with market context\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"}],\"openings\":[{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, this case is about a narrow event definition, not about proving the private fact of a pregnancy to medical certainty. The proposition asks whether, after the April 20, 2026 market creation and before the stated deadline, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. Under the preponderance standard, the question is whether the better-supported reading of the available source chain is that a qualifying announcement occurred.\\n\\nThe present case packet already fixes the governing rule and the official market posture. The Polymarket page record states that the market resolves Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy, that only credible announcements qualify, that jokes do not suffice, and that statements from Clavicular or his representatives are the primary resolution source while a definitive consensus of credible media may also be considered. The same official-source packet records the platform/API state: the market went through proposed/disputed sequences and ultimately shows a final Yes outcome.\\n\\nThat matters, but it is not the whole case. A final Yes state is strong circumstantial and procedural evidence that the market's resolver accepted the event as satisfied, but by itself it does not show the exact words, tone, context, or credibility of the underlying announcement. The plaintiff's burden is therefore to connect that official Yes state to the source material that caused it.\\n\\nThe packet points to that connection. Forbes reported the dispute as turning on what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. Other reports described livestream remarks about wanting children or becoming a dad soon, and several sources frame the incident as a viral controversy. Those reports explain why the market moved and why the oracle dispute arose. They support the plaintiff's theory that there was, at minimum, a public announcement or reported announcement that the market treated as sufficient.\\n\\nThe defense will stress the same record's weaknesses. The packet does not yet preserve the original livestream clip, VOD, full transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification mentioned by Forbes, or UMA transaction-level record. The Times of India fact-check says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular; other reporting characterizes the comments as a contest, stunt, joke, or out-of-context viral content. Those are real weight issues because the rule expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes.\\n\\nSo the decisive factual questions are these: first, what exactly did Clavicular say, and was it about an existing partner pregnancy rather than a future desire, stunt, or contest? Second, did the statement occur after market creation? Third, did Clavicular or a representative make it, or did credible media reach the definitive consensus allowed by the rules? Fourth, does the Polymarket/UMA Yes resolution rest on that source chain or on speculation and trader pressure?\\n\\nThe plaintiff expects the later evidentiary phase to focus on the primary artifacts the packet identifies: the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, the Polymarket clarification, the Forbes source capture, the Domahhhh thread, any Kick Champ source, and UMA oracle records. If those materials show that Clavicular publicly stated that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the final Yes outcome and corroborating credible reporting should satisfy preponderance. If the best source instead shows only jokes, wishful remarks, a contest proposal, or unsupported reposts, the plaintiff's case would be materially weaker.\\n\\nFor opening purposes, the plaintiff's theory is disciplined: the official market record and secondary reporting make Yes the more plausible starting point, but the case should be decided by the preserved source chain, not by market price alone.\"},{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense position starts with the market rule itself. This case is not resolved by asking whether a rumor circulated, whether Polymarket ultimately showed a Yes outcome, or whether traders believed a provocative streamer had created controversy. The proposition requires proof, by a preponderance, that Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the relevant window.\\n\\nThe admitted packet proves some important background. The market page record fixes the contract language: only credible announcements qualify; jokes do not; the ordinary resolution source is statements from Clavicular or his representatives, with a definitive consensus of credible media as a possible secondary source. The same packet also shows the market was created on April 20, 2026 and later displayed a final Yes state after proposed and disputed resolution sequences. The defense does not need to pretend those facts are irrelevant. They explain why this dispute exists.\\n\\nBut they do not prove the proposition. The preserved primary/platform evidence is the Polymarket page and Gamma/API status material. It proves the rule and the platform result; it does not preserve the original livestream, VOD, clip, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, or UMA voter/proposer record that would show why the market ended Yes. The packet's own primary-evidence assessment says the fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\\nThat missing link matters because the secondary record is internally conflicted on the very element the plaintiff must prove. Forbes is favorable to plaintiff insofar as it describes a dispute over a streamer who allegedly told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But the Times of India fact-check, also in the packet, says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular. Other packet excerpts describe remarks about wanting children, being a dad in the next few months, or a proposed pregnancy contest. Those are not the same thing as announcing that he and a partner are already expecting a baby through pregnancy.\\n\\nThe defense theory is therefore straightforward: final Yes resolution is circumstantial evidence of market administration, not a substitute for the qualifying announcement required by the rule. A viral claim repeated through social media, a contest proposal, a future-oriented wish to have children, shock-content banter, or an out-of-context clip does not satisfy a rule that expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes. If plaintiff can later preserve the original source and it shows an unambiguous, credible statement by Clavicular or his representative that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the defense will have to confront it. On the current record, that source is absent.\\n\\nThe decisive evidence in later phases should be narrow: the full original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript; any statement from Clavicular, a representative, or a publicist; the Polymarket clarification referenced in reporting; UMA transaction-level records showing the basis for the final outcome; and the source chain behind the Forbes characterization and the Domahhhh/Kick Champ leads. Those materials would let the council distinguish a real qualifying announcement from a rumor cycle.\\n\\nUntil that bridge is built, the plaintiff's strongest proof is that the market resolved Yes and some reporters described the controversy. The defense will show that the rule asks for more: a credible announcement, from the right source or a definitive credible-media consensus, about an existing partner pregnancy. The present packet identifies exactly why that has not yet been proven.\"}],\"prior_council_votes\":[{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The record contains conflicting secondary reports and lacks any primary statement or definitive media consensus confirming a credible announcement; thus the proposition is not more likely than not proven.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record contains conflicting secondary reports and no preserved primary statement from Clavicular announcing an existing partner pregnancy. The preserved quotes describe future-oriented contest/stunt language, and Times of India explicitly states no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy. The final Yes resolution does not establish what evidence the resolver relied upon, and there is no definitive consensus of credible media as the rule requires.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record contains no primary statement confirming a pregnancy announcement and presents conflicting secondary reports, so the proposition is not proven by preponderance.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"}],\"rebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense correctly identifies the record's weakest point: no original VOD, clip, or transcript is preserved. But the defense then treats that gap as dispositive. The market rule does not. It allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, and it also allows a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. That structure matters: the drafters anticipated that the council or resolver might have to decide from credible reporting, not only from a raw stream file.\\n\\nThe defense also understates the official final Yes. Plaintiff is not asking the council to treat market price as fact. PX-4 and the packet market record show more than price: a proposed Yes, dispute, proposed Yes, dispute, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0] and a resolved official state. That is the platform's resolution mechanism applying the same credibility rule after adversarial challenge. It is circumstantial, but it is unusually probative circumstantial evidence.\\n\\nThe defense says the Polymarket context describes future vows, a fertility-stack reveal, a dating-show/baby-mama proposal, and debunked girlfriend rumors. Yes, and plaintiff admitted that because unsupported viral reposts should be discounted. But that context does not erase the separate Forbes packet account: Forbes described the dispute as involving a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is not merely \\\"I want children someday\\\" language. It is the record's strongest description of an announcement that maps onto the rule.\\n\\nThe Times of India capture is adverse, but its force is narrower than the defense claims. It debunks the specific viral claim that Clavicular was expecting a first child with a girlfriend he met ten days earlier, and it discusses an out-of-context clip and a pregnancy-contest quote. It does not establish what the UMA resolver considered. It does not preserve the Polymarket clarification. It does not refute Forbes's specific characterization that the dispute concerned a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. And, like Forbes, it is secondary reporting rather than primary video.\\n\\nSo the evidentiary choice is not \\\"primary video versus nothing.\\\" It is whether the official final Yes, reached after two disputes under a rule that permits credible-media consensus, plus Forbes's affirmative characterization, outweighs adverse secondary reporting about a narrower viral rumor and the acknowledged absence of the raw source. On preponderance, plaintiff submits that it does.\\n\\nThe defense asks the council to infer that the official resolver accepted only a joke, stunt, or debunked rumor. That is possible, but it is not the better-supported inference on this record. The better-supported inference is that the official process credited a qualifying announcement or media-consensus path, even though the underlying primary artifact was not preserved in this packet. The gaps should reduce certainty; they should not convert a final official Yes and a favorable credible-media account into a No finding.\"}],\"submitted_evidence\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"size_bytes\":3638,\"source_description\":\"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.\",\"source_url\":\"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\",\"title\":\"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"size_bytes\":2189,\"source_description\":\"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.\",\"source_url\":\"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\",\"title\":\"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\"}],\"surrebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. The defense is not arguing that a raw VOD is the only legally possible proof. The rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. But that is the point: the record does not contain such a consensus.\\n\\nWhat the record contains is one favorable Forbes characterization, adverse Times of India reporting that no video or Clavicular statement confirmed pregnancy, Hindustan Times and Express Tribune descriptions of a pregnancy-contest stunt, and an admitted gaps file saying the original stream, transcript, platform clarification, and UMA records are missing. That is not a definitive media consensus. It is a conflicted source chain.\\n\\nPlaintiff says TOI only debunks the narrower ten-day girlfriend rumor. But the proposition is itself about a partner pregnancy, and TOI’s captured text goes beyond narrow timing: no video confirms a pregnancy; no statement from Clavicular confirms it; the shared clip was out of context; the preserved quote was about wanting children and a pregnancy contest; the viral claim likely came from jokes and out-of-context clips. Those points directly undercut credibility and qualification under a rule that excludes jokes and noncredible announcements.\\n\\nPlaintiff also asks the council to treat final Yes after disputes as unusually probative. It is probative that the market resolved Yes. It is not probative enough to fill the missing basis for that resolution. The record does not show what the resolver considered, whether it relied on Forbes, the viral Kick Champ rumor, trader pressure, or something else, and it lacks the platform clarification Forbes reportedly said pointed No. Without the source chain, final Yes risks becoming circular proof: the announcement happened because the market resolved Yes, and the market resolved Yes because the announcement happened.\\n\\nThe preponderance question is not whether plaintiff’s theory is possible. It is whether the qualifying announcement is more likely than not on the admitted record. Given the conflicting media accounts, the absence of the underlying statement, and the admitted context of future vows, stunt framing, and debunked rumors, plaintiff has not crossed that line.\"}],\"technical_reports\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Before filing, plaintiff rescanned the record and evidence list. Target sources were official Polymarket/Gamma records, Forbes reporting, Times of India adverse reporting, the original Kick/VOD or clip, the Polymarket clarification, Domahhhh X thread, Kick Champ source, and UMA records. The Polymarket page was opened and the Gamma API was fetched with python3 urllib; the official rule, final Yes sequence, IDs, outcome prices, and context were preserved as PX-4. The Times of India article was opened and adverse fact-check text was preserved as PX-5. Forbes direct page capture was attempted by web open/search, but no stronger article text than the existing packet capture was obtained in time, so plaintiff relied on PX-3 rather than submitting a search snippet. No original VOD/transcript or full UMA voter record was captured this phase; those remain material gaps affecting weight.\",\"title\":\"Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"Defense rescanned the current record and evidence list, then read the two new plaintiff submissions in full. Source targets considered were the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, Clavicular/representative statements, the Polymarket clarification referenced by Forbes, UMA proposer/disputer/voter records, Forbes source chain, Domahhhh X thread, and Kick Champ source. Opening-phase searches found Forbes, Polymarket, Times of India, Hindustan Times, X Domahhhh, Inkl, Poprant/Indiatimes, Binance, and Lines leads; X thread opening produced no readable text, and no original video/transcript or representative statement was captured. No new defense evidence was submitted because the material defense sources are already admitted through the packet and plaintiff's TOI capture, while uncaptured leads remain unverified. Unresolved gaps remain the original statement, full context, platform clarification, and UMA rationale.\",\"title\":\"Defense Source-Chain And Gap Ledger\"}]}}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T07:50:07.017222578Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":885915,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex09-20260630071703\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 885915\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex09-20260630071703\",\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"case\":{\"evidence_standard\":\"Preponderance of the evidence.\",\"member\":{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"model\":\"openrouter://mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5\",\"persona_filename\":\"personas/generic.md\"},\"opportunity\":{\"allowed_tools\":[\"submit_council_vote\"],\"id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"may_pass\":false,\"objective\":\"council vote by C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"role\":\"council\"},\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"proposition\":\"Between market creation on April 20, 2026, and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\",\"record\":{\"arguments\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff's case is strongest where it stays tied to the rule and the source chain. The proposition is not whether a child was born, and not whether every viral repost was accurate. It is whether Clavicular made a credible announcement, within the market window, that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\\n\\nThe official market evidence establishes the governing frame. The packet market page and the newly submitted official Polymarket/Gamma capture show the same rule: Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy; only credible announcements count; jokes do not; statements from Clavicular or representatives are the resolution source, with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting also permitted. The official source also shows the market was proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes again, disputed again, and finally resolved Yes. The Gamma extract fixes the market ID, condition ID, outcomes [Yes, No], outcomePrices [1,0], and resolver/closed-time fields. That is not mere trader gossip. It is the official resolution mechanism applying the very rule before this council.\\n\\nThe best explanation for that official Yes result appears in the case packet's secondary-reporting file. Forbes identified the dispute as being over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That description matters because it directly tracks the rule's central question: a statement by the covered person about having gotten a partner pregnant. Forbes also reported that the disagreement was binary: the market description and platform clarification were said to point No while the price pointed Yes, and the oracle had not closed the gap after two dispute rounds. The subsequent official record now shows the gap closed at Yes.\\n\\nThat sequence is plaintiff's preponderance case. The council can reasonably infer that the UMA/Polymarket final Yes did not arise from a vacuum. It followed a disputed process on a high-volume market whose rule allowed either the speaker's statements or a definitive credible-media consensus. The admitted record contains a credible financial-news account saying the dispute centered on a reported statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, and an official source showing the final resolver accepted Yes. On preponderance, those combined facts make a qualifying announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe defense is right that this proof has a missing primary artifact. The original livestream/VOD/transcript is not in the record. Nor is the full Polymarket clarification or transaction-level UMA voter record. The plaintiff does not ask the council to pretend otherwise. Those gaps reduce weight and make this a circumstantial/source-chain case, not a clean direct-video case.\\n\\nBut the gaps do not erase the official resolution and corroborating media account. The rule itself permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a preserved VOD is not automatically fatal. What matters is whether the admitted record, as a whole, makes the qualifying announcement more probable than the competing account that all of this was only a joke, contest, or rumor. The Forbes packet capture is the clearest pro-Yes secondary source; the official Polymarket/Gamma capture is the clearest official outcome source.\\n\\nThe plaintiff also submitted the Times of India fact-check because the council should see the strongest adverse source. It says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular, and it treats the viral claim as likely false or out of context. The live Polymarket context also cuts both ways: it describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama stunt, while acknowledging debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend pregnancy. That evidence undercuts any claim that every viral pregnancy story was credible.\\n\\nStill, TOI is not a primary record either. It is a fact-check of the rumor cycle, not the market-resolution record. It does not disprove that Clavicular made a qualifying announcement later accepted by the resolver or reflected in Forbes's account. It shows why the council should discount unsupported reposts and distinguish future-oriented fatherhood talk from an announcement of an existing pregnancy. Plaintiff's position survives that distinction because the favorable Forbes account is about a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, while the official resolver ultimately paid Yes under the same credibility standard.\\n\\nSo the plaintiff asks the council to give controlling weight to the official rule-and-resolution evidence, substantial corroborating weight to the Forbes secondary-reporting capture, and appropriate but not dispositive weight to the adverse TOI fact-check. The record is imperfect, but preponderance does not require certainty or medical confirmation. It requires the better answer. Here, the better answer is that the market's final Yes reflected a credible announcement or qualifying credible-media consensus that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy within the covered window.\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s case depends on converting a market result into proof of the underlying fact. The record does not support that conversion.\\n\\nThe rule requires a credible announcement that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. The official market evidence proves the wording, timing, dispute sequence, and final Yes outcome. It does not prove what Clavicular actually said. The packet’s official-source and primary-evidence files say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved and that the fact question remains dependent on locating the underlying stream, clip, transcript, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s new Polymarket/Gamma capture adds official details, but the added context cuts against plaintiff’s theory. It describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, a fertility-stack reveal, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama proposal involving 500 contestants. It separately describes “debunked rumors” of a girlfriend’s pregnancy after ten days. Those are not admissions that he and a partner were already expecting a baby. They are future intent, stunt framing, and rumor framing.\\n\\nThe strongest pro-Yes item is the Forbes excerpt in the secondary-reporting packet saying the dispute concerned a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But in this record Forbes is a summarized secondary account in an article about an oracle dispute, not the underlying video, transcript, source post, or representative statement. The same Forbes excerpt also reported that the market description and platform clarification said No while price said Yes, and that traders alleged the oracle had become a disinformation engine. That is not a clean source chain; it is a warning that market mechanics and trader incentives may have overtaken source proof.\\n\\nThe adverse evidence is more specific about the missing link. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, the actual preserved quote was future-oriented pregnancy-contest language, and the viral claim was false and likely came from jokes, out-of-context clips, and his content style. The secondary-reporting packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries match that: “I must have children,” “I must get children today,” and “I will be a dad in the next few months” were treated as a controversial proposal or stunt, not confirmation of an existing partner pregnancy.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a VOD is not automatically fatal. True, but the record does not show a definitive consensus. It shows conflict: Forbes characterizes the dispute one way; Times of India expressly debunks the girlfriend-pregnancy claim; Hindustan Times and Express Tribune frame the remarks as a contest/stunt; the packet says no primary source or Domahhhh thread text was located. A single favorable secondary characterization plus a final market resolution is not a definitive media consensus, especially where admitted adverse reporting directly denies confirmation.\\n\\nNor should the council give controlling weight to the final Yes state. The official resolver result proves that the market was resolved Yes. It does not reveal the evidence considered, the voters’ rationale, the proposer/disputer record, or whether the resolution rested on the same viral rumor now debunked in the record. The unresolved-gaps file expressly notes the missing UMA records and the missing Polymarket clarification Forbes said pointed No.\\n\\nOn preponderance, the better-supported finding is not that a qualifying announcement happened. It is that there was a viral controversy after market creation, built from future fatherhood talk, a pregnancy-contest stunt, social-media rumors, and a disputed market process that ultimately resolved Yes without preserving the basis. The proposition asks for a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy. The current record proves the controversy and the market result, but it does not prove that announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe defense therefore asks the council to find the proposition not proven on this record.\"}],\"closings\":[{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff does not ask you to decide that every viral post was true, or that the record proves the private medical fact of pregnancy. The proposition is narrower: whether Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the covered window.\\n\\nThe record proves the rule, the timing, and the official resolution. The market text required a credible announcement, excluded jokes, and allowed not only statements from Clavicular or representatives but also a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. The official Polymarket/Gamma evidence then shows proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes, disputed again, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0]. That is not a mere price chart. It is the official resolution process applying the same rule now before this council.\\n\\nThe record also contains the affirmative source-chain link. The secondary-reporting packet preserves Forbes's characterization that the dispute was over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is the key phrase in this case. It is not simply a desire to have children someday. It is a reported statement about having gotten a girl pregnant, which maps directly to the rule's pregnancy-announcement requirement. The final Yes resolution then confirms that the official process ultimately credited the Yes side despite disputes.\\n\\nThe defense's best point is real: the original VOD, transcript, Polymarket clarification, and UMA voter rationale are not in the record. That means the plaintiff's case is not direct-video proof. But preponderance does not demand perfect custody or certainty. It asks which inference is better supported by the admitted record.\\n\\nThe adverse record does not carry the defense over that line. The Times of India capture and the live Polymarket context warn against unsupported girlfriend-rumor reposts, out-of-context clips, future fatherhood talk, and stunt framing. Plaintiff accepts that warning. Those materials show why jokes and rumors should be discounted. They do not establish that the official resolver accepted a joke, and they do not erase Forbes's account of a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. They are secondary reports too; they are not the missing primary video.\\n\\nThe defense's theory requires a larger inference than plaintiff's. It asks you to conclude that, after two disputes, the official final Yes likely rested on nothing more than a noncredible rumor or stunt, even though the rule expressly excluded such material and even though Forbes described the dispute in terms of a pregnancy statement. That is possible, but on this record it is not the more probable account.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's account fits all of the admitted pieces: the rule allowed a credible announcement or credible-media consensus; Forbes reported the relevant announcement framing; the market underwent contested resolution; and the final official state paid Yes. The conflicting adverse reporting explains why the case was disputed and why the source chain is imperfect. It does not make No more likely than Yes.\\n\\nFor that reason, under the preponderance standard, the council should find that the proposition is proven.\"},{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the record leaves this case short of preponderance.\\n\\nThe plaintiff is right about one thing: the proposition is not whether a child was born or whether a pregnancy was medically true. The question is whether Clavicular made a credible qualifying announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. But the record still has to prove that announcement more likely than not.\\n\\nThe official market evidence proves the rule, the dates, the dispute sequence, and the final Yes state. It does not prove the underlying source. The case-packet official-source and primary-evidence files expressly say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved. The unresolved-gaps file identifies the same missing pieces: original livestream clip, VOD, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, and UMA proposer/disputer/voter records.\\n\\nThat matters because plaintiff’s case turns on a bridge it never fully builds. The bridge is one Forbes characterization that the dispute involved a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, plus the final Yes resolution. But the record does not preserve Forbes’s underlying source chain. And the same secondary-reporting packet records that Forbes described the market description and platform clarification as saying No, while price said Yes, and linked criticism of the oracle process. That is not a clean, independent confirmation of a qualifying announcement.\\n\\nThe contrary evidence is not just noise. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, and it identifies the actual preserved quote as future-oriented pregnancy-contest language. The packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries likewise frame the remarks as a contest or stunt: wanting children, needing children today, and being a dad in the next few months. Plaintiff’s own Polymarket/Gamma capture describes trader consensus as driven by public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, a dating-show/baby-mama stunt, and debunked girlfriend-pregnancy rumors. Those facts fit a rumor and stunt cycle at least as well as they fit a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. It does. But this record is not a consensus. It is a conflict: one favorable Forbes phrasing, adverse fact-checking, multiple contest/stunt accounts, and admitted missing source-chain material. A definitive consensus cannot be inferred from divided secondary reporting.\\n\\nPlaintiff also says the official Yes after disputes is unusually probative. It has some weight, but it cannot carry the burden by itself. The record does not show what the resolver considered or why it resolved Yes. Without the UMA rationale, source material, or platform clarification, final Yes is at risk of circular reasoning: using the market’s outcome to prove the fact that the market outcome was supposed to decide.\\n\\nThe defense is not asking the council to find that no rumor existed, or that no one ever thought Clavicular might make such an announcement. The defense is asking the council to apply the actual proposition and the preponderance standard. On this record, a qualifying credible announcement is not more likely than a nonqualifying mix of future fatherhood talk, a provocative contest proposal, out-of-context clips, and debunked viral claims.\\n\\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition not proven.\"}],\"evidence\":[{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407\",\"size_bytes\":1254,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"04/045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:34Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"size_bytes\":2189,\"source_description\":\"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.\",\"source_url\":\"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\",\"storage_name\":\"55/5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068\",\"size_bytes\":4343,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"79/795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"official-source-record.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0\",\"size_bytes\":1851,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"a7/a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"official-source-record.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"market-page.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5\",\"size_bytes\":2778,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"d1/d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"market-page.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:11Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"size_bytes\":3638,\"source_description\":\"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.\",\"source_url\":\"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\",\"storage_name\":\"f0/f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"primary-evidence.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94\",\"size_bytes\":1589,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"f8/f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"primary-evidence.txt\"}],\"exhibits\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"label\":\"PX-1 Market page packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\\n\\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRule text:\\n\\n\\u003e This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\\n\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\\n\\nEvent:\\n\\n- event id: 400878\\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: true\\n- event closed: true\\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\\n\\nMarket:\\n\\n- market id: 2037907\\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\\n- market closed: true\\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"PX-2 Official source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\n## Polymarket source\\n\\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\n\\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\\n\\n## Clavicular or representative statements\\n\\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\\n\\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\\n\\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\\n\\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\\n\\n## UMA / oracle source\\n\\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"PX-3 Secondary reporting packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"PX-4 Official Polymarket/Gamma merits capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"PX-5 Times of India adverse fact-check capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"PX-6 Record gaps packet file\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page\",\"label\":\"DX-1 Market rule and initial final-outcome packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\\n\\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRule text:\\n\\n\\u003e This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\u003e\\n\\u003e The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\\n\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\\n\\nEvent:\\n\\n- event id: 400878\\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: true\\n- event closed: true\\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\\n\\nMarket:\\n\\n- market id: 2037907\\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\\n- market closed: true\\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"DX-2 Official-source packet record showing missing primary statement and UMA detail\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\n## Polymarket source\\n\\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\n\\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\\n\\n## Clavicular or representative statements\\n\\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\\n\\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\\n\\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\\n\\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\\n\\n## UMA / oracle source\\n\\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence\",\"label\":\"DX-3 Primary-evidence packet assessment of missing underlying proof\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Primary evidence\\n\\n## Preserved primary/platform evidence\\n\\n- Polymarket market page: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Polymarket Gamma API event record: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- Captured files: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt; source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json; source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\\n\\nThe official market rule requires a credible announcement by Clavicular that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy during the specified window.\\n\\n## Potential primary-source leads not locally preserved\\n\\n- Clavicular's Kick page or VODs: https://kick.com/clavicular/videos, referenced by Hindustan Times.\\n- Domahhhh's April 30 X thread about the oracle dispute: https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218, referenced by Forbes.\\n- JexTrade's April 29 X post about a large No buy, referenced by Forbes.\\n- @holy_moses7 posts claiming the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” referenced by Forbes.\\n- The viral Kick Champ post that Times of India says claimed Clavicular was “expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days ago.” The exact source URL was not captured.\\n\\n## Preliminary source assessment\\n\\nThe preserved primary evidence proves the contract wording and the platform's final Yes state. It does not itself prove that a qualifying credible announcement occurred. The fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"DX-4 Secondary-reporting conflict and adverse context\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"DX-5 Unresolved record gaps\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"DX-6 Plaintiff Polymarket/Gamma capture, including context about vows, stunt, and debunked rumors\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"DX-7 Plaintiff-submitted Times of India adverse fact-check\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"label\":\"DX-S1 TOI fact-check on no confirming video or Clavicular statement\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\\n\\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \\\"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\\\"\\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says: \\\"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\\\"\\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \\\"pregnancy contest\\\" and quotes: \\\"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\\\"\\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"DX-S2 Conflicting secondary reporting and contest/stunt framing\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\\n\\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\\n\\n## Times of India fact check\\n\\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\\n\\n## Hindustan Times\\n\\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\\n\\n## The Express Tribune\\n\\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\\n\\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\\n\\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\\n\\n## Search notes\\n\\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"DX-S3 Missing original statement, platform clarification, and UMA records\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"label\":\"DX-S4 Official Polymarket/Gamma capture with market context\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\n\\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\\nSources:\\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\\n\\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDisplayed probability: \\u003e99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\\n\\nRules text shown on page:\\nThis market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \\\"No\\\".\\n\\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\\n\\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\\n\\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\\n- Disputed\\n- Final outcome: Yes\\n\\nMarket context text shown on page:\\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \\\"dating show\\\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\\n\\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\\n\\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\\n\\n## Gamma API fields observed\\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\\nEvent id: 400878.\\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nDescription: same rules text as above.\\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\\nEvent active: true.\\nEvent closed: true.\\nEvent archived: false.\\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\\nMarket id: 2037907.\\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\\nOutcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"].\\nOutcome prices: [\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"].\\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\\n\\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase.\"}],\"openings\":[{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, this case is about a narrow event definition, not about proving the private fact of a pregnancy to medical certainty. The proposition asks whether, after the April 20, 2026 market creation and before the stated deadline, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. Under the preponderance standard, the question is whether the better-supported reading of the available source chain is that a qualifying announcement occurred.\\n\\nThe present case packet already fixes the governing rule and the official market posture. The Polymarket page record states that the market resolves Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy, that only credible announcements qualify, that jokes do not suffice, and that statements from Clavicular or his representatives are the primary resolution source while a definitive consensus of credible media may also be considered. The same official-source packet records the platform/API state: the market went through proposed/disputed sequences and ultimately shows a final Yes outcome.\\n\\nThat matters, but it is not the whole case. A final Yes state is strong circumstantial and procedural evidence that the market's resolver accepted the event as satisfied, but by itself it does not show the exact words, tone, context, or credibility of the underlying announcement. The plaintiff's burden is therefore to connect that official Yes state to the source material that caused it.\\n\\nThe packet points to that connection. Forbes reported the dispute as turning on what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. Other reports described livestream remarks about wanting children or becoming a dad soon, and several sources frame the incident as a viral controversy. Those reports explain why the market moved and why the oracle dispute arose. They support the plaintiff's theory that there was, at minimum, a public announcement or reported announcement that the market treated as sufficient.\\n\\nThe defense will stress the same record's weaknesses. The packet does not yet preserve the original livestream clip, VOD, full transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification mentioned by Forbes, or UMA transaction-level record. The Times of India fact-check says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular; other reporting characterizes the comments as a contest, stunt, joke, or out-of-context viral content. Those are real weight issues because the rule expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes.\\n\\nSo the decisive factual questions are these: first, what exactly did Clavicular say, and was it about an existing partner pregnancy rather than a future desire, stunt, or contest? Second, did the statement occur after market creation? Third, did Clavicular or a representative make it, or did credible media reach the definitive consensus allowed by the rules? Fourth, does the Polymarket/UMA Yes resolution rest on that source chain or on speculation and trader pressure?\\n\\nThe plaintiff expects the later evidentiary phase to focus on the primary artifacts the packet identifies: the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, the Polymarket clarification, the Forbes source capture, the Domahhhh thread, any Kick Champ source, and UMA oracle records. If those materials show that Clavicular publicly stated that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the final Yes outcome and corroborating credible reporting should satisfy preponderance. If the best source instead shows only jokes, wishful remarks, a contest proposal, or unsupported reposts, the plaintiff's case would be materially weaker.\\n\\nFor opening purposes, the plaintiff's theory is disciplined: the official market record and secondary reporting make Yes the more plausible starting point, but the case should be decided by the preserved source chain, not by market price alone.\"},{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense position starts with the market rule itself. This case is not resolved by asking whether a rumor circulated, whether Polymarket ultimately showed a Yes outcome, or whether traders believed a provocative streamer had created controversy. The proposition requires proof, by a preponderance, that Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the relevant window.\\n\\nThe admitted packet proves some important background. The market page record fixes the contract language: only credible announcements qualify; jokes do not; the ordinary resolution source is statements from Clavicular or his representatives, with a definitive consensus of credible media as a possible secondary source. The same packet also shows the market was created on April 20, 2026 and later displayed a final Yes state after proposed and disputed resolution sequences. The defense does not need to pretend those facts are irrelevant. They explain why this dispute exists.\\n\\nBut they do not prove the proposition. The preserved primary/platform evidence is the Polymarket page and Gamma/API status material. It proves the rule and the platform result; it does not preserve the original livestream, VOD, clip, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, or UMA voter/proposer record that would show why the market ended Yes. The packet's own primary-evidence assessment says the fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\\n\\nThat missing link matters because the secondary record is internally conflicted on the very element the plaintiff must prove. Forbes is favorable to plaintiff insofar as it describes a dispute over a streamer who allegedly told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But the Times of India fact-check, also in the packet, says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular. Other packet excerpts describe remarks about wanting children, being a dad in the next few months, or a proposed pregnancy contest. Those are not the same thing as announcing that he and a partner are already expecting a baby through pregnancy.\\n\\nThe defense theory is therefore straightforward: final Yes resolution is circumstantial evidence of market administration, not a substitute for the qualifying announcement required by the rule. A viral claim repeated through social media, a contest proposal, a future-oriented wish to have children, shock-content banter, or an out-of-context clip does not satisfy a rule that expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes. If plaintiff can later preserve the original source and it shows an unambiguous, credible statement by Clavicular or his representative that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the defense will have to confront it. On the current record, that source is absent.\\n\\nThe decisive evidence in later phases should be narrow: the full original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript; any statement from Clavicular, a representative, or a publicist; the Polymarket clarification referenced in reporting; UMA transaction-level records showing the basis for the final outcome; and the source chain behind the Forbes characterization and the Domahhhh/Kick Champ leads. Those materials would let the council distinguish a real qualifying announcement from a rumor cycle.\\n\\nUntil that bridge is built, the plaintiff's strongest proof is that the market resolved Yes and some reporters described the controversy. The defense will show that the rule asks for more: a credible announcement, from the right source or a definitive credible-media consensus, about an existing partner pregnancy. The present packet identifies exactly why that has not yet been proven.\"}],\"prior_council_votes\":[{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The record contains conflicting secondary reports and lacks any primary statement or definitive media consensus confirming a credible announcement; thus the proposition is not more likely than not proven.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record contains conflicting secondary reports and no preserved primary statement from Clavicular announcing an existing partner pregnancy. The preserved quotes describe future-oriented contest/stunt language, and Times of India explicitly states no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy. The final Yes resolution does not establish what evidence the resolver relied upon, and there is no definitive consensus of credible media as the rule requires.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record contains no primary statement confirming a pregnancy announcement and presents conflicting secondary reports, so the proposition is not proven by preponderance.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"}],\"rebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense correctly identifies the record's weakest point: no original VOD, clip, or transcript is preserved. But the defense then treats that gap as dispositive. The market rule does not. It allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, and it also allows a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. That structure matters: the drafters anticipated that the council or resolver might have to decide from credible reporting, not only from a raw stream file.\\n\\nThe defense also understates the official final Yes. Plaintiff is not asking the council to treat market price as fact. PX-4 and the packet market record show more than price: a proposed Yes, dispute, proposed Yes, dispute, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0] and a resolved official state. That is the platform's resolution mechanism applying the same credibility rule after adversarial challenge. It is circumstantial, but it is unusually probative circumstantial evidence.\\n\\nThe defense says the Polymarket context describes future vows, a fertility-stack reveal, a dating-show/baby-mama proposal, and debunked girlfriend rumors. Yes, and plaintiff admitted that because unsupported viral reposts should be discounted. But that context does not erase the separate Forbes packet account: Forbes described the dispute as involving a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is not merely \\\"I want children someday\\\" language. It is the record's strongest description of an announcement that maps onto the rule.\\n\\nThe Times of India capture is adverse, but its force is narrower than the defense claims. It debunks the specific viral claim that Clavicular was expecting a first child with a girlfriend he met ten days earlier, and it discusses an out-of-context clip and a pregnancy-contest quote. It does not establish what the UMA resolver considered. It does not preserve the Polymarket clarification. It does not refute Forbes's specific characterization that the dispute concerned a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. And, like Forbes, it is secondary reporting rather than primary video.\\n\\nSo the evidentiary choice is not \\\"primary video versus nothing.\\\" It is whether the official final Yes, reached after two disputes under a rule that permits credible-media consensus, plus Forbes's affirmative characterization, outweighs adverse secondary reporting about a narrower viral rumor and the acknowledged absence of the raw source. On preponderance, plaintiff submits that it does.\\n\\nThe defense asks the council to infer that the official resolver accepted only a joke, stunt, or debunked rumor. That is possible, but it is not the better-supported inference on this record. The better-supported inference is that the official process credited a qualifying announcement or media-consensus path, even though the underlying primary artifact was not preserved in this packet. The gaps should reduce certainty; they should not convert a final official Yes and a favorable credible-media account into a No finding.\"}],\"submitted_evidence\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab\",\"size_bytes\":3638,\"source_description\":\"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.\",\"source_url\":\"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\",\"title\":\"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5\",\"size_bytes\":2189,\"source_description\":\"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.\",\"source_url\":\"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\",\"title\":\"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\"}],\"surrebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. The defense is not arguing that a raw VOD is the only legally possible proof. The rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. But that is the point: the record does not contain such a consensus.\\n\\nWhat the record contains is one favorable Forbes characterization, adverse Times of India reporting that no video or Clavicular statement confirmed pregnancy, Hindustan Times and Express Tribune descriptions of a pregnancy-contest stunt, and an admitted gaps file saying the original stream, transcript, platform clarification, and UMA records are missing. That is not a definitive media consensus. It is a conflicted source chain.\\n\\nPlaintiff says TOI only debunks the narrower ten-day girlfriend rumor. But the proposition is itself about a partner pregnancy, and TOI’s captured text goes beyond narrow timing: no video confirms a pregnancy; no statement from Clavicular confirms it; the shared clip was out of context; the preserved quote was about wanting children and a pregnancy contest; the viral claim likely came from jokes and out-of-context clips. Those points directly undercut credibility and qualification under a rule that excludes jokes and noncredible announcements.\\n\\nPlaintiff also asks the council to treat final Yes after disputes as unusually probative. It is probative that the market resolved Yes. It is not probative enough to fill the missing basis for that resolution. The record does not show what the resolver considered, whether it relied on Forbes, the viral Kick Champ rumor, trader pressure, or something else, and it lacks the platform clarification Forbes reportedly said pointed No. Without the source chain, final Yes risks becoming circular proof: the announcement happened because the market resolved Yes, and the market resolved Yes because the announcement happened.\\n\\nThe preponderance question is not whether plaintiff’s theory is possible. It is whether the qualifying announcement is more likely than not on the admitted record. Given the conflicting media accounts, the absence of the underlying statement, and the admitted context of future vows, stunt framing, and debunked rumors, plaintiff has not crossed that line.\"}],\"technical_reports\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Before filing, plaintiff rescanned the record and evidence list. Target sources were official Polymarket/Gamma records, Forbes reporting, Times of India adverse reporting, the original Kick/VOD or clip, the Polymarket clarification, Domahhhh X thread, Kick Champ source, and UMA records. The Polymarket page was opened and the Gamma API was fetched with python3 urllib; the official rule, final Yes sequence, IDs, outcome prices, and context were preserved as PX-4. The Times of India article was opened and adverse fact-check text was preserved as PX-5. Forbes direct page capture was attempted by web open/search, but no stronger article text than the existing packet capture was obtained in time, so plaintiff relied on PX-3 rather than submitting a search snippet. No original VOD/transcript or full UMA voter record was captured this phase; those remain material gaps affecting weight.\",\"title\":\"Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"Defense rescanned the current record and evidence list, then read the two new plaintiff submissions in full. Source targets considered were the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, Clavicular/representative statements, the Polymarket clarification referenced by Forbes, UMA proposer/disputer/voter records, Forbes source chain, Domahhhh X thread, and Kick Champ source. Opening-phase searches found Forbes, Polymarket, Times of India, Hindustan Times, X Domahhhh, Inkl, Poprant/Indiatimes, Binance, and Lines leads; X thread opening produced no readable text, and no original video/transcript or representative statement was captured. No new defense evidence was submitted because the material defense sources are already admitted through the packet and plaintiff's TOI capture, while uncaptured leads remain unverified. Unresolved gaps remain the original statement, full context, platform clarification, and UMA rationale.\",\"title\":\"Defense Source-Chain And Gap Ledger\"}]}}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T07:50:07.017222578Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":885915,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12}}"}],"structuredContent":{"case_id":"arb-ex09-20260630071703","member_id":"C4","ok":true,"result":{"case":{"evidence_standard":"Preponderance of the evidence.","member":{"member_id":"C4","model":"openrouter://mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5","persona_filename":"personas/generic.md"},"opportunity":{"allowed_tools":["submit_council_vote"],"id":"deliberation:1:C4","may_pass":false,"objective":"council vote by C4","phase":"deliberation","role":"council"},"phase":"deliberation","proposition":"Between market creation on April 20, 2026, and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.","record":{"arguments":[{"phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the plaintiff's case is strongest where it stays tied to the rule and the source chain. The proposition is not whether a child was born, and not whether every viral repost was accurate. It is whether Clavicular made a credible announcement, within the market window, that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy.\n\nThe official market evidence establishes the governing frame. The packet market page and the newly submitted official Polymarket/Gamma capture show the same rule: Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy; only credible announcements count; jokes do not; statements from Clavicular or representatives are the resolution source, with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting also permitted. The official source also shows the market was proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes again, disputed again, and finally resolved Yes. The Gamma extract fixes the market ID, condition ID, outcomes [Yes, No], outcomePrices [1,0], and resolver/closed-time fields. That is not mere trader gossip. It is the official resolution mechanism applying the very rule before this council.\n\nThe best explanation for that official Yes result appears in the case packet's secondary-reporting file. Forbes identified the dispute as being over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That description matters because it directly tracks the rule's central question: a statement by the covered person about having gotten a partner pregnant. Forbes also reported that the disagreement was binary: the market description and platform clarification were said to point No while the price pointed Yes, and the oracle had not closed the gap after two dispute rounds. The subsequent official record now shows the gap closed at Yes.\n\nThat sequence is plaintiff's preponderance case. The council can reasonably infer that the UMA/Polymarket final Yes did not arise from a vacuum. It followed a disputed process on a high-volume market whose rule allowed either the speaker's statements or a definitive credible-media consensus. The admitted record contains a credible financial-news account saying the dispute centered on a reported statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, and an official source showing the final resolver accepted Yes. On preponderance, those combined facts make a qualifying announcement more likely than not.\n\nThe defense is right that this proof has a missing primary artifact. The original livestream/VOD/transcript is not in the record. Nor is the full Polymarket clarification or transaction-level UMA voter record. The plaintiff does not ask the council to pretend otherwise. Those gaps reduce weight and make this a circumstantial/source-chain case, not a clean direct-video case.\n\nBut the gaps do not erase the official resolution and corroborating media account. The rule itself permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a preserved VOD is not automatically fatal. What matters is whether the admitted record, as a whole, makes the qualifying announcement more probable than the competing account that all of this was only a joke, contest, or rumor. The Forbes packet capture is the clearest pro-Yes secondary source; the official Polymarket/Gamma capture is the clearest official outcome source.\n\nThe plaintiff also submitted the Times of India fact-check because the council should see the strongest adverse source. It says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular, and it treats the viral claim as likely false or out of context. The live Polymarket context also cuts both ways: it describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama stunt, while acknowledging debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend pregnancy. That evidence undercuts any claim that every viral pregnancy story was credible.\n\nStill, TOI is not a primary record either. It is a fact-check of the rumor cycle, not the market-resolution record. It does not disprove that Clavicular made a qualifying announcement later accepted by the resolver or reflected in Forbes's account. It shows why the council should discount unsupported reposts and distinguish future-oriented fatherhood talk from an announcement of an existing pregnancy. Plaintiff's position survives that distinction because the favorable Forbes account is about a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant, while the official resolver ultimately paid Yes under the same credibility standard.\n\nSo the plaintiff asks the council to give controlling weight to the official rule-and-resolution evidence, substantial corroborating weight to the Forbes secondary-reporting capture, and appropriate but not dispositive weight to the adverse TOI fact-check. The record is imperfect, but preponderance does not require certainty or medical confirmation. It requires the better answer. Here, the better answer is that the market's final Yes reflected a credible announcement or qualifying credible-media consensus that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy within the covered window."},{"phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, plaintiff’s case depends on converting a market result into proof of the underlying fact. The record does not support that conversion.\n\nThe rule requires a credible announcement that Clavicular and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. The official market evidence proves the wording, timing, dispute sequence, and final Yes outcome. It does not prove what Clavicular actually said. The packet’s official-source and primary-evidence files say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved and that the fact question remains dependent on locating the underlying stream, clip, transcript, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\n\nPlaintiff’s new Polymarket/Gamma capture adds official details, but the added context cuts against plaintiff’s theory. It describes trader consensus as driven by repeated public vows to become a father, a fertility-stack reveal, and a controversial dating-show/baby-mama proposal involving 500 contestants. It separately describes “debunked rumors” of a girlfriend’s pregnancy after ten days. Those are not admissions that he and a partner were already expecting a baby. They are future intent, stunt framing, and rumor framing.\n\nThe strongest pro-Yes item is the Forbes excerpt in the secondary-reporting packet saying the dispute concerned a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But in this record Forbes is a summarized secondary account in an article about an oracle dispute, not the underlying video, transcript, source post, or representative statement. The same Forbes excerpt also reported that the market description and platform clarification said No while price said Yes, and that traders alleged the oracle had become a disinformation engine. That is not a clean source chain; it is a warning that market mechanics and trader incentives may have overtaken source proof.\n\nThe adverse evidence is more specific about the missing link. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, the actual preserved quote was future-oriented pregnancy-contest language, and the viral claim was false and likely came from jokes, out-of-context clips, and his content style. The secondary-reporting packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries match that: “I must have children,” “I must get children today,” and “I will be a dad in the next few months” were treated as a controversial proposal or stunt, not confirmation of an existing partner pregnancy.\n\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting, so the absence of a VOD is not automatically fatal. True, but the record does not show a definitive consensus. It shows conflict: Forbes characterizes the dispute one way; Times of India expressly debunks the girlfriend-pregnancy claim; Hindustan Times and Express Tribune frame the remarks as a contest/stunt; the packet says no primary source or Domahhhh thread text was located. A single favorable secondary characterization plus a final market resolution is not a definitive media consensus, especially where admitted adverse reporting directly denies confirmation.\n\nNor should the council give controlling weight to the final Yes state. The official resolver result proves that the market was resolved Yes. It does not reveal the evidence considered, the voters’ rationale, the proposer/disputer record, or whether the resolution rested on the same viral rumor now debunked in the record. The unresolved-gaps file expressly notes the missing UMA records and the missing Polymarket clarification Forbes said pointed No.\n\nOn preponderance, the better-supported finding is not that a qualifying announcement happened. It is that there was a viral controversy after market creation, built from future fatherhood talk, a pregnancy-contest stunt, social-media rumors, and a disputed market process that ultimately resolved Yes without preserving the basis. The proposition asks for a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy. The current record proves the controversy and the market result, but it does not prove that announcement more likely than not.\n\nThe defense therefore asks the council to find the proposition not proven on this record."}],"closings":[{"phase":"closings","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the plaintiff does not ask you to decide that every viral post was true, or that the record proves the private medical fact of pregnancy. The proposition is narrower: whether Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the covered window.\n\nThe record proves the rule, the timing, and the official resolution. The market text required a credible announcement, excluded jokes, and allowed not only statements from Clavicular or representatives but also a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. The official Polymarket/Gamma evidence then shows proposed Yes, disputed, proposed Yes, disputed again, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0]. That is not a mere price chart. It is the official resolution process applying the same rule now before this council.\n\nThe record also contains the affirmative source-chain link. The secondary-reporting packet preserves Forbes's characterization that the dispute was over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is the key phrase in this case. It is not simply a desire to have children someday. It is a reported statement about having gotten a girl pregnant, which maps directly to the rule's pregnancy-announcement requirement. The final Yes resolution then confirms that the official process ultimately credited the Yes side despite disputes.\n\nThe defense's best point is real: the original VOD, transcript, Polymarket clarification, and UMA voter rationale are not in the record. That means the plaintiff's case is not direct-video proof. But preponderance does not demand perfect custody or certainty. It asks which inference is better supported by the admitted record.\n\nThe adverse record does not carry the defense over that line. The Times of India capture and the live Polymarket context warn against unsupported girlfriend-rumor reposts, out-of-context clips, future fatherhood talk, and stunt framing. Plaintiff accepts that warning. Those materials show why jokes and rumors should be discounted. They do not establish that the official resolver accepted a joke, and they do not erase Forbes's account of a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. They are secondary reports too; they are not the missing primary video.\n\nThe defense's theory requires a larger inference than plaintiff's. It asks you to conclude that, after two disputes, the official final Yes likely rested on nothing more than a noncredible rumor or stunt, even though the rule expressly excluded such material and even though Forbes described the dispute in terms of a pregnancy statement. That is possible, but on this record it is not the more probable account.\n\nThe plaintiff's account fits all of the admitted pieces: the rule allowed a credible announcement or credible-media consensus; Forbes reported the relevant announcement framing; the market underwent contested resolution; and the final official state paid Yes. The conflicting adverse reporting explains why the case was disputed and why the source chain is imperfect. It does not make No more likely than Yes.\n\nFor that reason, under the preponderance standard, the council should find that the proposition is proven."},{"phase":"closings","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the record leaves this case short of preponderance.\n\nThe plaintiff is right about one thing: the proposition is not whether a child was born or whether a pregnancy was medically true. The question is whether Clavicular made a credible qualifying announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. But the record still has to prove that announcement more likely than not.\n\nThe official market evidence proves the rule, the dates, the dispute sequence, and the final Yes state. It does not prove the underlying source. The case-packet official-source and primary-evidence files expressly say no primary Clavicular or representative statement was preserved. The unresolved-gaps file identifies the same missing pieces: original livestream clip, VOD, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, and UMA proposer/disputer/voter records.\n\nThat matters because plaintiff’s case turns on a bridge it never fully builds. The bridge is one Forbes characterization that the dispute involved a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, plus the final Yes resolution. But the record does not preserve Forbes’s underlying source chain. And the same secondary-reporting packet records that Forbes described the market description and platform clarification as saying No, while price said Yes, and linked criticism of the oracle process. That is not a clean, independent confirmation of a qualifying announcement.\n\nThe contrary evidence is not just noise. The submitted Times of India capture says no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it. It says the shared clip was out of context, and it identifies the actual preserved quote as future-oriented pregnancy-contest language. The packet’s Hindustan Times and Express Tribune summaries likewise frame the remarks as a contest or stunt: wanting children, needing children today, and being a dad in the next few months. Plaintiff’s own Polymarket/Gamma capture describes trader consensus as driven by public vows to become a father, fertility-stack talk, a dating-show/baby-mama stunt, and debunked girlfriend-pregnancy rumors. Those facts fit a rumor and stunt cycle at least as well as they fit a credible announcement of an existing partner pregnancy.\n\nPlaintiff says the rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. It does. But this record is not a consensus. It is a conflict: one favorable Forbes phrasing, adverse fact-checking, multiple contest/stunt accounts, and admitted missing source-chain material. A definitive consensus cannot be inferred from divided secondary reporting.\n\nPlaintiff also says the official Yes after disputes is unusually probative. It has some weight, but it cannot carry the burden by itself. The record does not show what the resolver considered or why it resolved Yes. Without the UMA rationale, source material, or platform clarification, final Yes is at risk of circular reasoning: using the market’s outcome to prove the fact that the market outcome was supposed to decide.\n\nThe defense is not asking the council to find that no rumor existed, or that no one ever thought Clavicular might make such an announcement. The defense is asking the council to apply the actual proposition and the preponderance standard. On this record, a qualifying credible announcement is not more likely than a nonqualifying mix of future fatherhood talk, a provocative contest proposal, out-of-context clips, and debunked viral claims.\n\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition not proven."}],"evidence":[{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z","evidence_id":"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"unresolved-record-gaps.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407","size_bytes":1254,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"04/045c38eca93e3e04c18cac0d2c5d0c348df61a1e4493d5d359e4fbf8c04d0407","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"unresolved-record-gaps.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:25:34Z","evidence_id":"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z","sha256":"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5","size_bytes":2189,"source_description":"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.","source_url":"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms","storage_name":"55/5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z","evidence_id":"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"secondary-reporting.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068","size_bytes":4343,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"79/795651076696c1eb40b9a297f276f69caf5d48ded88abfcc599171982c839068","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"secondary-reporting.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z","evidence_id":"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"official-source-record.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0","size_bytes":1851,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"a7/a72d9da121a5ff7ddc33803cbe97b7ac1bfea33ed69701f2acbd66f1eb9328f0","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"official-source-record.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z","evidence_id":"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"market-page.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5","size_bytes":2778,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"d1/d15f364ccbef7d6705e59341f227ab2f64f2b5785d95ebf750d28a89700930e5","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"market-page.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:25:11Z","evidence_id":"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z","sha256":"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab","size_bytes":3638,"source_description":"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.","source_url":"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026","storage_name":"f0/f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T07:17:18Z","evidence_id":"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"primary-evidence.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94","size_bytes":1589,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"f8/f8cab9c3c6841a7bd7e666de250d9e5b7dc9c681d353543d2912fb3545d61e94","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"primary-evidence.txt"}],"exhibits":[{"evidence_id":"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page","label":"PX-1 Market page packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Market page record\n\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\n\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\n\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRule text:\n\n> This market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n>\n> Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n>\n> The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\n\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\n\nEvent:\n\n- event id: 400878\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: true\n- event closed: true\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\n\nMarket:\n\n- market id: 2037907\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\n- market closed: true\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"1\", \"0\"]\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record","label":"PX-2 Official source packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Official source record\n\n## Polymarket source\n\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\n\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\n\n## Clavicular or representative statements\n\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\n\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\n\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\n\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\n\n## UMA / oracle source\n\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting","label":"PX-3 Secondary reporting packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Secondary reporting\n\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\n\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\n\n## Times of India fact check\n\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\n\n## Hindustan Times\n\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\n\n## The Express Tribune\n\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\n\n## Search notes\n\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad","label":"PX-4 Official Polymarket/Gamma merits capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nSources:\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\n\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDisplayed probability: >99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\n\nRules text shown on page:\nThis market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\nMarket context text shown on page:\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \"dating show\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\n\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\n\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\n\n## Gamma API fields observed\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\nEvent id: 400878.\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDescription: same rules text as above.\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\nEvent active: true.\nEvent closed: true.\nEvent archived: false.\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\nMarket id: 2037907.\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nOutcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"].\nOutcome prices: [\"1\", \"0\"].\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase."},{"evidence_id":"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e","label":"PX-5 Times of India adverse fact-check capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\n\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\n\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\"\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says: \"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\"\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \"pregnancy contest\" and quotes: \"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\"\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition."},{"evidence_id":"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps","label":"PX-6 Record gaps packet file","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Unresolved record gaps\n\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_d15f364ccbef_market-page","label":"DX-1 Market rule and initial final-outcome packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Market page record\n\nOfficial market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nCaptured page file: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured market image: source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\n\n## Official Polymarket page text captured by web fetch on 2026-05-14\n\nQuestion/title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRule text:\n\n> This market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n>\n> Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n>\n> The resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nThe rendered page capture also showed:\n\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\n## Gamma API fields captured on 2026-05-14\n\nEvent:\n\n- event id: 400878\n- ticker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- title: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n- event creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z\n- event startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z\n- event endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: true\n- event closed: true\n- event closedTime: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\n- event automaticallyResolved: true\n- event volume at capture: 13,934,862.960998023\n- event openInterest at capture: 5,749,723.168803\n\nMarket:\n\n- market id: 2037907\n- conditionId: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19\n- questionID: 0x24b6bade3cce1deaee8a6381420b7fb88b0f409b447747471b0245061d986280\n- market createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z\n- market startDate: 2026-04-20T22:41:29.998973Z\n- market closed: true\n- market closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00\n- umaEndDate: 2026-05-01T00:33:40Z\n- umaResolutionStatus: resolved\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"1\", \"0\"]\n- lastTradePrice at capture: 0.999\n- bestBid/bestAsk at capture: 0.998 / 0.999\n- resolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The key contested terms are “announces,” “he and a partner,” “expecting a baby through pregnancy,” and “credible.” The rule excludes non-credible announcements, including jokes, and allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, with credible-media consensus as a possible secondary source.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_a72d9da121a5_official-source-record","label":"DX-2 Official-source packet record showing missing primary statement and UMA detail","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Official source record\n\n## Polymarket source\n\n- Market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Gamma API URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Raw captures: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt and source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\n\nThe Polymarket rule says the resolution source is “statements from Clavicular or his representatives,” with a definitive consensus of credible media reporting allowed as a possible source.\n\n## Clavicular or representative statements\n\nNo primary statement from Clavicular or a representative has been preserved in this packet as a local source capture.\n\nThe secondary reporting located during packet preparation describes two different categories of statement:\n\n1. Reported livestream remarks about wanting children or proposing a “pregnancy contest,” including “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.” Those remarks may show intent or shock-content performance, but they do not by themselves identify an existing partner pregnancy.\n2. Viral claims that he had gotten a girlfriend pregnant after meeting her recently. The located fact-check reporting says those claims lacked proof and were not confirmed by Clavicular.\n\nBecause this is an open-record run, attorneys may search for the original stream, clips, X posts, Kick/VOD material, representative statements, and any later clarification. A later closed-record packet should preserve the primary video or statement relied on by either side.\n\n## UMA / oracle source\n\nThe packet preserves the Polymarket page and Gamma API fields showing two proposed/disputed sequences and final/resolved Yes state. It does not preserve UMA DVM transaction-level voting records or proposer/disputer records.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_f8cab9c3c684_primary-evidence","label":"DX-3 Primary-evidence packet assessment of missing underlying proof","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Primary evidence\n\n## Preserved primary/platform evidence\n\n- Polymarket market page: https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Polymarket Gamma API event record: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- Captured files: source-captures/polymarket-page.txt; source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json; source-captures/polymarket-market-image.jpg\n\nThe official market rule requires a credible announcement by Clavicular that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy during the specified window.\n\n## Potential primary-source leads not locally preserved\n\n- Clavicular's Kick page or VODs: https://kick.com/clavicular/videos, referenced by Hindustan Times.\n- Domahhhh's April 30 X thread about the oracle dispute: https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218, referenced by Forbes.\n- JexTrade's April 29 X post about a large No buy, referenced by Forbes.\n- @holy_moses7 posts claiming the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” referenced by Forbes.\n- The viral Kick Champ post that Times of India says claimed Clavicular was “expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days ago.” The exact source URL was not captured.\n\n## Preliminary source assessment\n\nThe preserved primary evidence proves the contract wording and the platform's final Yes state. It does not itself prove that a qualifying credible announcement occurred. The fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting","label":"DX-4 Secondary-reporting conflict and adverse context","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Secondary reporting\n\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\n\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\n\n## Times of India fact check\n\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\n\n## Hindustan Times\n\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\n\n## The Express Tribune\n\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\n\n## Search notes\n\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps","label":"DX-5 Unresolved record gaps","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Unresolved record gaps\n\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad","label":"DX-6 Plaintiff Polymarket/Gamma capture, including context about vows, stunt, and debunked rumors","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nSources:\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\n\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDisplayed probability: >99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\n\nRules text shown on page:\nThis market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\nMarket context text shown on page:\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \"dating show\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\n\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\n\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\n\n## Gamma API fields observed\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\nEvent id: 400878.\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDescription: same rules text as above.\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\nEvent active: true.\nEvent closed: true.\nEvent archived: false.\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\nMarket id: 2037907.\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nOutcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"].\nOutcome prices: [\"1\", \"0\"].\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase."},{"evidence_id":"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e","label":"DX-7 Plaintiff-submitted Times of India adverse fact-check","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\n\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\n\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\"\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says: \"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\"\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \"pregnancy contest\" and quotes: \"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\"\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition."},{"evidence_id":"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e","label":"DX-S1 TOI fact-check on no confirming video or Clavicular statement","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"# Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nMethod: web open of article; relevant text extracted from page lines 92-124.\n\nTitle: Fact check: Is Clavicular really expecting his first child after 10 days relationship amid viral pregnancy contest rumor?\nByline/date: Sehjal Gupta / TIMESOFINDIA.COM / Updated: Apr 29, 2026, 17:14 IST.\n\nRelevant captured text summary and excerpts:\n- The article states Clavicular, real name Braden Peters, became the subject of fast-spreading claims that he was expecting his first child and that people said he got a girl pregnant just 10 days after meeting her.\n- It says some believed the claim because Clavicular had recently said he wanted to become a father soon, but that \"there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.\"\n- It identifies the rumor as starting from a viral Kick Champ post that crossed 13 million views and claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says: \"No video confirms a pregnancy. No statement from Clavicular confirms it either.\"\n- It says the shared clip was taken out of context and did not show him reacting to baby news; instead he looked tired and unwell.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement about a \"pregnancy contest\" and quotes: \"I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.\"\n- It reports that internet users mixed that statement with unrelated clips and that the rumor grew on its own.\n- It concludes that there is no confirmed pregnancy, and that the viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and Clavicular's controversial content style.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is adverse secondary reporting, not primary video or a statement from Clavicular. It is useful for credibility analysis and missing-link assessment, not direct proof of the proposition."},{"evidence_id":"ev_795651076696_secondary-reporting","label":"DX-S2 Conflicting secondary reporting and contest/stunt framing","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"# Secondary reporting\n\n## Forbes: Polymarket's $16M Clavicular Bet Sparks Oracle Dispute\n\nURL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/digital-assets/2026/04/30/inmates-taking-the-asylum-polymarkets-16m-clavicular-bet/\nCaptured file: source-captures/forbes-clavicular-bet.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Forbes identified the disputed market as “Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?” and reported $16.46 million in lifetime volume, roughly $4.5 million in the prior 24 hours, Yes shares at 97 cents, and UMA dispute status as of April 30.\n- Forbes summarized the dispute: “The argument is over what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. The market’s own rules state that ‘pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.’”\n- Forbes reported that other traders, including @holy_moses7, said the market had been “confirmed to resolve as ‘No’ two days ago,” while Yes shares rose anyway.\n- Forbes wrote: “Across the orderbook, the disagreement is binary. The market description and the platform clarification say No. The price says Yes. The oracle, after two dispute rounds, has not closed the gap.”\n- Forbes linked the Domahhhh thread at https://x.com/domahhhh/status/2049886900513657218 and described it as alleging that Polymarket's oracle had become “a disinformation engine” run by “rogue traders.”\n\n## Times of India fact check\n\nURL: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms\nCaptured file: source-captures/timesofindia-fact-check.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article says the rumor claimed Clavicular was expecting his first child with a girlfriend he met 10 days earlier.\n- It says there was “no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, and no medical update.”\n- It reports that no video confirmed a pregnancy and no statement from Clavicular confirmed it.\n- It identifies a separate livestream statement: “I must have children. I must get children today. I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It concludes: “Right now, the truth is that there is no confirmed pregnancy. The viral claim is false and likely came from a mix of jokes, clips taken out of context, and his own controversial content style.”\n\n## Hindustan Times\n\nURL: https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/claviculars-bizarre-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-on-social-media-i-will-be-a-dad-101776968389298.html\nCaptured file: source-captures/hindustantimes-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- Hindustan Times reported a livestream suggestion for a contest involving 500 women, structured like a beauty-pageant type contest, with the winner becoming impregnated by him.\n- It quoted Peters as saying: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- The article treated the remarks as a controversial proposal or stunt, not as confirmation that a partner was already pregnant.\n\n## The Express Tribune\n\nURL: https://tribune.com.pk/story/2604737/claviculars-pregnancy-contest-claim-sparks-backlash-after-controversial-live-stream-comments\nCaptured file: source-captures/tribune-pregnancy-contest.txt\n\nRelevant excerpts from the readable capture:\n\n- The article reported that Braden Peters, known as Clavicular, proposed a “pregnancy contest” during a livestream.\n- It reported that he said he wanted children “within the next couple months” and quoted: “I must have children. I must get children today” and “I will be a dad in the next few months, guys. I am telling you.”\n- It said Clavicular had not provided further clarification on whether the proposed contest was genuine or satirical.\n\n## Search notes\n\nA narrow X API search during packet preparation did not locate the cited Domahhhh thread text or a primary Clavicular statement. It did locate public posts discussing a “500 girl modeling competition” and a claim that he had broken down after a girlfriend was pregnant. Those posts are weak evidence unless tied back to original clips or statements.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_045c38eca93e_unresolved-record-gaps","label":"DX-S3 Missing original statement, platform clarification, and UMA records","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"# Unresolved record gaps\n\n1. The packet does not contain the original Clavicular livestream clip, VOD, transcript, or representative statement that allegedly triggered the Yes proposal.\n2. The packet does not contain the Polymarket clarification Forbes refers to when it says the “platform clarification” said No.\n3. The packet does not contain UMA proposer, disputer, or voter records beyond Polymarket's API status fields.\n4. The exact meaning of “credible” is not defined beyond the rule's example excluding jokes.\n5. The Gamma API event endDate field is 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z, while the rule text says December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The arbitration proposition follows the rule text.\n6. Located secondary reporting conflicts in emphasis: Forbes describes a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant, while Times of India says no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy and no video confirmed it. The original source material is necessary for a closed-record conclusion.\n7. The market closed before the stated December 31, 2026 deadline. The packet records the final Yes state but does not evaluate whether early resolution was procedurally proper, because the arbitration proposition is the factual condition only.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad","label":"DX-S4 Official Polymarket/Gamma capture with market context","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"# Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\n\nRetrieval timestamp: 2026-06-30T07:25:00Z\nSources:\n- https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\n- https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nMethod: web open of rendered Polymarket page; python3 urllib request to Gamma API with Mozilla user-agent.\n\n## Rendered Polymarket page text observed\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDisplayed probability: >99% chance / 99.9% implied probability for Yes.\nDisplayed volume: $13,934,863.\nEnd date: Dec 31, 2026.\n\nRules text shown on page:\nThis market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy between market creation and December 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n\nOnly credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice. This market will resolve based on the date of announcement, regardless of when the child is born.\n\nThe resolution source will be statements from Clavicular or his representatives; however, a definitive consensus of credible media reporting may be considered.\n\nMarket opened: Apr 20, 2026, 6:39 PM ET.\nResolver shown: 0x65070BE91... (polygonscan link on rendered page).\nResolution sequence shown on rendered page:\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Outcome proposed: Yes\n- Disputed\n- Final outcome: Yes\n\nMarket context text shown on page:\nTrader consensus on Polymarket has locked in a 99.9% implied probability for Yes on Clavicular's pregnancy announcement in 2026, driven by Kick streamer Braden Peters' (aka Clavicular) repeated public vows to become a father by year-end, including his detailed fertility stack reveal and controversial pitch for a \"dating show\" to select a baby mama from 500 contestants.\n\nRecent viral backlash from his April livestream stunt--coupled with debunked rumors of an 18-year-old girlfriend's pregnancy after just 10 days, sparking emotional on-stream breakdowns--has amplified the narrative of imminent fatherhood. With $16 million in trading volume, the skin-in-the-game crowd sees his unfiltered influencer persona as a lock for some announcement before December 31.\n\nRealistic upsets remain slim but possible: a platform ban amid ongoing outrage, personal change of heart, or legal hurdles derailing his plans.\n\n## Gamma API fields observed\nAPI URL: https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026\nResponse length observed: 7273 bytes.\nEvent id: 400878.\nTicker/slug: clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026.\nTitle: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nDescription: same rules text as above.\nEvent creationDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569518Z.\nEvent startDate: 2026-04-20T22:47:28.569523Z.\nEvent endDate: 2026-12-31T00:00:00Z.\nEvent active: true.\nEvent closed: true.\nEvent archived: false.\nEvent volume: 13934862.960998023.\nEvent openInterest: 5749723.168803.\nEvent updatedAt: 2026-06-30T02:49:27.136133Z.\nMarket id: 2037907.\nCondition ID: 0x6747bae2269c348786d0c0c0f4286ac006f13f16325d4dcbab954b46de029f19.\nQuestion: Clavicular pregnancy in 2026?\nOutcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"].\nOutcome prices: [\"1\", \"0\"].\nMarket createdAt: 2026-04-20T22:28:48.129526Z.\nMarket updatedAt: 2026-05-02T00:40:21.634529Z.\nMarket closedTime: 2026-05-01 00:33:40+00.\nSubmitted_by: 0x91430CaD2d3975766499717fA0D66A78D814E5c5.\nResolvedBy: 0x65070BE91477460D8A7AeEb94ef92fe056C2f2A7.\n\nLimits and caveats: This is a text extraction and field summary, not a full binary archive of the page or full JSON. It preserves the decisive official fields observed during the merits phase."}],"openings":[{"phase":"openings","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, this case is about a narrow event definition, not about proving the private fact of a pregnancy to medical certainty. The proposition asks whether, after the April 20, 2026 market creation and before the stated deadline, Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy. Under the preponderance standard, the question is whether the better-supported reading of the available source chain is that a qualifying announcement occurred.\n\nThe present case packet already fixes the governing rule and the official market posture. The Polymarket page record states that the market resolves Yes if Clavicular announces that he and a partner are expecting a baby through pregnancy, that only credible announcements qualify, that jokes do not suffice, and that statements from Clavicular or his representatives are the primary resolution source while a definitive consensus of credible media may also be considered. The same official-source packet records the platform/API state: the market went through proposed/disputed sequences and ultimately shows a final Yes outcome.\n\nThat matters, but it is not the whole case. A final Yes state is strong circumstantial and procedural evidence that the market's resolver accepted the event as satisfied, but by itself it does not show the exact words, tone, context, or credibility of the underlying announcement. The plaintiff's burden is therefore to connect that official Yes state to the source material that caused it.\n\nThe packet points to that connection. Forbes reported the dispute as turning on what counts as a credible pregnancy announcement from a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. Other reports described livestream remarks about wanting children or becoming a dad soon, and several sources frame the incident as a viral controversy. Those reports explain why the market moved and why the oracle dispute arose. They support the plaintiff's theory that there was, at minimum, a public announcement or reported announcement that the market treated as sufficient.\n\nThe defense will stress the same record's weaknesses. The packet does not yet preserve the original livestream clip, VOD, full transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification mentioned by Forbes, or UMA transaction-level record. The Times of India fact-check says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular; other reporting characterizes the comments as a contest, stunt, joke, or out-of-context viral content. Those are real weight issues because the rule expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes.\n\nSo the decisive factual questions are these: first, what exactly did Clavicular say, and was it about an existing partner pregnancy rather than a future desire, stunt, or contest? Second, did the statement occur after market creation? Third, did Clavicular or a representative make it, or did credible media reach the definitive consensus allowed by the rules? Fourth, does the Polymarket/UMA Yes resolution rest on that source chain or on speculation and trader pressure?\n\nThe plaintiff expects the later evidentiary phase to focus on the primary artifacts the packet identifies: the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, the Polymarket clarification, the Forbes source capture, the Domahhhh thread, any Kick Champ source, and UMA oracle records. If those materials show that Clavicular publicly stated that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the final Yes outcome and corroborating credible reporting should satisfy preponderance. If the best source instead shows only jokes, wishful remarks, a contest proposal, or unsupported reposts, the plaintiff's case would be materially weaker.\n\nFor opening purposes, the plaintiff's theory is disciplined: the official market record and secondary reporting make Yes the more plausible starting point, but the case should be decided by the preserved source chain, not by market price alone."},{"phase":"openings","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the defense position starts with the market rule itself. This case is not resolved by asking whether a rumor circulated, whether Polymarket ultimately showed a Yes outcome, or whether traders believed a provocative streamer had created controversy. The proposition requires proof, by a preponderance, that Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the relevant window.\n\nThe admitted packet proves some important background. The market page record fixes the contract language: only credible announcements qualify; jokes do not; the ordinary resolution source is statements from Clavicular or his representatives, with a definitive consensus of credible media as a possible secondary source. The same packet also shows the market was created on April 20, 2026 and later displayed a final Yes state after proposed and disputed resolution sequences. The defense does not need to pretend those facts are irrelevant. They explain why this dispute exists.\n\nBut they do not prove the proposition. The preserved primary/platform evidence is the Polymarket page and Gamma/API status material. It proves the rule and the platform result; it does not preserve the original livestream, VOD, clip, transcript, representative statement, Polymarket clarification, or UMA voter/proposer record that would show why the market ended Yes. The packet's own primary-evidence assessment says the fact question remains dependent on locating and evaluating the underlying statement, clip, representative statement, or credible-media consensus.\n\nThat missing link matters because the secondary record is internally conflicted on the very element the plaintiff must prove. Forbes is favorable to plaintiff insofar as it describes a dispute over a streamer who allegedly told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. But the Times of India fact-check, also in the packet, says there was no proof, no confirmed girlfriend, no medical update, no confirming video, and no confirming statement from Clavicular. Other packet excerpts describe remarks about wanting children, being a dad in the next few months, or a proposed pregnancy contest. Those are not the same thing as announcing that he and a partner are already expecting a baby through pregnancy.\n\nThe defense theory is therefore straightforward: final Yes resolution is circumstantial evidence of market administration, not a substitute for the qualifying announcement required by the rule. A viral claim repeated through social media, a contest proposal, a future-oriented wish to have children, shock-content banter, or an out-of-context clip does not satisfy a rule that expressly excludes noncredible announcements and jokes. If plaintiff can later preserve the original source and it shows an unambiguous, credible statement by Clavicular or his representative that he and a partner were expecting a baby, the defense will have to confront it. On the current record, that source is absent.\n\nThe decisive evidence in later phases should be narrow: the full original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript; any statement from Clavicular, a representative, or a publicist; the Polymarket clarification referenced in reporting; UMA transaction-level records showing the basis for the final outcome; and the source chain behind the Forbes characterization and the Domahhhh/Kick Champ leads. Those materials would let the council distinguish a real qualifying announcement from a rumor cycle.\n\nUntil that bridge is built, the plaintiff's strongest proof is that the market resolved Yes and some reporters described the controversy. The defense will show that the rule asks for more: a credible announcement, from the right source or a definitive credible-media consensus, about an existing partner pregnancy. The present packet identifies exactly why that has not yet been proven."}],"prior_council_votes":[{"member_id":"C1","rationale":"The record contains conflicting secondary reports and lacks any primary statement or definitive media consensus confirming a credible announcement; thus the proposition is not more likely than not proven.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C2","rationale":"The admitted record contains conflicting secondary reports and no preserved primary statement from Clavicular announcing an existing partner pregnancy. The preserved quotes describe future-oriented contest/stunt language, and Times of India explicitly states no statement from Clavicular confirmed a pregnancy. The final Yes resolution does not establish what evidence the resolver relied upon, and there is no definitive consensus of credible media as the rule requires.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C3","rationale":"The admitted record contains no primary statement confirming a pregnancy announcement and presents conflicting secondary reports, so the proposition is not proven by preponderance.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"}],"rebuttals":[{"phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the defense correctly identifies the record's weakest point: no original VOD, clip, or transcript is preserved. But the defense then treats that gap as dispositive. The market rule does not. It allows statements from Clavicular or representatives, and it also allows a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. That structure matters: the drafters anticipated that the council or resolver might have to decide from credible reporting, not only from a raw stream file.\n\nThe defense also understates the official final Yes. Plaintiff is not asking the council to treat market price as fact. PX-4 and the packet market record show more than price: a proposed Yes, dispute, proposed Yes, dispute, and final Yes, with outcomePrices [1,0] and a resolved official state. That is the platform's resolution mechanism applying the same credibility rule after adversarial challenge. It is circumstantial, but it is unusually probative circumstantial evidence.\n\nThe defense says the Polymarket context describes future vows, a fertility-stack reveal, a dating-show/baby-mama proposal, and debunked girlfriend rumors. Yes, and plaintiff admitted that because unsupported viral reposts should be discounted. But that context does not erase the separate Forbes packet account: Forbes described the dispute as involving a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant. That is not merely \"I want children someday\" language. It is the record's strongest description of an announcement that maps onto the rule.\n\nThe Times of India capture is adverse, but its force is narrower than the defense claims. It debunks the specific viral claim that Clavicular was expecting a first child with a girlfriend he met ten days earlier, and it discusses an out-of-context clip and a pregnancy-contest quote. It does not establish what the UMA resolver considered. It does not preserve the Polymarket clarification. It does not refute Forbes's specific characterization that the dispute concerned a statement that he had gotten a girl pregnant. And, like Forbes, it is secondary reporting rather than primary video.\n\nSo the evidentiary choice is not \"primary video versus nothing.\" It is whether the official final Yes, reached after two disputes under a rule that permits credible-media consensus, plus Forbes's affirmative characterization, outweighs adverse secondary reporting about a narrower viral rumor and the acknowledged absence of the raw source. On preponderance, plaintiff submits that it does.\n\nThe defense asks the council to infer that the official resolver accepted only a joke, stunt, or debunked rumor. That is possible, but it is not the better-supported inference on this record. The better-supported inference is that the official process credited a qualifying announcement or media-consensus path, even though the underlying primary artifact was not preserved in this packet. The gaps should reduce certainty; they should not convert a final official Yes and a favorable credible-media account into a No finding."}],"submitted_evidence":[{"evidence_id":"ev_f0160b3ff4ad_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f0160b3ff4ad","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Official source for the market rule, market timing, final Yes outcome, Polymarket context text, API outcome prices, and dispute/final-resolution status.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"f0160b3ff4adda3a809b62a6da02552d3665af82537802e9d2f79b28bfddadab","size_bytes":3638,"source_description":"Official Polymarket rendered page text opened with web tool and Gamma API fetched with python3 urllib during plaintiff merits phase.","source_url":"https://polymarket.com/event/clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026 ; https://gamma-api.polymarket.com/events?slug=clavicular-pregnancy-in-2026","title":"Official Polymarket/Gamma capture for Clavicular pregnancy market"},{"evidence_id":"ev_5570c630032e_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-5570c630032e","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Adverse secondary reporting on whether there was a confirmed pregnancy announcement, useful to evaluate credibility, source-chain gaps, and whether viral material was out of context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T07:25:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"5570c630032efbfd49996258af818149b11e4a7b94db835fa0670c91812274f5","size_bytes":2189,"source_description":"Times of India article opened with web tool; text lines 92-124 captured as adverse/fact-checking secondary source.","source_url":"https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/fact-check-is-clavicular-really-expecting-his-first-child-after-10-days-relationship-amid-viral-pregnancy-contest-rumor/articleshow/130539375.cms","title":"Times of India fact-check capture on Clavicular pregnancy rumor"}],"surrebuttals":[{"phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the issue. The defense is not arguing that a raw VOD is the only legally possible proof. The rule permits a definitive consensus of credible media reporting. But that is the point: the record does not contain such a consensus.\n\nWhat the record contains is one favorable Forbes characterization, adverse Times of India reporting that no video or Clavicular statement confirmed pregnancy, Hindustan Times and Express Tribune descriptions of a pregnancy-contest stunt, and an admitted gaps file saying the original stream, transcript, platform clarification, and UMA records are missing. That is not a definitive media consensus. It is a conflicted source chain.\n\nPlaintiff says TOI only debunks the narrower ten-day girlfriend rumor. But the proposition is itself about a partner pregnancy, and TOI’s captured text goes beyond narrow timing: no video confirms a pregnancy; no statement from Clavicular confirms it; the shared clip was out of context; the preserved quote was about wanting children and a pregnancy contest; the viral claim likely came from jokes and out-of-context clips. Those points directly undercut credibility and qualification under a rule that excludes jokes and noncredible announcements.\n\nPlaintiff also asks the council to treat final Yes after disputes as unusually probative. It is probative that the market resolved Yes. It is not probative enough to fill the missing basis for that resolution. The record does not show what the resolver considered, whether it relied on Forbes, the viral Kick Champ rumor, trader pressure, or something else, and it lacks the platform clarification Forbes reportedly said pointed No. Without the source chain, final Yes risks becoming circular proof: the announcement happened because the market resolved Yes, and the market resolved Yes because the announcement happened.\n\nThe preponderance question is not whether plaintiff’s theory is possible. It is whether the qualifying announcement is more likely than not on the admitted record. Given the conflicting media accounts, the absence of the underlying statement, and the admitted context of future vows, stunt framing, and debunked rumors, plaintiff has not crossed that line."}],"technical_reports":[{"phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","summary":"Before filing, plaintiff rescanned the record and evidence list. Target sources were official Polymarket/Gamma records, Forbes reporting, Times of India adverse reporting, the original Kick/VOD or clip, the Polymarket clarification, Domahhhh X thread, Kick Champ source, and UMA records. The Polymarket page was opened and the Gamma API was fetched with python3 urllib; the official rule, final Yes sequence, IDs, outcome prices, and context were preserved as PX-4. The Times of India article was opened and adverse fact-check text was preserved as PX-5. Forbes direct page capture was attempted by web open/search, but no stronger article text than the existing packet capture was obtained in time, so plaintiff relied on PX-3 rather than submitting a search snippet. No original VOD/transcript or full UMA voter record was captured this phase; those remain material gaps affecting weight.","title":"Plaintiff source-search and capture ledger"},{"phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","summary":"Defense rescanned the current record and evidence list, then read the two new plaintiff submissions in full. Source targets considered were the original Kick/VOD or clip and transcript, Clavicular/representative statements, the Polymarket clarification referenced by Forbes, UMA proposer/disputer/voter records, Forbes source chain, Domahhhh X thread, and Kick Champ source. Opening-phase searches found Forbes, Polymarket, Times of India, Hindustan Times, X Domahhhh, Inkl, Poprant/Indiatimes, Binance, and Lines leads; X thread opening produced no readable text, and no original video/transcript or representative statement was captured. No new defense evidence was submitted because the material defense sources are already admitted through the packet and plaintiff's TOI capture, while uncaptured leads remain unverified. Unresolved gaps remain the original statement, full context, platform clarification, and UMA rationale.","title":"Defense Source-Chain And Gap Ledger"}]}}},"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T07:50:07.017222578Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C4","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":885915,"role_id":"council","turn_number":12}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"get_case"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782804921105}]}
